{"title_page": "Henry Yorke Stanger", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n[[File:Henry Yorke Stanger MP.jpg|thumb|right|Henry Yorke Stanger]]\n'''His Hon. Henry Yorke Stanger''' (11 November 1849 \u2013 19 April 1929), was a British [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] politician and judge.\n\nHe was born in [[Nottingham]], the third son of [[George Eaton Stanger]] and Mary Hurst. He was educated at [[Lincoln College, Oxford]] (Scholar); Tancred Law Student; 2nd class Classical Moderations; 1st class Greats. He married in 1880, Henrietta Sophia Wastie Green. They had one son and two daughters.<ref>Who's Who</ref>\n\n==Legal career==\nHe was called to the Bar in 1874. He was a [[Electoral registration in the United Kingdom#Registration process from 1832|Revising Barrister]] for [[Warwickshire]] in 1892\u201393\u20131894. He became a [[Queen's Counsel|Queens Council]] in 1895. He became a Bencher of [[Lincoln\u2019s Inn]] in 1898. He was formerly a Member of the Midland Circuit. He served as Recorder of Nottingham from 1909\u201311. He was a County Court Judge, for Circuit 7 from 1910\u201314 and a County Court Judge for the Bristol Circuit (No. 54) from 1914\u201322. He retired in 1922. He also served as a Justice of the Peace in [[Gloucestershire]].<ref>Who's Who</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nHe was a member of the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]]. He first stood for parliament in a [[1900 Newark by-election|by-election in 1900]] at the safe Conservative seat of [[Newark (UK Parliament constituency)|Newark]], when he was well beaten by the Conservative.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Election intelligence|day_of_week=Monday |date=19 February 1900 |page_number=13 |issue=36069 }}</ref> A few months later at the 1900 General Election he switched seats to contest the more marginal Conservative seat of [[Nottingham South (UK Parliament constituency)|Nottingham South]], but again finished second. He was finally elected Liberal MP down in London for [[Kensington North (UK Parliament constituency)|Kensington North]] at the 1906 General election, gaining the seat for the Liberals from the Conservatives. \n[[File:KensingtonNorth1885.png|right|thumb|190px|Kensington North]]\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906 General Election]]: Kensington, North<ref>British parliamentary election results 1885-1918, Craig, F. W. S.</ref>\nElectorate }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = '''Henry Yorke Stanger'''\n  |votes      = 4,416\n  |percentage = 56.8\n  |change     = 13.1\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[William Ellis Hume-Williams]]\n  |votes      = 3,358\n  |percentage = 43.2\n  |change     = -13.1\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      = 1,058\n  |percentage = 13.6\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n |votes = 10,270\n |percentage = 75.7\n |change = \n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n |winner = Liberal Party (UK)\n |loser = Conservative Party (UK)\n |swing = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nHe was a strong supporter of Votes for Women and in 1908 he introduced a [[Private member's bill]] in favour of [[Women's Suffrage]]. The bill made good progress before finally being blocked.<ref>From Liberal to Labour with Women's Suffrage: The Story Of Catherine Marshall by Jo Vellacott</ref> \nHe stood down after one term in January 1910.<ref>British parliamentary election results 1885-1918, Craig, F. W. S.</ref> He was an Independent Chairman of the Nottinghamshire Joint Committee under the [[Coal Mines (Minimum Wage) Act 1912]].\n\n==Sources==\n*Who Was Who; http://www.ukwhoswho.com\n*British parliamentary election results 1885\u20131918, Craig, F. W. S.\n\n==Further reading==\n*The Descendants of Nathan Hurst, circa 1740; http://airgale.com.au/hurst-n/d4.htm\n*Nap-kin; http://www.nap-kin.net/getperson.php?personID=I5088&tree=napkin\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[William Edward Thompson Sharpe]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Kensington North (UK Parliament constituency)|Kensington North]]\n | years = [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]] \u2013 [[January 1910 United Kingdom general election|January 1910]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Alan Hughes Burgoyne]] }}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stanger, Henry Yorke}}\n[[Category:1849 births]]\n[[Category:1929 deaths]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1906\u20131910]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Lincoln College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Nottingham]]\n[[Category:Members of Lincoln's Inn]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n[[File:Henry Yorke Stanger MP.jpg|thumb|right|Henry Yorke Stanger]]\n'''His Hon. Henry Yorke Stanger''' (11 November 1849 \u2013 19 April 1929), was a British [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] politician and judge.\n\nHe was born in [[Nottingham]], the third son of [[George Eaton Stanger]] and Mary Hurst. He was educated at [[Lincoln College, Oxford]] (Scholar); Tancred Law Student; 2nd class Classical Moderations; 1st class Greats. He married in 1880, Henrietta Sophia Wastie Green. They had one son and two daughters.<ref>Who's Who</ref>\n\n==Legal career==\nHe was called to the Bar in 1874. He was a [[Electoral registration in the United Kingdom#Registration process from 1832|Revising Barrister]] for [[Warwickshire]] in 1892\u201393\u20131894. He became a [[Queen's Counsel|Queens Council]] in 1895. He became a Bencher of [[Lincoln\u2019s Inn]] in 1898. He was formerly a Member of the Midland Circuit. He served as Recorder of Nottingham from 1909\u201311. He was a County Court Judge, for Circuit 7 from 1910\u201314 and a County Court Judge for the Bristol Circuit (No. 54) from 1914\u201322. He retired in 1922. He also served as a Justice of the Peace in [[Gloucestershire]].<ref>Who's Who</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nHe was a member of the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]]. He first stood for parliament in a [[1900 Newark by-election|by-election in 1900]] at the safe Conservative seat of [[Newark (UK Parliament constituency)|Newark]], when he was well beaten by the Conservative.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Election intelligence|day_of_week=Monday |date=19 February 1900 |page_number=13 |issue=36069 }}</ref> A few months later at the 1900 General Election he switched seats to contest the more marginal Conservative seat of [[Nottingham South (UK Parliament constituency)|Nottingham South]], but again finished second. He was finally elected Liberal MP down in London for [[Kensington North (UK Parliament constituency)|Kensington North]] at the 1906 General election, gaining the seat for the Liberals from the Conservatives. \n[[File:KensingtonNorth1885.png|right|thumb|190px|Kensington North]]\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906 General Election]]: Kensington, North<ref>British parliamentary election results 1885-1918, Craig, F. W. S.</ref>\nElectorate }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = '''Henry Yorke Stanger'''\n  |votes      = 4,416\n  |percentage = 56.8\n  |change     = 13.1\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[William Ellis Hume-Williams]]\n  |votes      = 3,358\n  |percentage = 43.2\n  |change     = -13.1\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      = 1,058\n  |percentage = 13.6\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n |votes = 10,270\n |percentage = 75.7\n |change = \n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n |winner = Liberal Party (UK)\n |loser = Conservative Party (UK)\n |swing = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nHe was a strong supporter of Votes for Women and in 1908 he introduced a [[Private member's bill]] in favour of [[Women's Suffrage]]. The bill made good progress before finally being blocked.<ref>From Liberal to Labour with Women's Suffrage: The Story Of Catherine Marshall by Jo Vellacott</ref> \nHe stood down after one term in January 1910.<ref>British parliamentary election results 1885-1918, Craig, F. W. S.</ref> He was an Independent Chairman of the Nottinghamshire Joint Committee under the [[Coal Mines (Minimum Wage) Act 1912]].\n\n==Sources==\n*Who Was Who; http://www.ukwhoswho.com\n*British parliamentary election results 1885-1918, Craig, F. W. S.\n\n==Further reading==\n*The Descendants of Nathan Hurst, circa 1740; http://airgale.com.au/hurst-n/d4.htm\n*Nap-kin; http://www.nap-kin.net/getperson.php?personID=I5088&tree=napkin\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[William Edward Thompson Sharpe]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Kensington North (UK Parliament constituency)|Kensington North]]\n | years = [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]] \u2013 [[January 1910 United Kingdom general election|January 1910]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Alan Hughes Burgoyne]] }}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stanger, Henry Yorke}}\n[[Category:1849 births]]\n[[Category:1929 deaths]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1906\u20131910]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Lincoln College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Nottingham]]\n[[Category:Members of Lincoln's Inn]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSources:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1885-1918 \u2192 1885\u20131918", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Yorke_Stanger"}
{"title_page": "Philip Snowden, 1st Viscount Snowden", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Lord Snowdon (disambiguation){{!}}Lord Snowdon}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name                = The Viscount Snowden\n| honorific-suffix    = [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]]\n| image               = Lord Snowden.jpg\n| birth_date          = 18 July 1864\n| birth_place         = [[Cowling, Craven|Cowling]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], [[England]]\n| death_place         = [[Tilford]], [[Surrey]], England\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|1937|05|15|1864|07|18|df=y}}\n| office              = [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]]\n| term_start          = 7 June 1929\n| term_end            = 5 November 1931\n| primeminister       = [[Ramsay MacDonald]]\n| predecessor         = [[Winston Churchill]]\n| successor           = [[Neville Chamberlain]]\n| term_start1         = 22 January 1924\n| term_end1           = 3 November 1924\n| primeminister1      = [[Ramsay MacDonald]]\n| predecessor1        = [[Neville Chamberlain]]\n| successor1          = [[Winston Churchill]]\n| party               = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] ({{circa|1894\u20131931}})<br>[[National Labour Organisation|National Labour]] (1931\u20131932)<br>None (1932\u20131937)\n| spouse              = {{marriage|[[Ethel Snowden|Ethel Annakin]]|1905}}\n| office2             = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Colne Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Colne Valley]]\n| term_start2         = 15 November 1922\n| term_end2           = 27 October 1931\n| predecessor2        = [[Frederick Mallalieu]]\n| successor2          = [[Lance Mallalieu]]\n}}\n\n'''Philip Snowden, 1st Viscount Snowden''', [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]] ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|n|o\u028a|d|\u0259n}}; 18 July 1864 \u2013 15 May 1937) was a British [[politician]]. A strong speaker, he became popular in trade union circles for his denunciation of capitalism as unethical and his promise of a socialist utopia.  He was the first [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], a position he held in 1924 and again between 1929 and 1931. He broke with Labour policy in 1931, and was expelled from the party and excoriated as a [[turncoat]], as the Party was overwhelmingly crushed that year by the [[National Government (1931)|National Government]] coalition that Snowden supported. He was succeeded as Chancellor by [[Neville Chamberlain]].\n\n==Early life: 1864\u20131906==\nSnowden was born in [[Cowling, Craven|Cowling]] in the [[West Riding of Yorkshire]]. His father John Snowden had been a weaver and a supporter of [[Chartism]], and later a [[Gladstonian liberalism|Gladstonian liberal]]. Snowden later wrote in his autobiography: \"I was brought up in this [[Radicalism (historical)#United Kingdom|Radical]] atmosphere, and it was then that I imbibed the political and social principles which I have held fundamentally ever since\".<ref>Philip, Viscount Snowden, ''An Autobiography. Volume One. 1864-1919'' (London: Ivor Nicholson and Watson, 1934), p. 19.</ref> Although his parents and sisters were involved in weaving at the Ickornshaw Mill, he did not join them; after attending a local board school (where he received additional lessons in French and Latin from the schoolmaster) he stayed on as a pupil-teacher.<ref name=\"obit\" /> When he was 15 he became an insurance office clerk in Burnley.<ref name=\"obit\" /> During his seven years as a clerk, he studied and then passed the civil service entry examination; in 1886, he was appointed to a junior position at the [[HM Excise|Excise Office]] in Liverpool.<ref name=\"obit\" /> Snowden moved on to other posts around Scotland and then to [[Devon]].<ref name=\"obit\" />\n\nIn August 1891, when he was aged 27, Snowden severely injured his back in a cycling accident in Devon and was paralyzed from the waist down.<ref name=\"obit\">\"Lord Snowden.\" Times [London, England] 17 May 1937: 15. The Times Digital Archive. Web. 8 September 2013.</ref> He learned to walk again with the aid of sticks within two years.<ref name=\"ODNB\">Duncan Tanner, \"Snowden, Philip, Viscount Snowden (1864\u20131937)]\", ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', 2004;</ref> His [[Inland Revenue]] job was kept open for him for two years following the accident; however, owing to his condition, he decided to resign from the civil service.<ref name=\"obit\" /> While he was convalescing at his mother's house at Cowling he began to study [[Socialism|socialist]] theory and history.<ref name=\"obit\" />\n\nSnowden joined the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]], and followed his parents in becoming a [[Methodist]] and a teetotaller. In 1893, in the aftermath of the formation of the [[Independent Labour Party]] (ILP) in neighboring [[Bradford]], he was asked to give a speech for the Cowling Liberal Club on the dangers of socialism. Whilst researching the subject, Snowden instead became convinced by the ideology. He eventually joined the executive committee of the [[Keighley]] ILP in 1899, and went on to chair the ILP from 1903 to 1906. He became a prominent speaker for the party, and wrote a popular [[Christian socialism|Christian socialist]] pamphlet with [[Keir Hardie]] in 1903, entitled ''The Christ that is to Be''. His strident rhetoric, well-laced with statistics and [[Evangelicalism|evangelical]] themes, contrasted the evil conditions under capitalism with the moral and economic utopia of future socialism. He condemned as \"bloodsuckers and parasites\" local textile company executives. In 1898, he launched the ''Keighley Labour Journal'', using it to denounce waste, pettiness, and corruption. However, he ignored the concerns of the trade unions, which he judged to be conservative and fixated on wages.<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> By 1902, he had moved his base to [[Leeds]] and toured Britain as a lecturer on politics and corruption, with his own syndicated column and short essays in numerous working class outlets. By the time he was elected [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for [[Blackburn (UK Parliament constituency)|Blackburn]] in 1906, he had become a well-known socialist figure, standing at the national level alongside both Keir Hardie, [[Arnold Lupton|Professor Arnold Lupton]] and [[Ramsay MacDonald]].<ref name=\"ODNB\" /><ref>Millman, Brock, ''Domestic Dissent in First World War Britain'', 2000, page 186.</ref>\n\nSnowden married [[Ethel Snowden|Ethel Annakin]], a campaigner for [[women's suffrage]], in 1905. He supported his wife's ideals, and he became a noted speaker at suffragette meetings and other public meetings.<ref name=\"ODNB\" />\n\n==Member of Parliament: 1906\u20131924==\n[[File:Labour Representation Committee leaders 1906.jpg|thumb|Snowden (fourth from left) in 1906, with other leading figures in the party]]\nSnowden unsuccessfully contested the [[Wakefield (UK Parliament constituency)|Wakefield]] constituency in West Yorkshire in a by-election in March 1902, where he received 40 percent of the votes.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Election intelligence |day_of_week=Wednesday |date=26 March 1902 |page_number=10 |issue=36725| }}</ref>\nIn [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]], he became the Labour MP for Blackburn.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=27885 |date=13 February 1906 |page=1038 }}</ref> He continued his writing and lectures, and now was advocating more radical measures than the ruling Liberals were implementing. He even devised his own \"Socialist budget\" to rival [[David Lloyd George]]'s 1909 \"[[People's Budget]]\".<ref name=\"ODNB\" />\n\nSnowden was in Australia on a worldwide lecture tour when the [[World War I|First World War]] broke out in August 1914; he did not return to Britain until February 1915. He was not a pacifist; however, he did not support recruiting for the armed forces, and he campaigned against conscription. His stance was unpopular with the public and he lost his seat in the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918 general election]]. In 1922, he was elected to represent [[Colne Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Colne Valley]].<ref name=\"ODNB\" />\n\n==Chancellor of the Exchequer: 1924==\nUpon Ramsay MacDonald's appointment as Prime Minister in January 1924, Snowden was appointed as the Labour Party's first ever [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]]<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=32901 |date=25 January 1924 |page=770 }}</ref> and sworn of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=32901 |date=25 January 1924 |page=769 }}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=13992 |date=29 January 1924 |page=147 |city=e }}</ref>\n\nIn his budget, Snowden lowered the duties on tea, coffee, cocoa, chicory and sugar; reduced spending on armaments; and provided money for council housing. However, he did not implement the [[capital levy]]. Snowden claimed that because of the lowering of duties on foodstuffs consumed by the working class, the budget went \"far to realize the cherished radical idea of a [[free breakfast table]]\".<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,718325-1,00.html ''Time'', Labor's Budget, 12 May 1924]</ref> He profoundly believed in the morality of the balanced budget, with rigorous economy and not a penny wasted. He grasped how serious unemployment was becoming, but differed with the rising belief in [[deficit spending]] as a way to combat it. [[A. J. P. Taylor]] said his budget \"would have delighted the heart of Gladstone\".<ref>Taylor, ''English History, 1914-1945'', p. 212.</ref>\n\nIn his first budget, Snowden earmarked \u00a338 million for the reduction of food taxes, the introduction of pensions for widows, and a reduction in the pensionable age to 65. However, only the first of these measures was realized during the first Labour Government's time in office.<ref>''Foundations of the Welfare State'', 2nd Edition by [[Pat Thane]], published 1996</ref>\n\n==Opposition: 1924\u20131929==\nAlthough he had chaired the ILP for a second time, from 1917 to 1920, Snowden resigned from the party in 1927 because he believed it was \"drifting more and more away from...evolutionary socialism into revolutionary socialism\". He was also opposed to the new [[Keynesian]] economic ideas which provided a rationale for deficit spending, and criticized their expression in the Liberals' manifesto for the [[1929 United Kingdom general election|1929 election]], titled ''We can Conquer Unemployment''.<ref name=\"ODNB\" />\n\n==Chancellor of the Exchequer: 1929\u20131931==\nSnowden was again appointed Chancellor after Labour formed a government in 1929, after emerging as the largest party in the general election.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=33508 |date=21 June 1929 |page=4106 }}</ref> His economic philosophy was one of strict Gladstonian Liberalism rather than socialism. His official biographer wrote, \"He was raised in an atmosphere which regarded borrowing as an evil and [[free trade]] as an essential ingredient of prosperity\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Keith Laybourn|title=Philip Snowden: a biography : 1864-1937|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UakgAAAAMAAJ|year=1988|publisher=Temple Smith|page=97}}</ref>\n\nHe was considered by many at the time and later as being the principal opponent to the government following any radical economic policy to tackle the [[Great Depression in the United Kingdom|Great Depression]] as well as blocking proposals to introduce [[Protectionism|protectionist]] tariffs. The government eventually collapsed over arguments about a budget deficit amidst refusals by a significant minority of ministers to enact cuts in unemployment benefit.<ref>Robert Skidelsky, ''Politicians and the Slump: The Labour Government of 1929-1931'' (1967)</ref>\n\nSnowden retained the position of Chancellor during the [[National Government (1931)|National Government]] of 1931. As a consequence he was expelled from the party, along with MacDonald and [[J. H. Thomas|Jimmy Thomas]]. In a BBC radio broadcast on 16 October 1931, he called Labour's policies \"Bolshevism run mad\" and contrasted them unfavorably with his own \"sane and evolutionary Socialism\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Kevin Jeffreys|title=Leading Labour: From Keir Hardie to Tony Blair|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZCuC-mrnjZsC&pg=PA33|year=1999|publisher=I.B.Tauris|page=33}}</ref> Snowden decided not to stand for parliament in the [[1931 United Kingdom general election|election of November 1931]]. At that election, Labour's number of seats declined catastrophically from 288 to 52. It was during that year he had [[prostate gland]] surgery, following which his health and mobility declined.<ref name=\"ODNB\" />\n\nSkidelsky is representative of the Keynesians who have charged that Snowden and MacDonald were blinded by their economic philosophy that required balanced budgets, sound money, the gold standard and free trade, regardless of the damage that Keynesians thought it would do to the economy and the people.<ref>Skidelsky, ''Politicians and the Slump: The Labour Government of 1929-1931'' (1967)</ref> However, with the decline of Keynesianism as a model after 1968, historians have reevaluated Snowden in a more favorable light. McKibbin argues that the Labour government had very limited room to manoeuvre in 1929\u201331, and it did as well as could be expected; and that it handled the British economy better than most foreign governments handled theirs, and the [[Great Depression]] was less severe in Britain than elsewhere.<ref>Ross McKibbin, \"The Economic Policy of the Second Labour Government 1929-1931,\" ''Past & Present'' (1975) #68 pp. 95-123 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/650274 in JSTOR]</ref>\n\n==Later life: 1931\u20131937==\n[[File:Vera & Chaim Weizmann, Herbert Samuel, Lloyd George, Ethel Snowden, Philip Snowden.jpeg|thumb|210px|[[Vera Weizmann]], [[Chaim Weizmann]], [[Herbert Samuel]], [[Lloyd George]], [[Ethel Snowden]], and Philip Snowden]]\nIn the [[1931 Dissolution Honours]] he was raised to the peerage as '''Viscount Snowden''' of Ickornshaw, in the West Riding of the County of York,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=33775 |date=27 November 1931 |page=7658 }}</ref> and served as [[Lord Privy Seal]] in the National government from 1931<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=33772 |date=17 November 1931 |page=7409 }}</ref> to 1932, when he resigned in protest at the enactment of a full scheme of [[Imperial Preference]] and [[Protectionism|protectionist]] tariffs. That year, Snowden said there was never a greater mistake than to say that [[Cobdenism]] was dead: \"Cobdenism was never more alive throughout the world than it was to-day...To-day the ideas of Cobden were in revolt against selfish nationalism. The need for the breaking down of trade restrictions, which took various forms, was universally recognized even by those who were unable to throw off those shackles\".<ref>''The Times'' (8 July 1932), p. 9.</ref>\n\nHe subsequently wrote his ''Autobiography'' in which he strongly attacked MacDonald. In the [[1935 United Kingdom general election|1935 general election]], Snowden supported the Keynesian economic program  proposed by Lloyd George (\"Lloyd George's New Deal\"), despite it being a complete repudiation of Snowden's own classical liberal fiscal policies. Snowden claimed that he was returning to long-held economic views, but that these had been \"temporarily inadvisable\" during the crisis of 1931, when \"national necessity\" demanded cutting public expenditure.<ref name=\"ODNB\" />\n\nLord Snowden died of a [[heart attack]] at his home, Eden Lodge, [[Tilford]], [[Surrey]] on 15 May 1937, aged 72. After cremation at [[Woking Crematorium]] his ashes were scattered on [[Cowling Moor]] near Ickornshaw. His library of books and pamphlets was presented to Keighley [[public library|Public Library]] by his widow, and a cairn was erected to his memory on Ickornshaw Moor in 1938.<ref name=\"ODNB\" />\n\nHis viscountcy died with him. Lady Snowden died in February 1951, aged 69.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n*{{cite book | first=Colin |last=Cross |title=Philip Snowden |publisher=Barrie & Jenkins |date=1966  |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book |first= Keith |last= Laybourn |first2= David |last2= James |editors=Keith Laybourn & David James |title= Philip Snowden: The First Labour Chancellor of the Exchequer |publisher=Bradford Arts, Museums and Libraries Service |date= 1987 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book |first=Keith |last=Laybourn |title=Philip Snowden. A Biography, 1864\u20131937 |publisher=Dartmouth Publishing |date= 1988 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book |first=Philip, Viscount |last=Snowden |title=An Autobiography |volume=vol. One  1864-1919 |place=London |publisher= Ivor Nicholson and Watson |date= 1934 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book | first=Philip, Viscount |last=Snowden |title=An Autobiography |volume=vol. Two 1919-1934 |place=London |publisher=Ivor Nicholson and Watson |date= 1934 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite journal |first=Duncan |last=Tanner |authorlink=Duncan Tanner |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/36181 |title=Snowden, Philip, Viscount Snowden (1864\u20131937)| journal=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |publisher=Oxford University Press |date= 2004 | accessdate= 1 July 2011 |ref=harv }}\n\n;Secondary sources\n\n*{{cite journal |first=Ross |last=McKibbin |title=The Economic Policy of the Second Labour Government 1929-1931 |journal= Past & Present |date=1975 |volume= #68 |pages=pp.&nbsp;95\u2013123 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book |first=A. J. P. |last=Taylor |title= English History, 1914-1945 |url=https://archive.org/details/englishhistory1900tayl |url-access=registration |publisher=Oxford University Press |date= 1965 |ref= p.209 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisource author}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-philip-snowden | Philip Snowden }}\n* {{FadedPage|id=Snowden, Philip|name=Philip Snowden|author=yes}}\n* [http://www.blackburnlabour.org/history/philip-snowden Philip Snowden] - Blackburn Labour Party\n* {{Cite EB1922|wstitle=Snowden, Phillip |short=x}}\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/016703}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Blackburn (historic UK Parliament constituency)|Blackburn]]\n  | years  = [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]]\u2013[[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]]\n  | with   = [[Harry Hornby|Sir Harry Hornby]] 1906\u20131910\n  | with2  = [[Thomas Barclay (economic writer)|Sir Thomas Barclay]] 1910\n  | with3  = [[Sir Henry Norman, 1st Baronet|Sir Henry Norman]] 1910\u20131918\n  | before = [[Sir William Coddington, 1st Baronet|Sir William Coddington]]<br />[[Harry Hornby|Sir Harry Hornby]]\n  | after  = [[Percy Dean]]<br />[[Sir Henry Norman, 1st Baronet|Sir Henry Norman]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Colne Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Colne Valley]]\n  | years  = [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922]]\u2013[[1931 United Kingdom general election|1931]]\n  | before = [[Frederick Mallalieu]]\n  | after  = [[Lance Mallalieu]]\n}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = Chairman of the [[Independent Labour Party]]\n  | years  = 1903\u20131906\n  | before = [[Bruce Glasier]]\n  | after  = [[Ramsay MacDonald]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = Chairman of the [[Independent Labour Party]]\n  | years  = 1917\u20131920\n  | before = [[Fred Jowett]]\n  | after  = [[R.&nbsp;C. Wallhead]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = Treasurer of the [[Independent Labour Party]]\n  | years  = 1920\u20131922\n  | before = [[T.&nbsp;D. Benson]]\n  | after  = [[George Benson (politician)|George Benson]]\n}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] | before=[[Neville Chamberlain]] | after=[[Winston Churchill]] | years=1924}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] | before=[[Winston Churchill]] | after=[[Neville Chamberlain]] | years=1929\u20131931}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Lord Privy Seal]] | before=[[William Peel, 1st Earl Peel|The Earl Peel]] | after=[[Stanley Baldwin]] | years=1931\u20131932}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{s-new|creation}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Viscount Snowden]]|years=1931\u20131937}}\n{{s-non|reason=Extinct}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{British Chancellors of the Exchequer}}\n{{First Macdonald Ministry}}\n{{Independent Labour Party}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Snowden, Philip}}\n[[Category:Chancellors of the Exchequer of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Lords Privy Seal]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Independent Labour Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Independent Labour Party National Administrative Committee members]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1906\u20131910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1922\u20131923]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1923\u20131924]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1924\u20131929]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1929\u20131931]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Snowden, Philip Snowden, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:Viscounts in the Peerage of the United Kingdom|Snowden, Philip Snowden, 1st]]\n[[Category:English memoirists|Snowden, Philip Snowden, 1st]]\n[[Category:English Methodists|Snowden, Philip Snowden, 1st]]\n[[Category:1864 births|Snowden, Philip Snowden, 1st]]\n[[Category:1937 deaths|Snowden, Philip Snowden, 1st]]\n[[Category:Politics of Blackburn with Darwen]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) hereditary peers]]\n[[Category:English Christian socialists]]\n[[Category:Methodist socialists]]\n[[Category:English evangelicals]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Lord Snowdon (disambiguation){{!}}Lord Snowdon}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name                = The Viscount Snowden\n| honorific-suffix    = [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]]\n| image               = Lord Snowden.jpg\n| birth_date          = 18 July 1864\n| birth_place         = [[Cowling, Craven|Cowling]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], [[England]]\n| death_place         = [[Tilford]], [[Surrey]], England\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|1937|05|15|1864|07|18|df=y}}\n| office              = [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]]\n| term_start          = 7 June 1929\n| term_end            = 5 November 1931\n| primeminister       = [[Ramsay MacDonald]]\n| predecessor         = [[Winston Churchill]]\n| successor           = [[Neville Chamberlain]]\n| term_start1         = 22 January 1924\n| term_end1           = 3 November 1924\n| primeminister1      = [[Ramsay MacDonald]]\n| predecessor1        = [[Neville Chamberlain]]\n| successor1          = [[Winston Churchill]]\n| party               = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] ({{circa|1894\u20131931}})<br>[[National Labour Organisation|National Labour]] (1931\u20131932)<br>None (1932\u20131937)\n| spouse              = {{marriage|[[Ethel Snowden|Ethel Annakin]]|1905}}\n| office2             = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Colne Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Colne Valley]]\n| term_start2         = 15 November 1922\n| term_end2           = 27 October 1931\n| predecessor2        = [[Frederick Mallalieu]]\n| successor2          = [[Lance Mallalieu]]\n}}\n\n'''Philip Snowden, 1st Viscount Snowden''', [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]] ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|n|o\u028a|d|\u0259n}}; 18 July 1864 \u2013 15 May 1937) was a British [[politician]]. A strong speaker, he became popular in trade union circles for his denunciation of capitalism as unethical and his promise of a socialist utopia.  He was the first [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], a position he held in 1924 and again between 1929 and 1931. He broke with Labour policy in 1931, and was expelled from the party and excoriated as a [[turncoat]], as the Party was overwhelmingly crushed that year by the [[National Government (1931)|National Government]] coalition that Snowden supported. He was succeeded as Chancellor by [[Neville Chamberlain]].\n\n==Early life: 1864\u20131906==\nSnowden was born in [[Cowling, Craven|Cowling]] in the [[West Riding of Yorkshire]]. His father John Snowden had been a weaver and a supporter of [[Chartism]], and later a [[Gladstonian liberalism|Gladstonian liberal]]. Snowden later wrote in his autobiography: \"I was brought up in this [[Radicalism (historical)#United Kingdom|Radical]] atmosphere, and it was then that I imbibed the political and social principles which I have held fundamentally ever since\".<ref>Philip, Viscount Snowden, ''An Autobiography. Volume One. 1864-1919'' (London: Ivor Nicholson and Watson, 1934), p. 19.</ref> Although his parents and sisters were involved in weaving at the Ickornshaw Mill, he did not join them; after attending a local board school (where he received additional lessons in French and Latin from the schoolmaster) he stayed on as a pupil-teacher.<ref name=\"obit\" /> When he was 15 he became an insurance office clerk in Burnley.<ref name=\"obit\" /> During his seven years as a clerk, he studied and then passed the civil service entry examination; in 1886, he was appointed to a junior position at the [[HM Excise|Excise Office]] in Liverpool.<ref name=\"obit\" /> Snowden moved on to other posts around Scotland and then to [[Devon]].<ref name=\"obit\" />\n\nIn August 1891, when he was aged 27, Snowden severely injured his back in a cycling accident in Devon and was paralyzed from the waist down.<ref name=\"obit\">\"Lord Snowden.\" Times [London, England] 17 May 1937: 15. The Times Digital Archive. Web. 8 September 2013.</ref> He learned to walk again with the aid of sticks within two years.<ref name=\"ODNB\">Duncan Tanner, \"Snowden, Philip, Viscount Snowden (1864\u20131937)]\", ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', 2004;</ref> His [[Inland Revenue]] job was kept open for him for two years following the accident; however, owing to his condition, he decided to resign from the civil service.<ref name=\"obit\" /> While he was convalescing at his mother's house at Cowling he began to study [[Socialism|socialist]] theory and history.<ref name=\"obit\" />\n\nSnowden joined the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]], and followed his parents in becoming a [[Methodist]] and a teetotaller. In 1893, in the aftermath of the formation of the [[Independent Labour Party]] (ILP) in neighboring [[Bradford]], he was asked to give a speech for the Cowling Liberal Club on the dangers of socialism. Whilst researching the subject, Snowden instead became convinced by the ideology. He eventually joined the executive committee of the [[Keighley]] ILP in 1899, and went on to chair the ILP from 1903 to 1906. He became a prominent speaker for the party, and wrote a popular [[Christian socialism|Christian socialist]] pamphlet with [[Keir Hardie]] in 1903, entitled ''The Christ that is to Be''. His strident rhetoric, well-laced with statistics and [[Evangelicalism|evangelical]] themes, contrasted the evil conditions under capitalism with the moral and economic utopia of future socialism. He condemned as \"bloodsuckers and parasites\" local textile company executives. In 1898, he launched the ''Keighley Labour Journal'', using it to denounce waste, pettiness, and corruption. However, he ignored the concerns of the trade unions, which he judged to be conservative and fixated on wages.<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> By 1902, he had moved his base to [[Leeds]] and toured Britain as a lecturer on politics and corruption, with his own syndicated column and short essays in numerous working class outlets. By the time he was elected [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for [[Blackburn (UK Parliament constituency)|Blackburn]] in 1906, he had become a well-known socialist figure, standing at the national level alongside both Keir Hardie, [[Arnold Lupton|Professor Arnold Lupton]] and [[Ramsay MacDonald]].<ref name=\"ODNB\" /><ref>Millman, Brock, ''Domestic Dissent in First World War Britain'', 2000, page 186.</ref>\n\nSnowden married [[Ethel Snowden|Ethel Annakin]], a campaigner for [[women's suffrage]], in 1905. He supported his wife's ideals, and he became a noted speaker at suffragette meetings and other public meetings.<ref name=\"ODNB\" />\n\n==Member of Parliament: 1906\u20131924==\n[[File:Labour Representation Committee leaders 1906.jpg|thumb|Snowden (fourth from left) in 1906, with other leading figures in the party]]\nSnowden unsuccessfully contested the [[Wakefield (UK Parliament constituency)|Wakefield]] constituency in West Yorkshire in a by-election in March 1902, where he received 40 percent of the votes.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Election intelligence |day_of_week=Wednesday |date=26 March 1902 |page_number=10 |issue=36725| }}</ref>\nIn [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]], he became the Labour MP for Blackburn.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=27885 |date=13 February 1906 |page=1038 }}</ref> He continued his writing and lectures, and now was advocating more radical measures than the ruling Liberals were implementing. He even devised his own \"Socialist budget\" to rival [[David Lloyd George]]'s 1909 \"[[People's Budget]]\".<ref name=\"ODNB\" />\n\nSnowden was in Australia on a worldwide lecture tour when the [[World War I|First World War]] broke out in August 1914; he did not return to Britain until February 1915. He was not a pacifist; however, he did not support recruiting for the armed forces, and he campaigned against conscription. His stance was unpopular with the public and he lost his seat in the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918 general election]]. In 1922, he was elected to represent [[Colne Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Colne Valley]].<ref name=\"ODNB\" />\n\n==Chancellor of the Exchequer: 1924==\nUpon Ramsay MacDonald's appointment as Prime Minister in January 1924, Snowden was appointed as the Labour Party's first ever [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]]<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=32901 |date=25 January 1924 |page=770 }}</ref> and sworn of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=32901 |date=25 January 1924 |page=769 }}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=13992 |date=29 January 1924 |page=147 |city=e }}</ref>\n\nIn his budget, Snowden lowered the duties on tea, coffee, cocoa, chicory and sugar; reduced spending on armaments; and provided money for council housing. However, he did not implement the [[capital levy]]. Snowden claimed that because of the lowering of duties on foodstuffs consumed by the working class, the budget went \"far to realize the cherished radical idea of a [[free breakfast table]]\".<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,718325-1,00.html ''Time'', Labor's Budget, 12 May 1924]</ref> He profoundly believed in the morality of the balanced budget, with rigorous economy and not a penny wasted. He grasped how serious unemployment was becoming, but differed with the rising belief in [[deficit spending]] as a way to combat it. [[A. J. P. Taylor]] said his budget \"would have delighted the heart of Gladstone\".<ref>Taylor, ''English History, 1914-1945'', p. 212.</ref>\n\nIn his first budget, Snowden earmarked \u00a338 million for the reduction of food taxes, the introduction of pensions for widows, and a reduction in the pensionable age to 65. However, only the first of these measures was realized during the first Labour Government's time in office.<ref>''Foundations of the Welfare State'', 2nd Edition by [[Pat Thane]], published 1996</ref>\n\n==Opposition: 1924\u20131929==\nAlthough he had chaired the ILP for a second time, from 1917 to 1920, Snowden resigned from the party in 1927 because he believed it was \"drifting more and more away from...evolutionary socialism into revolutionary socialism\". He was also opposed to the new [[Keynesian]] economic ideas which provided a rationale for deficit spending, and criticized their expression in the Liberals' manifesto for the [[1929 United Kingdom general election|1929 election]], titled ''We can Conquer Unemployment''.<ref name=\"ODNB\" />\n\n==Chancellor of the Exchequer: 1929\u20131931==\nSnowden was again appointed Chancellor after Labour formed a government in 1929, after emerging as the largest party in the general election.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=33508 |date=21 June 1929 |page=4106 }}</ref> His economic philosophy was one of strict Gladstonian Liberalism rather than socialism. His official biographer wrote, \"He was raised in an atmosphere which regarded borrowing as an evil and [[free trade]] as an essential ingredient of prosperity\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Keith Laybourn|title=Philip Snowden: a biography : 1864-1937|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UakgAAAAMAAJ|year=1988|publisher=Temple Smith|page=97}}</ref>\n\nHe was considered by many at the time and later as being the principal opponent to the government following any radical economic policy to tackle the [[Great Depression in the United Kingdom|Great Depression]] as well as blocking proposals to introduce [[Protectionism|protectionist]] tariffs. The government eventually collapsed over arguments about a budget deficit amidst refusals by a significant minority of ministers to enact cuts in unemployment benefit.<ref>Robert Skidelsky, ''Politicians and the Slump: The Labour Government of 1929-1931'' (1967)</ref>\n\nSnowden retained the position of Chancellor during the [[National Government (1931)|National Government]] of 1931. As a consequence he was expelled from the party, along with MacDonald and [[J. H. Thomas|Jimmy Thomas]]. In a BBC radio broadcast on 16 October 1931, he called Labour's policies \"Bolshevism run mad\" and contrasted them unfavorably with his own \"sane and evolutionary Socialism\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Kevin Jeffreys|title=Leading Labour: From Keir Hardie to Tony Blair|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZCuC-mrnjZsC&pg=PA33|year=1999|publisher=I.B.Tauris|page=33}}</ref> Snowden decided not to stand for parliament in the [[1931 United Kingdom general election|election of November 1931]]. At that election, Labour's number of seats declined catastrophically from 288 to 52. It was during that year he had [[prostate gland]] surgery, following which his health and mobility declined.<ref name=\"ODNB\" />\n\nSkidelsky is representative of the Keynesians who have charged that Snowden and MacDonald were blinded by their economic philosophy that required balanced budgets, sound money, the gold standard and free trade, regardless of the damage that Keynesians thought it would do to the economy and the people.<ref>Skidelsky, ''Politicians and the Slump: The Labour Government of 1929-1931'' (1967)</ref> However, with the decline of Keynesianism as a model after 1968, historians have reevaluated Snowden in a more favorable light. McKibbin argues that the Labour government had very limited room to manoeuvre in 1929-31, and it did as well as could be expected; and that it handled the British economy better than most foreign governments handled theirs, and the [[Great Depression]] was less severe in Britain than elsewhere.<ref>Ross McKibbin, \"The Economic Policy of the Second Labour Government 1929-1931,\" ''Past & Present'' (1975) #68 pp. 95-123 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/650274 in JSTOR]</ref>\n\n==Later life: 1931\u20131937==\n[[File:Vera & Chaim Weizmann, Herbert Samuel, Lloyd George, Ethel Snowden, Philip Snowden.jpeg|thumb|210px|[[Vera Weizmann]], [[Chaim Weizmann]], [[Herbert Samuel]], [[Lloyd George]], [[Ethel Snowden]], and Philip Snowden]]\nIn the [[1931 Dissolution Honours]] he was raised to the peerage as '''Viscount Snowden''' of Ickornshaw, in the West Riding of the County of York,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=33775 |date=27 November 1931 |page=7658 }}</ref> and served as [[Lord Privy Seal]] in the National government from 1931<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=33772 |date=17 November 1931 |page=7409 }}</ref> to 1932, when he resigned in protest at the enactment of a full scheme of [[Imperial Preference]] and [[Protectionism|protectionist]] tariffs. That year, Snowden said there was never a greater mistake than to say that [[Cobdenism]] was dead: \"Cobdenism was never more alive throughout the world than it was to-day...To-day the ideas of Cobden were in revolt against selfish nationalism. The need for the breaking down of trade restrictions, which took various forms, was universally recognized even by those who were unable to throw off those shackles\".<ref>''The Times'' (8 July 1932), p. 9.</ref>\n\nHe subsequently wrote his ''Autobiography'' in which he strongly attacked MacDonald. In the [[1935 United Kingdom general election|1935 general election]], Snowden supported the Keynesian economic program  proposed by Lloyd George (\"Lloyd George's New Deal\"), despite it being a complete repudiation of Snowden's own classical liberal fiscal policies. Snowden claimed that he was returning to long-held economic views, but that these had been \"temporarily inadvisable\" during the crisis of 1931, when \"national necessity\" demanded cutting public expenditure.<ref name=\"ODNB\" />\n\nLord Snowden died of a [[heart attack]] at his home, Eden Lodge, [[Tilford]], [[Surrey]] on 15 May 1937, aged 72. After cremation at [[Woking Crematorium]] his ashes were scattered on [[Cowling Moor]] near Ickornshaw. His library of books and pamphlets was presented to Keighley [[public library|Public Library]] by his widow, and a cairn was erected to his memory on Ickornshaw Moor in 1938.<ref name=\"ODNB\" />\n\nHis viscountcy died with him. Lady Snowden died in February 1951, aged 69.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n*{{cite book | first=Colin |last=Cross |title=Philip Snowden |publisher=Barrie & Jenkins |date=1966  |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book |first= Keith |last= Laybourn |first2= David |last2= James |editors=Keith Laybourn & David James |title= Philip Snowden: The First Labour Chancellor of the Exchequer |publisher=Bradford Arts, Museums and Libraries Service |date= 1987 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book |first=Keith |last=Laybourn |title=Philip Snowden. A Biography, 1864\u20131937 |publisher=Dartmouth Publishing |date= 1988 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book |first=Philip, Viscount |last=Snowden |title=An Autobiography |volume=vol. One  1864-1919 |place=London |publisher= Ivor Nicholson and Watson |date= 1934 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book | first=Philip, Viscount |last=Snowden |title=An Autobiography |volume=vol. Two 1919-1934 |place=London |publisher=Ivor Nicholson and Watson |date= 1934 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite journal |first=Duncan |last=Tanner |authorlink=Duncan Tanner |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/36181 |title=Snowden, Philip, Viscount Snowden (1864\u20131937)| journal=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |publisher=Oxford University Press |date= 2004 | accessdate= 1 July 2011 |ref=harv }}\n\n;Secondary sources\n\n*{{cite journal |first=Ross |last=McKibbin |title=The Economic Policy of the Second Labour Government 1929-1931 |journal= Past & Present |date=1975 |volume= #68 |pages=pp.&nbsp;95\u2013123 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book |first=A. J. P. |last=Taylor |title= English History, 1914-1945 |url=https://archive.org/details/englishhistory1900tayl |url-access=registration |publisher=Oxford University Press |date= 1965 |ref= p.209 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisource author}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-philip-snowden | Philip Snowden }}\n* {{FadedPage|id=Snowden, Philip|name=Philip Snowden|author=yes}}\n* [http://www.blackburnlabour.org/history/philip-snowden Philip Snowden] - Blackburn Labour Party\n* {{Cite EB1922|wstitle=Snowden, Phillip |short=x}}\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/016703}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Blackburn (historic UK Parliament constituency)|Blackburn]]\n  | years  = [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]]\u2013[[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]]\n  | with   = [[Harry Hornby|Sir Harry Hornby]] 1906\u20131910\n  | with2  = [[Thomas Barclay (economic writer)|Sir Thomas Barclay]] 1910\n  | with3  = [[Sir Henry Norman, 1st Baronet|Sir Henry Norman]] 1910\u20131918\n  | before = [[Sir William Coddington, 1st Baronet|Sir William Coddington]]<br />[[Harry Hornby|Sir Harry Hornby]]\n  | after  = [[Percy Dean]]<br />[[Sir Henry Norman, 1st Baronet|Sir Henry Norman]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Colne Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Colne Valley]]\n  | years  = [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922]]\u2013[[1931 United Kingdom general election|1931]]\n  | before = [[Frederick Mallalieu]]\n  | after  = [[Lance Mallalieu]]\n}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = Chairman of the [[Independent Labour Party]]\n  | years  = 1903\u20131906\n  | before = [[Bruce Glasier]]\n  | after  = [[Ramsay MacDonald]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = Chairman of the [[Independent Labour Party]]\n  | years  = 1917\u20131920\n  | before = [[Fred Jowett]]\n  | after  = [[R.&nbsp;C. Wallhead]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = Treasurer of the [[Independent Labour Party]]\n  | years  = 1920\u20131922\n  | before = [[T.&nbsp;D. Benson]]\n  | after  = [[George Benson (politician)|George Benson]]\n}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] | before=[[Neville Chamberlain]] | after=[[Winston Churchill]] | years=1924}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] | before=[[Winston Churchill]] | after=[[Neville Chamberlain]] | years=1929\u20131931}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Lord Privy Seal]] | before=[[William Peel, 1st Earl Peel|The Earl Peel]] | after=[[Stanley Baldwin]] | years=1931\u20131932}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{s-new|creation}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Viscount Snowden]]|years=1931\u20131937}}\n{{s-non|reason=Extinct}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{British Chancellors of the Exchequer}}\n{{First Macdonald Ministry}}\n{{Independent Labour Party}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Snowden, Philip}}\n[[Category:Chancellors of the Exchequer of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Lords Privy Seal]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Independent Labour Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Independent Labour Party National Administrative Committee members]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1906\u20131910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1922\u20131923]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1923\u20131924]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1924\u20131929]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1929\u20131931]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Snowden, Philip Snowden, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:Viscounts in the Peerage of the United Kingdom|Snowden, Philip Snowden, 1st]]\n[[Category:English memoirists|Snowden, Philip Snowden, 1st]]\n[[Category:English Methodists|Snowden, Philip Snowden, 1st]]\n[[Category:1864 births|Snowden, Philip Snowden, 1st]]\n[[Category:1937 deaths|Snowden, Philip Snowden, 1st]]\n[[Category:Politics of Blackburn with Darwen]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) hereditary peers]]\n[[Category:English Christian socialists]]\n[[Category:Methodist socialists]]\n[[Category:English evangelicals]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eChancellor of the Exchequer: 1929\u20131931:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1929-31 \u2192 1929\u201331", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philip_Snowden,_1st_Viscount_Snowden"}
{"title_page": "F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of Birkenhead", "text_new": "{{For|the author of \"633 Squadron\"|Frederick E. Smith}}\n{{short description|British politician}}\n{{short description|British politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Earl of Birkenhead\n| honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|GCSI|PC|DL}}\n| image        = 1stEarlOfBirkenhead.jpg\n| order1       = [[Secretary of State for India]]\n| term_start1  = 6 November 1924\n| term_end1    = 18 October 1928\n| monarch1     = [[George V]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Stanley Baldwin]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Sydney Olivier, 1st Baron Olivier|The Lord Olivier]]\n| successor1   = [[William Wellesley Peel, 1st Earl Peel|The Viscount Peel]]\n| order2       = [[Lord Chancellor|Lord High Chancellor of Great Britain]]\n| term_start2  = 10 January 1919\n| term_end2    = 19 October 1922\n| monarch2     = [[George V]]\n| primeminister2 = [[David Lloyd George]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Robert Finlay, 1st Viscount Finlay|The Lord Finlay]]\n| successor2   = [[George Cave, 1st Viscount Cave|The Viscount Cave]]\n| order3       = [[Attorney General for England and Wales]]\n| term_start3  = 3 November 1915\n| term_end3    = 10 January 1919\n| predecessor3 = [[Edward Carson, Baron Carson|Sir Edward Carson]]\n| successor3 = [[Gordon Hewart, 1st Viscount Hewart|Sir Gordon Hewart]]\n| monarch3     = [[George V]]\n| primeminister3 = [[H. H. Asquith]]\n| order4 = [[Solicitor General for England and Wales]]\n| term_start4 = 2 June 1915\n| term_end4 = 8 November 1915\n| predecessor4 = [[Stanley Buckmaster, 1st Viscount Buckmaster|Sir Stanley Buckmaster]]\n| successor4 = [[George Cave, 1st Viscount Cave|Sir George Cave]]\n| monarch4     = [[George V]]\n| primeminister4 = [[H. H. Asquith]]\n|office8         = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start8     = 3 February 1919\n|term_end8       = 30 September 1930<br>[[Hereditary Peerage]]\n|predecessor8    = ''[[Earl of Birkenhead|Peerage created]]''\n|successor8      = [[Frederick Smith, 2nd Earl of Birkenhead|The 2nd Earl of Birkenhead]]\n| office9 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br/>for [[Liverpool Walton (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Walton]]\n| term_start9    =  8 February 1906\n| term_end9      =  14 December 1918\n| predecessor9   =  [[James Henry Stock]]\n| successor9     =  Harry Chilcott\n| birth_name = Frederick Edwin Smith\n| birth_date = {{birth-date|12 July 1872|}}\n| birth_place = [[Birkenhead]], Cheshire\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1930|9|30|1872|7|12}}\n| death_place = [[Grosvenor Gardens, London|Grosvenor Gardens]], London\n| nationality = British\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| education = [[University of Liverpool]]<br>[[Wadham College, Oxford]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Margaret Eleanor Furneaux<br>|1901|30 September 1930|end=his death}}\n| children = Lady [[Eleanor Smith (writer)|Eleanor Smith]] (1902\u20131945)<br>[[Frederick Winston Furneaux-Smith, 2nd Earl of Birkenhead]] (1907\u20131975)<br>[[Pamela Smith|Lady Pamela Smith]] (1915\u20131982)\n}}\n\n'''Frederick Edwin Smith, 1st Earl of Birkenhead''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|GCSI|PC|DL}} (12 July 1872 \u2013 30 September 1930), known as '''F. E. Smith''', was a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician and barrister who attained high office in the early 20th century, in particular as [[Lord Chancellor|Lord High Chancellor of Great Britain]]. He was a skilled [[orator]], noted for his staunch opposition to [[Irish nationalism]], his wit, pugnacious views, and hard living and drinking. He is perhaps best remembered today as [[Winston Churchill]]'s greatest personal and political friend until Birkenhead's death aged 58 from pneumonia caused by cirrhosis of the liver.\n\n==Early life and schooling==\nSmith was born at 38 Pilgrim Street, [[Birkenhead]] in [[Cheshire]], the eldest son and second of five surviving children of Frederick Smith (1845-1888) and Elizabeth (1842\u20131928), daughter of Edwin Taylor a rate collector, of Birkenhead.<ref name=\"oxforddnb.com\">http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/odnb/9780192683120.001.0001/odnb-9780192683120-e-36137</ref><ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Schuster |first=Claud |authorlink=Claud Schuster, 1st Baron Schuster |year= |title=The Post Victorians: Lord Birkenhead |place= |publisher= |page=85}}{{clarify |reason=Who published this book, where and when? |date=March 2018}}</ref> His father had joined the family business as an estate agent, later becoming a barrister and local Tory politician. Frederick Smith senior died at the age of forty-three, only a month after being elected mayor of Birkenhead.<ref name=\"oxforddnb.com\"/><ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref>\n\nSmith was educated first at a [[dame school]] in Birkenhead, then at Sandringham School in [[Southport]] (where he announced, at the age of ten, his ambition to become lord chancellor), and then, having failed the entrance exam for [[Harrow School]], at Birkenhead School (1887\u20131889).<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref>\n\n==Oxford==\nSmith won a scholarship to [[University of Liverpool|University College, Liverpool]], where he spent four terms (a fact he subsequently suppressed).<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref>\n\nHe won a scholarship to [[Wadham College, Oxford]], in 1891.<ref name=odnb1>{{cite book |last=Campbell |first=John |title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |volume=51 |year=2004 |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=113 |isbn=0-19-861401-2}}</ref> Smith made his name as an Oxford \u201cswell\u201d, distinguishing himself by his dark good looks, his energy, his unashamed ambition and his scathing wit. He was the dominant figure of a group of Wadham contemporaries including the athlete [[C. B. Fry]], the future Liberal politician [[John Simon, 1st Viscount Simon|John Simon]], and the Liberal economist [[Francis Hirst]]. Between them they dominated both the rugby field and the [[Oxford Union Society]].<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref>\n\nSmith was already active in national politics as a Tory speaker in the [[1892 United Kingdom general election|July 1892 general election]]. Announced initially as his father's son, he spoke all over Lancashire, stirring up Orange opinion against the Liberal policy of [[Irish home rule]].<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref>\n\nHe obtained a [[British undergraduate degree classification|Second Class]] in [[Honour Moderations|Classical Mods]] before switching to Law. He often debated against [[Hilaire Belloc]] at the Oxford Union, where a bust of him now stands, and became [[List of presidents of the Oxford Union|President]] in Trinity (summer) term 1894. By massive last-minute cramming he graduated with a first class BA degree in law in 1895.<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref>\n\nTo his disappointment, he only obtained a Second in his [[Bachelor of Civil Law]] degree. In 1896 he won the [[Vinerian Scholarship|Vinerian law scholarship]] and was elected a fellow of [[Merton College, Oxford|Merton College]] (1896\u20139), and also a lecturership at [[Oriel College, Oxford|Oriel College]].<ref name=compeerage>{{cite book |title=The Complete Peerage, Volume XIII, Peerage Creations 1901\u20131938 |year=1940 |place= |publisher=St Catherine's Press |page=293}}</ref><ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref> The F.E. Smith Memorial Mooting Prizes nowadays commemorate him at [[Merton College, Oxford|Merton]]. In later life his depth of legal learning often surprised critics.<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref>\n\nSmith added to his Oxford reputation in May 1897, when he went to see [[Edward VII|the Prince of Wales]] open the new [[Oxford Town Hall]].  A detachment of the [[Metropolitan Police Mounted Branch]] had been drafted in to reinforce the small [[Oxford City Police]] force against a large demonstration of University undergraduates. The Metropolitan police, who were unused to boisterous Oxford undergraduates, attacked them with batons, causing several serious injuries. The crowd unhorsed and trampled one policeman.<ref name=Rose>{{cite book |last=Rose |first=Geoff |year=1979 |title=A Pictorial History of the Oxford City Police |place=Oxford |publisher=Oxford Publishing Co |isbn=0-86093-094-7 |page=5}}</ref> Smith took no part in the disorder, but was arrested when he tried to rescue his college servant, who was being manhandled by the police. Smith became the first prisoner in the police station in the new Town Hall. Before being locked in, Smith raised his hands for silence and declared \"I have great pleasure in declaring this cell open\". He was tried for obstructing the police in the lawful execution of their duty, but was found not guilty after defending himself in court.<ref name=\"Rose\" />\n\n==Career as a barrister==\nHaving eaten his dinners at [[Gray's Inn]] and passed his bar finals with distinction in the summer of 1899, Smith was [[called to the Bar]] and finally left [[University of Oxford|Oxford]], and quickly built up a brilliant and lucrative practice on the [[Northern Circuit]], initially basing himself in [[Liverpool]].<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref>\n\nSmith married Margaret Eleanor Furneaux, daughter of classical scholar [[Henry Furneaux]], in April 1901 and they had three children, [[Eleanor Smith (writer)|Eleanor Smith]], [[Frederick Winston Furneaux-Smith, 2nd Earl of Birkenhead|Frederick]] and [[Pamela Smith]].\n\nSmith rapidly acquired a reputation as a formidable [[advocate]], first in Liverpool and then, after his election to Parliament in 1906, in [[London]]. In 1907 he was asked to give an opinion on a proposed [[libel]] action by the [[Lever Brothers]] against newspapers owned by [[Lord Northcliffe]] concerning the latter's allegations of a conspiracy to raise the price of soap by means of a 'soap trust'. He checked into the [[Savoy Hotel|Savoy]] and, after working all night reading a pile of papers nearly four feet thick and consuming a bottle of champagne and two dozen oysters, Smith wrote a one-sentence opinion: \"There is no [[defense (legal)|answer]] to this action in libel, and the damages must be enormous\".<ref>{{cite journal |last=Johnson |first=Paul |authorlink=Paul Johnson (writer) |title=The age of stout hearts, sharp swords \u2014 and fun |journal=The Spectator |place=London |date=15 March 2006 |url= http://www.spectator.co.uk/2006/04/the-age-of-stout-hearts-sharp-swords-and-fun/}}</ref><ref>Judgment in ''Cox v. MGN Ltd'' [2006] EWHC 1235, \u00a7&nbsp;32 (Eady J)</ref> The newspapers subsequently paid Lever \u00a350,000, more than four times the previous record for a defamation action or out-of-court published settlement in the country.\n\nIn February 1908, Smith was made a [[King's Counsel]] by [[Robert Reid, 1st Earl Loreburn|Lord Loreburn]], on the same day as his friend and rival from Wadham College, future Home Secretary Sir [[John Simon, 1st Viscount Simon|John Simon]].\n\nAt the Bar, he became one of the best known and most highly paid barristers in the country, making over \u00a310,000 per year before the First World War. His spending was commensurate with this income even after he took less well-paid government positions in later years, something of which he would bitterly complain.\n\nIn one of the best-known cases in which Smith was involved he successfully defended [[Ethel le Neve]], mistress of [[Hawley Harvey Crippen]] (\"Dr Crippen\") against a charge of murder. Le Neve was accused of killing Crippen's wife. Crippen was tried separately and convicted.\n\n==Member of Parliament==\n[[File:Birkenhead by Spy0002.jpg|thumb|upright|<center>\"A Successful First Speech (\"[[Psalm 108|Moab is my Washpot]]\")\"<br>FE Smith MP depicted in ''[[Vanity Fair (UK magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', January 1907</center>]]\nAmbitious to enter [[British House of Commons|Parliament]], Smith cultivated the local Tory [[Political boss|boss]] [[Archibald Salvidge]].<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref> He stood unsuccessfully in Liverpool, for [[Liverpool Scotland (UK Parliament constituency)|Scotland division]] in a by-election in 1903.<ref name=compeerage/><ref name=EB1922>{{Cite EB1922 |wstitle=Birkenhead, Frederick Edwin Smith, 1st Viscount |volume=30 |page=457}}</ref>\n\nIn 1903, Smith gave a dazzling speech in Liverpool in support of [[Joseph Chamberlain]], who was campaigning for [[Tariff Reform]]. On the strength of this, he was selected three months later as candidate for the working-class constituency of [[Liverpool Walton (UK Parliament constituency)|Walton division]].<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref> He stood, again unsuccessfully, for Walton in another by-election in 1905.<ref name=compeerage/><ref name=EB1922>{{Cite EB1922 |wstitle=Birkenhead, Frederick Edwin Smith, 1st Viscount |volume=30 |page=457}}</ref> He campaigned as the champion of hard-drinking, patriotic working men (Liberals tended to favour temperance and more pacific foreign policy) and in the [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906 election]] he narrowly held the seat despite the national Liberal landslide. He held the seat until the redrawing of boundaries in 1918.<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref>\n\nHe attracted attention by a brilliant [[maiden speech]], \"[[I warn the Government]]...\" After this speech, [[Timothy Michael Healy|Tim Healy]], the Irish Nationalist, a master of parliamentary invective, sent Smith a note, \"I am old, and you are young, but you have beaten me at my own game.\" In his maiden speech he argued that advocating tariffs had not hurt the Tories at the recent election.<ref>Harris 2013, p.244</ref> Smith also opposed the [[Trade Disputes Act 1906]] arguing that intimidatory picketing should not be allowed. The Conservative leadership, unwilling to antagonise organised labour, did not oppose the Act very hard.<ref>Harris 2013, p.244</ref>\n\nSmith did not support restriction on the powers of the [[House of Lords]], fearing that tyranny could result from an unchecked [[unicameral]] parliament.\n\nHe was soon a prominent leader of the [[Unionism (Ireland)|Unionist]] wing of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]], especially in the planned [[Ulster]] resistance to [[Irish Home Rule]]. He attended the Blenheim Palace rally on 27 July 1912, at which Bonar Law advocated forcible resistance. From the signing of the [[Ulster Covenant]] in September 1912 onwards, he was often on [[Edward Carson]]\u2019s side on horseback, hence the derisive nickname \u201cGalloper Smith\u201d.<ref>Harris 2013, pp.255-6</ref>\n\nA vociferous opponent of the [[Disestablishmentarianism|Disestablishment]] of the [[Church in Wales|Welsh part of the Church of England]], he called the [[Welsh Church Act 1914|Welsh Disestablishment Bill]] \"a bill which has shocked the conscience of every Christian community in Europe\". This prompted [[G. K. Chesterton]] to write a satirical poem, [[s:Antichrist, or the Reunion of Christendom: An Ode|''\u201cAntichrist, Or the Reunion of Christendom: An Ode\u201d'']], which asked if [[Brittany|Breton]] sailors, Russian peasants and Christians evicted by the [[Ottoman Empire|Turks]] would know or care of what happened to the [[Church in Wales|Anglican Church of Wales]], and answered the question with the line \"Chuck it, Smith\". The bill was approved by Parliament under the provisions of the [[Parliament Act 1911]], but its implementation delayed by the outbreak of the [[First World War]]. When it was finally implemented in 1920, Smith was part of the [[Lloyd George Coalition Government|Lloyd George Coalition]] that did so.\n\n==First World War==\nSmith had joined the [[Territorial Army (United Kingdom)|Territorial Army]] by commission into the [[Queen's Own Oxfordshire Hussars]], in which Churchill was already an officer, in 1913,<ref name=compeerage/> and was a [[Captain (British Army)|captain]] in the regiment<ref name=\"kelly\">{{cite book |title=Kelly's Handbook to the Titled, Landed and Official Classes, 1930 |place= |publisher=Kelly's |page=239}}</ref> before the outbreak of the First World War. On its outbreak he was placed in charge of the Government's Press Bureau, with rank of full colonel and responsibility for newspaper censorship. He was not very successful in this role, and in 1914\u20131915 served in France as a staff officer with the [[Indian Corps]] with ultimate temporary rank of [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|lieutenant-colonel]].<ref name=\"kelly\"/> He and his successor as 'recording officer' (a [[Colonel (British Army)|Colonel]] Merewether) later collaborated on an official history entitled ''The Indian Corps in France'' (published 1917).<ref name=compeerage2>{{cite book |title=The Complete Peerage, Volume XIII |place= |publisher= |page=294}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1915, he was appointed [[Solicitor General for England and Wales|Solicitor General]] by [[Herbert Henry Asquith|H. H. Asquith]] and [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]].<ref name=EB1922/> He soon after (in October 1915) succeeded his friend [[Edward Carson|Sir Edward Carson]] as [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Attorney General]],<ref name=EB1922/> with the right to attend Cabinet. Early in 1916 he was briefly placed under military arrest for arriving at [[Boulogne]] without a pass, and had to be 'appeased' by a meeting with [[General (United Kingdom)|General]] [[Douglas Haig, 1st Earl Haig|Sir Douglas Haig]].<ref>Groot 1988, p.226</ref>\n\nAs [[Attorney General of England and Wales|Attorney General]], it was his responsibility to lead the prosecution for [[the Crown]] in major cases such as the trial in 1916 of the [[Irish nationalist]] [[Sir Roger Casement]] for [[Treason in the United Kingdom|treason]].<ref name=EB1922/> Sir Roger had been captured after landing from [[SM U-19 (Germany)|a ''Kaiserliche Marine'' U-boat]] on [[Banna Strand]] in [[Tralee Bay]] in north [[County Kerry]], south-west Ireland, just a few days before the [[Easter Rising]] in late April 1916.<ref>Martin Green, \"Children of the Sun: A Narrative of Decadence in England After 1918\"</ref> His prosecution of Casement (and [[Alice Wheeldon|Wheeldon]] in 1917) contributed to Smith's reputation as a spectacular advocate at the time.<ref>Watson Andrew (2019), 'A spectacular quartet of leading barristers' in ''Speaking in Court.'' Palgrave Macmillan.https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-10395-8_8</ref>\n\nSmith was made a [[baronet]] in 1918. Following abolition of the Walton seat in constituency boundary changes, Smith was returned at the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|December 1918 general election]] for neighbouring [[Liverpool West Derby (UK Parliament constituency)|West Derby Division]], only to be elevated to the House of Lords two months later.<ref name=\"odnb4\">{{cite book|title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Volume 51|pages=116}}</ref>\n\n==Postwar Coalition: Lord Chancellor==\n[[File:F. E. Smith as Lord Chancellor.jpg|thumb|upright|Sir F. E. Smith, newly created [[Earl of Birkenhead|Lord Birkenhead]], on his appointment as [[Lord Chancellor]]]]\nIn 1919, he was created '''Baron Birkenhead''', of Birkenhead in the County of Cheshire following his appointment as [[Lord Chancellor]] by [[David Lloyd George|Lloyd George]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31201|page=2735|date=25 February 1919}}</ref> At the age of 47, he was the youngest Lord Chancellor since [[George Jeffreys, 1st Baron Jeffreys|Judge Jeffreys]].{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} The ''[[Morning Post]]'' dismissed his appointment as \"carrying a joke beyond the limits of pleasantry\", while the [[George V|King]] urged Lloyd George to reconsider.{{sfn|Campbell|1991|p=460}} Birkenhead proved an excellent Lord Chancellor, but tales of his drunkenness begin from this time, very likely as he grew bored with the job and as it dawned on him that he had probably ruled himself out from the premiership by accepting a peerage.{{sfn|Harris|2013|pp=277-81}}\n\nThat year, in the House of Lords debate on the [[Amritsar Massacre]], he courageously denounced Tories who declared [[Reginald Dyer|General Dyer]] (the responsible officer) a hero.<ref name=odnb3>{{cite book |title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |volume=51 |page=117}}</ref> He played a key role in the passage of several key legal reforms, including the reform of English land law which was to come to fruition in [[Law of Property Act 1925|the mid-1920s]].{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} He also unsuccessfully championed a reform of the divorce laws, which he judged caused great misery and which favoured the wealthy.\n\nDespite his Unionist background, Smith played an important role in the negotiations that led to the signature of the [[Anglo-Irish Treaty]] in 1921, which led to the formation of the [[Irish Free State]] the following year.{{sfn|Harris|2013|pp=275}} Much of the treaty was drafted by Smith. His support for this, and his warm relations with the Irish nationalist leaders [[Arthur Griffith]] and [[Michael Collins (Irish leader)|Michael Collins]], angered some of his former Unionist associates, notably Sir Edward Carson. Upon signing the Treaty he remarked to Collins, \"I may have just signed my political death warrant\", to which Collins dryly and with prescient accuracy replied, \"I have just signed my actual death warrant\". Collins was killed by opponents of the treaty eight months after the signing, during the [[Irish Civil War]].{{sfn|Aitken|1963|pp=96\u2013123}}\n\nAlso in 1921, he was responsible for the [[House of Lords]] rejecting a proposal, put forward by [[Frederick Alexander Macquisten]], MP for [[Argyllshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Argyllshire]], to criminalise lesbianism. During the debate, Birkenhead argued that 999 women out of a thousand had \"never even heard a whisper of these practices\".<ref>{{cite book |last=Doan |first=Laura |title=Fashioning Sapphism: The Origins of a Modern English Lesbian Culture |url=https://archive.org/details/fashioningsapphi00doan |url-access=registration |publisher=Columbia University Press |year=2001 |place=New York |isbn=0-231-11007-3 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/fashioningsapphi00doan/page/56 56\u201360]}}</ref><ref>{{cite hansard |jurisdiction=UK |title=Commons Amdendment, HL Deb 15 August 1921 vol 43 cc567-77 |url= http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1921/aug/15/commons-amendment-2#S5LV0043P0_19210815_HOL_114 |house=House of Lords |date=15 August 1921 |column=574 |speaker=The Lord Chancellor |position=574}}</ref>\n\nSmith was created '''Viscount Birkenhead''', of Birkenhead in the [[County of Chester]], in the [[1921 Birthday Honours]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=32346 |date=4 June 1921 |page=4529 |supp=y}}</ref> then '''Viscount Furneaux''', of [[Charlton, Northamptonshire|Charlton]] in the [[County of Northampton]], and '''Earl of Birkenhead''' in 1922. By 1922 Birkenhead and Churchill had become the leading figures of the [[David Lloyd George|Lloyd George]] Coalition. The [[Anglo-Irish Treaty]], the attempt to go to war with [[Turkey]] over [[Chanak Crisis|Chanak]] (which was later vetoed by the governments of the Dominions) and a general whiff of moral and financial corruption which had come to surround the Coalition were all hallmarks of his tenure in office.\n\nA scandal erupted in 1922 when it became known that Lloyd George, through the agency of [[Maundy Gregory]],<ref name=camp/> had awarded honours and titles such as a baronetcy to rich businessmen in return for cash in the range of \u00a310,000 and more.<ref>{{cite book |first=Travis L |last=Crosby |title=The Unknown David Lloyd George: A Statesman in Conflict |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=MIW9AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA330 |year=2014 |place= |publisher=IB Tauris |page=330 |isbn=978-1-78076-485-6}}</ref> At an earlier meeting before Parliament broke up for the summer, and more famously at the [[Carlton Club]] meeting in October 1922, Birkenhead's hectoring of the junior ministers and backbenchers was one of the factors leading to the withdrawal of support from the Coalition.{{sfn|Aitken|1963|pp=200\u2013203}}\n\n==Out of office: 1922-24==\nLike many of the senior members of the Coalition, Birkenhead did not hold office in the [[Bonar Law]] and Baldwin governments of 1922\u201324. Unlike the others Birkenhead was rude and open in his contempt for the new governments. He bore no grudge against Bonar Law but criticised [[Leslie Wilson (politician)|Leslie Wilson]] and Lord Curzon. He sneered that Wilson and Sir [[George Younger, 1st Viscount Younger of Leckie|George Younger]] were \"the cabin boys\" who had taken over the ship, he referred to [[James Gascoyne-Cecil, 4th Marquess of Salisbury|Lords Salisbury]] and [[Lord Selborne|Selborne]] as \"the [[Dolly Sisters]]\" after two starlets of the era and remarked that the new Cabinet was one of \"second-class brains\", to which came the reply from [[Robert Cecil, 1st Viscount Cecil of Chelwood|Lord Robert Cecil]]<ref>the quote is also sometimes attributed to Stanley Baldwin</ref> that this was better than \"second-class characters\". He remarked that he had lost the Woolsack but was still \u201ccaptain of [his] own soul\u201d to which a wag retorted that this was \u201ca small command of which no-one will want to deprive him\u201d.<ref>Harris 2013 pp.286-7</ref>\n\nIn the House of Lords he accused the Foreign Secretary [[Lord Curzon]] (who had deserted the Coalition in its final hours and thus retained his office under [[Bonar Law]]) of making unauthorised promises of support to [[Greece]] in her [[Greco-Turkish War (1919\u201322)|war against Turkey]]; he was forced to apologise when Curzon produced the key documents which he had circulated to the Cabinet, and which Birkenhead had initialled as read. [[Grace Curzon, Marchioness Curzon of Kedleston|Lady Curzon]] retaliated by [[Cut (etiquette)|cutting]] Birkenhead at a ball, but as she remarked to her husband in a letter, he was \"too drunk to notice\" the snub.\n\nIn May 1923, [[Stanley Baldwin]] succeeded Bonar Law as Prime Minister. He remarked to his new Cabinet, referring to Birkenhead's exclusion, that they were \u201ca Cabinet of faithful husbands\u201d \u2013 this referred to Birkenhead's general character rather than simply his marital infidelities.<ref>Lloyd George and Robert Horne were also notorious womanisers - see their articles for details</ref><ref>Charmley 1993, p. 203</ref>\n\nEven a famous speech, the Rectorial Address to [[Glasgow University]] on 7 November 1923,<ref>\"Idealism in International Politics.\" Reprinted in: ''The Speeches of Lord Birkenhead.'' London, 1929. p. 204-217. According to Paul Johnson (''Heroes: From Alexander the Great and Julius Caesar to Churchill and de Gaulle.'' New York, 2007. p. 207), \"The speech was, in its own way, as sensational as his maiden, and required the same kind of courage.\"</ref> in which Birkenhead told undergraduates that the world still offered \"glittering prizes\" to those with \"stout hearts and sharp swords\", now seemed out of kilter with the less aggressive and more self-consciously moral style of politics advocated by the new generation of Conservative politicians such as Stanley Baldwin and [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Edward Wood]], the future Lord Halifax. Birkenhead regarded the [[League of Nations]] as idealistic nonsense, and thought that international relations should be guided by \u201cself-interest\u201d, lest Britain decline like [[Spanish Empire|Imperial Spain]].<ref>Charmley 1993, pp203-4</ref> Rather, he believed that the power of nations would still be determined by their military strength.<ref>Haris 2013, p.332</ref>\n\nBy this time Birkenhead was regarded with distaste by much of the grassroots Conservative Party. [[J. C. C. Davidson|J.C.C. Davidson]] reported back to [[Conservative Campaign Headquarters|Central Office]] (18 November 1923) on his recent re-adoption as candidate for [[Hemel Hempstead (UK Parliament constituency)|Hemel Hempstead]] that many members were unwilling to support him without an assurance that he would not support Birkenhead's return to the Cabinet, lest this cost local votes at [[1923 United Kingdom general election|the upcoming election]]. He commented that this was proof that Puritanism was deep in the English blood, and not just in that of Nonconformist chapel-goers. [[Neville Chamberlain]] recorded in his diary (18 November 1923) that Birkenhead had \u201cso often and so deeply shocked the moral sense of the country by his drunkenness and loose living character that our Govt which rests largely on public confidence in our character would be seriously tarnished by association with such a man\u201d.<ref>Charmley 1993, pp203-4 </ref>\n\n==Secretary of State for India: 1924-28==\nAfter the December 1923 General Election, at which Baldwin lost his majority and a hung Parliament was returned, Birkenhead briefly intrigued for another Lloyd George coalition government. In order to discourage them from associating with Lloyd George, Baldwin quickly invited former coalitionists Austen Chamberlain, Birkenhead and Balfour to join the Shadow Cabinet.<ref>Harris 2013, pp.301-2</ref> Birkenhead persuaded his friend Churchill to stand (unsuccessfully, as an independent \u201cConstitutionalist\u201d) in the March [[1924 Westminster Abbey by-election]]. This was part of Churchill's move back towards rejoining the Conservative Party.<ref>Harris 2013, p.303</ref>.\n\nA 1924 entry in [[Evelyn Waugh]]'s diary states that an English High Court judge, presiding in a [[sodomy]] case, sought advice on sentencing from Lord Birkenhead. \"Could you tell me,\" he asked, \"what do you think one ought to give a man who allows himself to be buggered?\" Birkenhead replied without hesitation, \"Oh, thirty shillings or two pounds; whatever you happen to have on you.\"<ref>Cited in ''[[The Times]]'' 23 May 2006, Law supplement p.7</ref>\n\nDespite winning a large majority at the [[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924 election]], Baldwin formed a broad new (second) government by appointing former coalitionists such as Birkenhead, Austen Chamberlain and former Liberal Winston Churchill to senior Cabinet posts; this was to discourage them from associating with Lloyd George to revive the 1916-22 Coalition.<ref>Charmley 1993, pp. 202-3</ref> Birkenhead and Chamberlain lobbied Baldwin to reappoint another former coalitionist, [[Robert Horne, 1st Viscount Horne of Slamannan|Robert Horne]], to the Exchequer, but Baldwin refused and appointed Churchill instead.<ref>Charmley 1993, p. 200</ref> \n\nFrom 1924 to 1928 Birkenhead served as [[Secretary of State for India]]. His views on pre-partition India's independence movement were gloomy. He thought India's Hindu-Muslim religious divide insurmountable and sought to block advances in native participation in provincial governments that had been granted by the 1919 [[Montagu-Chelmsford Reforms]]. His parliamentary private secretary recalled much time ostensibly on India Office business seemed to be spent playing [[golf]].<ref name=odnb2>{{cite book |title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |volume=51 |page=118}}</ref>\n\nBirkenhead endorsed his old political opponent [[H.H. Asquith]], rather than his Cabinet colleague [[George Cave, 1st Viscount Cave|Lord Cave]], in the [[1925 University of Oxford Chancellor election]]. He wrote to ''[[The Times]]'' on 19 May, describing Asquith as the \u201cgreatest living Oxonian\u201d, but his support may have done more harm than good, because of his association with the discredited Lloyd George Coalition, and because of his open scepticism both of religion and of the League of Nations. It was quipped that Asquith was \u201ca [[Bed warmer|warming-pan]]\u201d for Birkenhead's views (a learned Oxford joke, referring to the legend that the [[James Francis Edward Stuart|Old Pretender]] had been an impostor baby rather than a rightful heir to the throne). Lord Cave was elected.<ref>Koss 1985, pp. 274-275</ref>\n\nHe was engaged outside the office in negotiating for the government with the [[Trades Union Congress]] to try to avert the [[1926 General Strike]] and he strongly supported the 1927 [[Trade Disputes and Trade Unions Act 1927|Trades Disputes Act]] which required union members to contract into the political levies.<ref name=odnb2/> It was in his government role that in October 1927 he unveiled the [[Neuve-Chapelle Indian Memorial]] to Indian Army soldiers of no known grave killed on the Western Front in the 1914\u201318 War.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.cwgc.org/find-a-cemetery/cemetery/144000/NEUVE%20CHAPELLE%20MEMORIAL |title=Neuve-Chapelle Memorial |publisher=[[Commonwealth War Graves Commission|CWGC]] |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nLord Cave resigned as Lord Chancellor early in 1928. Birkenhead apparently did not want to return to his old job, but neither did Baldwin offer it to him. According to Neville Chamberlain's diary (28 March 1928), this was because \u201che might be seen drunk in the street\u201d ([[Douglas Hogg, 1st Viscount Hailsham|Lord Hailsham]] was appointed instead).<ref>Charmley 1993, pp. 232-3</ref> Birkenhead retired from the Cabinet in October 1928 to make money in business.<ref>Charmley p.234</ref>\n\n==Later life and assessments==\nBirkenhead's increasingly pompous oratory caused [[David Low (cartoonist)|David Low]] to caricature him in the 1920s as \"Lord Burstinghead\".<ref name=odnb3/> After retiring from politics, he became Rector of the [[University of Aberdeen]], a director of [[Tate & Lyle]],{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} a director of [[Imperial Chemical Industries]],<ref name=camp/> and [[High Steward (academia)|High Steward]] of the [[University of Oxford]]. In a 1983 biography review, William Camp \u2014 who had written a 1960 biography of the man \u2014 opined that \"F.E. was the quintessential male chauvinist who, almost with his dying breath, dragged himself to the Lords in July 1930 to attack the right of peeresses to take their seats.\"<ref name=camp>{{cite news |url= http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/26th-november-1983/26/that-crooked-charmer-smith |title=That crooked charmer, Smith |newspaper=The Spectator |date=26 Nov 1983 |page=26}}</ref>\n\nBirkenhead wrote a series of articles (later republished in ''Last Essays'': 1930) about \"the peril to India\", in which he criticised the Indian Nationalist leaders as \"a collection ... of very inferior [[Alexander Kerensky|Kerenskis]]\" and asserted that it was widely accepted that without British rule India would collapse into anarchy. He attacked the [[Edward Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Irwin Declaration]] as \"so ambiguous that it is impossible to select from it any clear and unambiguous proposal\".<ref>Charmley 1993, p.245</ref>\n\nIn the opinion of [[Winston Churchill]], who was a friend: \"He had all the canine virtues in a remarkable degree \u2013 courage, fidelity, vigilance, love of chase.\" As for [[Margot Asquith]], who was not a friend, she thought: \"F. E. Smith is very clever, but sometimes his brains go to his head.\" Of Birkenhead's loyalty, Churchill added: \"If he was with you on Monday, he would be the same on Tuesday. And on Thursday, when things looked blue, he would still be marching forward with strong reinforcements.\"\n\n[[Gilbert Frankau]] recalled in his own autobiography ''Self Portrait'', that in 1928 [[Thomas Horder, 1st Baron Horder|Sir Thomas Horder]] confided: \"Birkenhead's pure eighteenth-century. He belongs to the days of [[Charles James Fox|Fox]] and [[William Pitt the younger|Pitt]]. Physically, he has all the strength of our best yeoman stock. Mentally, he's a colossus. But he'll tear himself to pieces by the time he's sixty.\"<ref name=frankau>{{cite book |last=Frankau |first=Gilbert |title=Self Portrait, A Novel of His Own Life |year=1941 |place= |publisher=The Book Club |pages=262\u2013263}}</ref>\n\nBirkenhead died in London aged 58 from [[pneumonia]] caused by [[cirrhosis of the liver]]. After cremation at [[Golders Green Crematorium]], his ashes were buried in the parish churchyard at [[Charlton, Northamptonshire]].<ref name=\"odnb2\"/>\n\n===Commemoration===\nAs \"Lord Birkenhead\", he is dramatised in the film ''[[Chariots of Fire]]'', as an official of the [[British Olympic Committee]]. He is played by actor [[Nigel Davenport]].\n\nIn the year of his death, he published his utopian ''The World in 2030 A.D.'' with airbrush illustrations by [[E. McKnight Kauffer]].<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.fulltable.com/VTS/f/fut/t.htm |last=McKnight Kauffer |first=E |title=The World in 2030 |website=fulltable.com |accessdate=}}</ref> The book was the subject of considerable controversy as several passages were alleged to have been copied from earlier works by [[J. B. S. Haldane]].{{sfn|Campbell|1991|p=828}}\n\n==Works==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* ''International Law in the Far East'', 2nd ed. 1908.\n* ''The Licensing Bill'', 1908.\n* ''International Law'', 4th ed. 1911.\n* ''Poems by Samuel Johnson, LLD''.\n* ''Toryism until 1832''.\n* ''Speeches, 1906\u20131909'' (2nd ed.).\n* ''The Destruction of Merchant Ships'', 1917.\n* ''My American Visit'', 1918 (2nd edition).\n* ''The Indian Corps in France'' (2nd edition).\n* ''The Story of Newfoundland'', 1920.\n* ''Points of View'', 1922.\n* ''Contemporary Personalities'', 1924.\n* ''America Revisited'', 1924.\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Fourteen English Judges'', 1926.\n* ''Famous Trials of History'', 1926.\n* ''Law, Life and Letters'', 1927.\n* ''More Famous Trials'', 1928.\n* ''The Speeches of Lord Birkenhead'', 1929.\n* ''The World in 2030 AD'', 1930.\n* ''Turning Points in History'', 1930.\n* ''Last Essays'', 1930.\n* (Editor) ''The Five Hundred Best English Letters'', 1931.\n* ''Fifty Famous Fights in Fact and Fiction'', 1932.\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Cases==\n===As counsel===\n* ''R v Casement'' [1917] 1 KB 98, prosecution of [[Roger Casement|Sir Roger Casement]] for [[High treason in the United Kingdom|high treason]]\n\n===As judge===\n* ''[[Margaret Mackworth, 2nd Viscountess Rhondda|Viscountess Rhondda]]'s Claim'' [1922] 2 AC 339, right of peeresses to sit in the [[House of Lords]]\n* [[R v Secretary of State for Home Affairs, ex p O'Brien|R ''v Secretary of State for Home Affairs, ex p O'Brien'']] [1923] AC 691, legality of British policy of internment in Ireland\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = [[File:Coronet of a British Earl.svg|centre|150px]][[File:Birkenhead Escutcheon.png|centre|200px]]\n|escutcheon = Ermine on a pale Gules between four cross crosslets of the second a like cross Or.\n|crest = A cubit arm couped fessways vested Gules cuffed Argent the hand Proper grasping a sword erect also Argent pommel and hilt Or.\n|supporters = Dexter a griffin Or wings per fess Or and Sable, sinister a lion Azure charged on the shoulder with a crozier Or.\n|motto = Faber Me\u00e6 Fortun\u00e6 <ref>{{cite book|title=Burke's Peerage |date=1959}}</ref>}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite book |last=Aitken |first=Max |authorlink=Max Aitken, 1st Baron Beaverbrook |year=1963 |title=The Decline and Fall of Lloyd George |place=London |publisher=Collins}}\n*{{cite book |last=Camp |first=William |year=1960 |title=The Glittering Prizes: A Biographical Study of F. E. Smith |place=London |publisher=MacGibbon & Kee}}\n*{{cite book |last=Campbell |first=John |year=1983 |title=F. E. Smith: First Earl of Birkenhead |place=London |publisher=Jonathan Cape |isbn= |ref=harv}}\n*{{ODNBweb |first=John |last=Campbell |title=Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930) |origyear=2004 |year=2015 |edition=online |id=36137 }}\n* {{citation | last= Charmley | first= John | title=Churchill: The End of Glory | publisher=Sceptre|date=1995 |origyear=1993| isbn=978- 0340599228}}\n*{{cite book |last=De Groot |first=Gerard |year=|title=Douglas Haig 1861\u20131928 |place=Larkfield, Maidstone |publisher=Unwin Hyman |isbn=}}\n* {{citation | last= Harris | first= Robin | title=The Conservatives - A History | publisher=Corgi|date=2013 | isbn=978-0552170338}}\n*{{cite book |last=Heuston |first=RVF |year=1964 |title=Lives of the Lord Chancellors 1885\u20131940 |url=https://archive.org/details/livesoflordchanc0000heus |url-access=registration |place=Oxford |publisher=Clarendon Press}}\n* {{cite book | last = Koss | first = Stephen | authorlink = Stephen Koss | year = 1985 | title = Asquith | url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=tBGGAAAAIAAJ&dq=Asquith+Stephen+Koss&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj09Ya9-LbOAhXlLMAKHaOeCCQQ6AEIKzAA | location = London | publisher = Hamish Hamilton | isbn = 978-0-231-06155-1| ref = {{sfnRef|Koss}}}}\n*{{cite book |last=Roberts |first=Carl Eric Bechhofer |year=1927 |title=Lord Birkenhead. Being an account of the life of F.E. Smith, first Earl of Birkenhead |place=London |publisher=Mills and Boon}}\n*{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Frederick |authorlink=Frederick Smith, 2nd Earl of Birkenhead |year=1933 |title=Frederick Edwin, Earl of Birkenhead |place=London |publisher=Thornton Butterworth}}\n*{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Frederick |year=1960 |title=F.E.: The Life of F. E. Smith First Earl of Birkenhead |place=London |publisher=Eyre and Spottiswoode}} \u2013 heavily revised edition of the above, with added material on Smith's political career, and much material relating to his legal career excised.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Frederick Edwin Smith, 1st Earl of Birkenhead}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{wikisource author}}\n* {{Gutenberg author |id=Birkenhead,+Frederick+Edwin+Smith,+Earl+of}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Frederick Edwin Smith, 1st Earl of Birkenhead}}\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-fe-smith| F. E. Smith}}\n* {{NPG name|name=F. E. Smith}}\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/016687}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[James Henry Stock]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament for [[Liverpool Walton (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Walton]] | years=[[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]]\u2013[[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Harry Warden Stanley Chilcott|Harry Chilcott]]}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Liverpool West Derby (UK Parliament constituency)|Member of Parliament for Liverpool West Derby]]\n| years = 1918\u20131919\n| before = [[Sir William Rutherford, 1st Baronet|William Rutherford]]\n| after = [[Reginald Hall|Sir Reginald Hall]]\n}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stanley Buckmaster, 1st Viscount Buckmaster|Sir Stanley Buckmaster]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Solicitor General for England and Wales]] | years=1915}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[George Cave, 1st Viscount Cave|Sir George Cave]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Edward Carson, Baron Carson|Sir Edward Carson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Attorney General for England and Wales]] | years=1915\u20131919}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Gordon Hewart, 1st Viscount Hewart|Sir Gordon Hewart]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Robert Finlay, 1st Viscount Finlay|The Lord Finlay]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lord Chancellor|Lord High Chancellor of Great Britain]] | years=1919\u20131922}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[George Cave, 1st Viscount Cave|The Viscount Cave]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sydney Olivier, 1st Baron Olivier|The Lord Olivier]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for India]] | years=1924\u20131928}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[William Peel, 1st Earl Peel|The Viscount Peel]]}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bonar Law]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Rector of the University of Glasgow]] | years=1922\u20131925}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Austen Chamberlain]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Robert Cecil, 1st Viscount Cecil of Chelwood|Viscount Cecil of Chelwood]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Rector of the University of Aberdeen]] | years=1927\u20131930}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Arthur Keith]]}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{s-new | rows= 3 | creation }}\n{{s-ttl | title= [[Earl of Birkenhead]]'''<br>and ''Viscount Furneaux'' | years= '''1922\u20131930 }}\n{{s-aft | rows= 3 | after=[[Frederick Smith, 2nd Earl of Birkenhead|Frederick Winston Furneaux Smith]] }}\n|-\n{{s-ttl | title= [[Viscount Birkenhead]] | years= 1921\u20131930 }}\n|-\n{{s-ttl | title= [[Baron Birkenhead]] | years= 1919\u20131930 }}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Samuel George Blythe]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of People on the Cover of Time Magazine: 1920s|Cover of Time Magazine]]\n| years=20 August 1923}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Frederick G. Banting]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Lord Chancellor}}\n{{Rectors of the University of Aberdeen}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Birkenhead, Frederick Edwin Smith, 1st Earl}}\n[[Category:Lord Chancellors of Great Britain|Birkenhead, F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of]]\n[[Category:British Secretaries of State|Birkenhead, F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State for India|Birkenhead, F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies|Smith, F. E.]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Oxford Union]]\n[[Category:People educated at Birkenhead School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Wadham College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Merton College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:English barristers]]\n[[Category:Members of Gray's Inn]]\n[[Category:Rectors of the University of Glasgow|Birkenhead, F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of]]\n[[Category:Rectors of the University of Aberdeen|Birkenhead, F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of]]\n[[Category:People from Birkenhead|Birkenhead, F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of]]\n[[Category:Earls in the Peerage of the United Kingdom|Birkenhead, F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of the United Kingdom|Smith, F. E.]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Commander of the Order of the Star of India|Birkenhead, F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of]]\n[[Category:1872 births|Birkenhead, F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of]]\n[[Category:1930 deaths|Birkenhead, F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of]]\n[[Category:Solicitors General for England and Wales|Smith, F. E.]]\n[[Category:Attorneys General for England and Wales|Smith, F. E.]]\n[[Category:Queen's Counsel 1901\u20132000]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1906\u20131910|Smith, F. E.]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910|Smith, F. E.]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918|Smith, F. E.]]\n[[Category:People of the Victorian era]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Liverpool constituencies|Smith, F. E.]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Legal scholars of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:Queen's Own Oxfordshire Hussars officers]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Members of the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the author of \"633 Squadron\"|Frederick E. Smith}}\n{{short description|British politician}}\n{{short description|British politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Earl of Birkenhead\n| honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|GCSI|PC|DL}}\n| image        = 1stEarlOfBirkenhead.jpg\n| order1       = [[Secretary of State for India]]\n| term_start1  = 6 November 1924\n| term_end1    = 18 October 1928\n| monarch1     = [[George V]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Stanley Baldwin]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Sydney Olivier, 1st Baron Olivier|The Lord Olivier]]\n| successor1   = [[William Wellesley Peel, 1st Earl Peel|The Viscount Peel]]\n| order2       = [[Lord Chancellor|Lord High Chancellor of Great Britain]]\n| term_start2  = 10 January 1919\n| term_end2    = 19 October 1922\n| monarch2     = [[George V]]\n| primeminister2 = [[David Lloyd George]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Robert Finlay, 1st Viscount Finlay|The Lord Finlay]]\n| successor2   = [[George Cave, 1st Viscount Cave|The Viscount Cave]]\n| order3       = [[Attorney General for England and Wales]]\n| term_start3  = 3 November 1915\n| term_end3    = 10 January 1919\n| predecessor3 = [[Edward Carson, Baron Carson|Sir Edward Carson]]\n| successor3 = [[Gordon Hewart, 1st Viscount Hewart|Sir Gordon Hewart]]\n| monarch3     = [[George V]]\n| primeminister3 = [[H. H. Asquith]]\n| order4 = [[Solicitor General for England and Wales]]\n| term_start4 = 2 June 1915\n| term_end4 = 8 November 1915\n| predecessor4 = [[Stanley Buckmaster, 1st Viscount Buckmaster|Sir Stanley Buckmaster]]\n| successor4 = [[George Cave, 1st Viscount Cave|Sir George Cave]]\n| monarch4     = [[George V]]\n| primeminister4 = [[H. H. Asquith]]\n|office8         = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start8     = 3 February 1919\n|term_end8       = 30 September 1930<br>[[Hereditary Peerage]]\n|predecessor8    = ''[[Earl of Birkenhead|Peerage created]]''\n|successor8      = [[Frederick Smith, 2nd Earl of Birkenhead|The 2nd Earl of Birkenhead]]\n| office9 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br/>for [[Liverpool Walton (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Walton]]\n| term_start9    =  8 February 1906\n| term_end9      =  14 December 1918\n| predecessor9   =  [[James Henry Stock]]\n| successor9     =  Harry Chilcott\n| birth_name = Frederick Edwin Smith\n| birth_date = {{birth-date|12 July 1872|}}\n| birth_place = [[Birkenhead]], Cheshire\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1930|9|30|1872|7|12}}\n| death_place = [[Grosvenor Gardens, London|Grosvenor Gardens]], London\n| nationality = British\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| education = [[University of Liverpool]]<br>[[Wadham College, Oxford]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Margaret Eleanor Furneaux<br>|1901|30 September 1930|end=his death}}\n| children = Lady [[Eleanor Smith (writer)|Eleanor Smith]] (1902\u20131945)<br>[[Frederick Winston Furneaux-Smith, 2nd Earl of Birkenhead]] (1907\u20131975)<br>[[Pamela Smith|Lady Pamela Smith]] (1915\u20131982)\n}}\n\n'''Frederick Edwin Smith, 1st Earl of Birkenhead''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|GCSI|PC|DL}} (12 July 1872 \u2013 30 September 1930), known as '''F. E. Smith''', was a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician and barrister who attained high office in the early 20th century, in particular as [[Lord Chancellor|Lord High Chancellor of Great Britain]]. He was a skilled [[orator]], noted for his staunch opposition to [[Irish nationalism]], his wit, pugnacious views, and hard living and drinking. He is perhaps best remembered today as [[Winston Churchill]]'s greatest personal and political friend until Birkenhead's death aged 58 from pneumonia caused by cirrhosis of the liver.\n\n==Early life and schooling==\nSmith was born at 38 Pilgrim Street, [[Birkenhead]] in [[Cheshire]], the eldest son and second of five surviving children of Frederick Smith (1845-1888) and Elizabeth (1842\u20131928), daughter of Edwin Taylor a rate collector, of Birkenhead.<ref name=\"oxforddnb.com\">http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/odnb/9780192683120.001.0001/odnb-9780192683120-e-36137</ref><ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Schuster |first=Claud |authorlink=Claud Schuster, 1st Baron Schuster |year= |title=The Post Victorians: Lord Birkenhead |place= |publisher= |page=85}}{{clarify |reason=Who published this book, where and when? |date=March 2018}}</ref> His father had joined the family business as an estate agent, later becoming a barrister and local Tory politician. Frederick Smith senior died at the age of forty-three, only a month after being elected mayor of Birkenhead.<ref name=\"oxforddnb.com\"/><ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref>\n\nSmith was educated first at a [[dame school]] in Birkenhead, then at Sandringham School in [[Southport]] (where he announced, at the age of ten, his ambition to become lord chancellor), and then, having failed the entrance exam for [[Harrow School]], at Birkenhead School (1887\u20131889).<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref>\n\n==Oxford==\nSmith won a scholarship to [[University of Liverpool|University College, Liverpool]], where he spent four terms (a fact he subsequently suppressed).<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref>\n\nHe won a scholarship to [[Wadham College, Oxford]], in 1891.<ref name=odnb1>{{cite book |last=Campbell |first=John |title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |volume=51 |year=2004 |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=113 |isbn=0-19-861401-2}}</ref> Smith made his name as an Oxford \u201cswell\u201d, distinguishing himself by his dark good looks, his energy, his unashamed ambition and his scathing wit. He was the dominant figure of a group of Wadham contemporaries including the athlete [[C. B. Fry]], the future Liberal politician [[John Simon, 1st Viscount Simon|John Simon]], and the Liberal economist [[Francis Hirst]]. Between them they dominated both the rugby field and the [[Oxford Union Society]].<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref>\n\nSmith was already active in national politics as a Tory speaker in the [[1892 United Kingdom general election|July 1892 general election]]. Announced initially as his father's son, he spoke all over Lancashire, stirring up Orange opinion against the Liberal policy of [[Irish home rule]].<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref>\n\nHe obtained a [[British undergraduate degree classification|Second Class]] in [[Honour Moderations|Classical Mods]] before switching to Law. He often debated against [[Hilaire Belloc]] at the Oxford Union, where a bust of him now stands, and became [[List of presidents of the Oxford Union|President]] in Trinity (summer) term 1894. By massive last-minute cramming he graduated with a first class BA degree in law in 1895.<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref>\n\nTo his disappointment, he only obtained a Second in his [[Bachelor of Civil Law]] degree. In 1896 he won the [[Vinerian Scholarship|Vinerian law scholarship]] and was elected a fellow of [[Merton College, Oxford|Merton College]] (1896\u20139), and also a lecturership at [[Oriel College, Oxford|Oriel College]].<ref name=compeerage>{{cite book |title=The Complete Peerage, Volume XIII, Peerage Creations 1901\u20131938 |year=1940 |place= |publisher=St Catherine's Press |page=293}}</ref><ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref> The F.E. Smith Memorial Mooting Prizes nowadays commemorate him at [[Merton College, Oxford|Merton]]. In later life his depth of legal learning often surprised critics.<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref>\n\nSmith added to his Oxford reputation in May 1897, when he went to see [[Edward VII|the Prince of Wales]] open the new [[Oxford Town Hall]].  A detachment of the [[Metropolitan Police Mounted Branch]] had been drafted in to reinforce the small [[Oxford City Police]] force against a large demonstration of University undergraduates. The Metropolitan police, who were unused to boisterous Oxford undergraduates, attacked them with batons, causing several serious injuries. The crowd unhorsed and trampled one policeman.<ref name=Rose>{{cite book |last=Rose |first=Geoff |year=1979 |title=A Pictorial History of the Oxford City Police |place=Oxford |publisher=Oxford Publishing Co |isbn=0-86093-094-7 |page=5}}</ref> Smith took no part in the disorder, but was arrested when he tried to rescue his college servant, who was being manhandled by the police. Smith became the first prisoner in the police station in the new Town Hall. Before being locked in, Smith raised his hands for silence and declared \"I have great pleasure in declaring this cell open\". He was tried for obstructing the police in the lawful execution of their duty, but was found not guilty after defending himself in court.<ref name=\"Rose\" />\n\n==Career as a barrister==\nHaving eaten his dinners at [[Gray's Inn]] and passed his bar finals with distinction in the summer of 1899, Smith was [[called to the Bar]] and finally left [[University of Oxford|Oxford]], and quickly built up a brilliant and lucrative practice on the [[Northern Circuit]], initially basing himself in [[Liverpool]].<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref>\n\nSmith married Margaret Eleanor Furneaux, daughter of classical scholar [[Henry Furneaux]], in April 1901 and they had three children, [[Eleanor Smith (writer)|Eleanor Smith]], [[Frederick Winston Furneaux-Smith, 2nd Earl of Birkenhead|Frederick]] and [[Pamela Smith]].\n\nSmith rapidly acquired a reputation as a formidable [[advocate]], first in Liverpool and then, after his election to Parliament in 1906, in [[London]]. In 1907 he was asked to give an opinion on a proposed [[libel]] action by the [[Lever Brothers]] against newspapers owned by [[Lord Northcliffe]] concerning the latter's allegations of a conspiracy to raise the price of soap by means of a 'soap trust'. He checked into the [[Savoy Hotel|Savoy]] and, after working all night reading a pile of papers nearly four feet thick and consuming a bottle of champagne and two dozen oysters, Smith wrote a one-sentence opinion: \"There is no [[defense (legal)|answer]] to this action in libel, and the damages must be enormous\".<ref>{{cite journal |last=Johnson |first=Paul |authorlink=Paul Johnson (writer) |title=The age of stout hearts, sharp swords \u2014 and fun |journal=The Spectator |place=London |date=15 March 2006 |url= http://www.spectator.co.uk/2006/04/the-age-of-stout-hearts-sharp-swords-and-fun/}}</ref><ref>Judgment in ''Cox v. MGN Ltd'' [2006] EWHC 1235, \u00a7&nbsp;32 (Eady J)</ref> The newspapers subsequently paid Lever \u00a350,000, more than four times the previous record for a defamation action or out-of-court published settlement in the country.\n\nIn February 1908, Smith was made a [[King's Counsel]] by [[Robert Reid, 1st Earl Loreburn|Lord Loreburn]], on the same day as his friend and rival from Wadham College, future Home Secretary Sir [[John Simon, 1st Viscount Simon|John Simon]].\n\nAt the Bar, he became one of the best known and most highly paid barristers in the country, making over \u00a310,000 per year before the First World War. His spending was commensurate with this income even after he took less well-paid government positions in later years, something of which he would bitterly complain.\n\nIn one of the best-known cases in which Smith was involved he successfully defended [[Ethel le Neve]], mistress of [[Hawley Harvey Crippen]] (\"Dr Crippen\") against a charge of murder. Le Neve was accused of killing Crippen's wife. Crippen was tried separately and convicted.\n\n==Member of Parliament==\n[[File:Birkenhead by Spy0002.jpg|thumb|upright|<center>\"A Successful First Speech (\"[[Psalm 108|Moab is my Washpot]]\")\"<br>FE Smith MP depicted in ''[[Vanity Fair (UK magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', January 1907</center>]]\nAmbitious to enter [[British House of Commons|Parliament]], Smith cultivated the local Tory [[Political boss|boss]] [[Archibald Salvidge]].<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref> He stood unsuccessfully in Liverpool, for [[Liverpool Scotland (UK Parliament constituency)|Scotland division]] in a by-election in 1903.<ref name=compeerage/><ref name=EB1922>{{Cite EB1922 |wstitle=Birkenhead, Frederick Edwin Smith, 1st Viscount |volume=30 |page=457}}</ref>\n\nIn 1903, Smith gave a dazzling speech in Liverpool in support of [[Joseph Chamberlain]], who was campaigning for [[Tariff Reform]]. On the strength of this, he was selected three months later as candidate for the working-class constituency of [[Liverpool Walton (UK Parliament constituency)|Walton division]].<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref> He stood, again unsuccessfully, for Walton in another by-election in 1905.<ref name=compeerage/><ref name=EB1922>{{Cite EB1922 |wstitle=Birkenhead, Frederick Edwin Smith, 1st Viscount |volume=30 |page=457}}</ref> He campaigned as the champion of hard-drinking, patriotic working men (Liberals tended to favour temperance and more pacific foreign policy) and in the [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906 election]] he narrowly held the seat despite the national Liberal landslide. He held the seat until the redrawing of boundaries in 1918.<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id = 36137|title = Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930)|first = John|last = Campbell|authorlink = John Campbell (biographer)}}</ref>\n\nHe attracted attention by a brilliant [[maiden speech]], \"[[I warn the Government]]...\" After this speech, [[Timothy Michael Healy|Tim Healy]], the Irish Nationalist, a master of parliamentary invective, sent Smith a note, \"I am old, and you are young, but you have beaten me at my own game.\" In his maiden speech he argued that advocating tariffs had not hurt the Tories at the recent election.<ref>Harris 2013, p.244</ref> Smith also opposed the [[Trade Disputes Act 1906]] arguing that intimidatory picketing should not be allowed. The Conservative leadership, unwilling to antagonise organised labour, did not oppose the Act very hard.<ref>Harris 2013, p.244</ref>\n\nSmith did not support restriction on the powers of the [[House of Lords]], fearing that tyranny could result from an unchecked [[unicameral]] parliament.\n\nHe was soon a prominent leader of the [[Unionism (Ireland)|Unionist]] wing of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]], especially in the planned [[Ulster]] resistance to [[Irish Home Rule]]. He attended the Blenheim Palace rally on 27 July 1912, at which Bonar Law advocated forcible resistance. From the signing of the [[Ulster Covenant]] in September 1912 onwards, he was often on [[Edward Carson]]\u2019s side on horseback, hence the derisive nickname \u201cGalloper Smith\u201d.<ref>Harris 2013, pp.255-6</ref>\n\nA vociferous opponent of the [[Disestablishmentarianism|Disestablishment]] of the [[Church in Wales|Welsh part of the Church of England]], he called the [[Welsh Church Act 1914|Welsh Disestablishment Bill]] \"a bill which has shocked the conscience of every Christian community in Europe\". This prompted [[G. K. Chesterton]] to write a satirical poem, [[s:Antichrist, or the Reunion of Christendom: An Ode|''\u201cAntichrist, Or the Reunion of Christendom: An Ode\u201d'']], which asked if [[Brittany|Breton]] sailors, Russian peasants and Christians evicted by the [[Ottoman Empire|Turks]] would know or care of what happened to the [[Church in Wales|Anglican Church of Wales]], and answered the question with the line \"Chuck it, Smith\". The bill was approved by Parliament under the provisions of the [[Parliament Act 1911]], but its implementation delayed by the outbreak of the [[First World War]]. When it was finally implemented in 1920, Smith was part of the [[Lloyd George Coalition Government|Lloyd George Coalition]] that did so.\n\n==First World War==\nSmith had joined the [[Territorial Army (United Kingdom)|Territorial Army]] by commission into the [[Queen's Own Oxfordshire Hussars]], in which Churchill was already an officer, in 1913,<ref name=compeerage/> and was a [[Captain (British Army)|captain]] in the regiment<ref name=\"kelly\">{{cite book |title=Kelly's Handbook to the Titled, Landed and Official Classes, 1930 |place= |publisher=Kelly's |page=239}}</ref> before the outbreak of the First World War. On its outbreak he was placed in charge of the Government's Press Bureau, with rank of full colonel and responsibility for newspaper censorship. He was not very successful in this role, and in 1914\u20131915 served in France as a staff officer with the [[Indian Corps]] with ultimate temporary rank of [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|lieutenant-colonel]].<ref name=\"kelly\"/> He and his successor as 'recording officer' (a [[Colonel (British Army)|Colonel]] Merewether) later collaborated on an official history entitled ''The Indian Corps in France'' (published 1917).<ref name=compeerage2>{{cite book |title=The Complete Peerage, Volume XIII |place= |publisher= |page=294}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1915, he was appointed [[Solicitor General for England and Wales|Solicitor General]] by [[Herbert Henry Asquith|H. H. Asquith]] and [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]].<ref name=EB1922/> He soon after (in October 1915) succeeded his friend [[Edward Carson|Sir Edward Carson]] as [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Attorney General]],<ref name=EB1922/> with the right to attend Cabinet. Early in 1916 he was briefly placed under military arrest for arriving at [[Boulogne]] without a pass, and had to be 'appeased' by a meeting with [[General (United Kingdom)|General]] [[Douglas Haig, 1st Earl Haig|Sir Douglas Haig]].<ref>Groot 1988, p.226</ref>\n\nAs [[Attorney General of England and Wales|Attorney General]], it was his responsibility to lead the prosecution for [[the Crown]] in major cases such as the trial in 1916 of the [[Irish nationalist]] [[Sir Roger Casement]] for [[Treason in the United Kingdom|treason]].<ref name=EB1922/> Sir Roger had been captured after landing from [[SM U-19 (Germany)|a ''Kaiserliche Marine'' U-boat]] on [[Banna Strand]] in [[Tralee Bay]] in north [[County Kerry]], south-west Ireland, just a few days before the [[Easter Rising]] in late April 1916.<ref>Martin Green, \"Children of the Sun: A Narrative of Decadence in England After 1918\"</ref> His prosecution of Casement (and [[Alice Wheeldon|Wheeldon]] in 1917) contributed to Smith's reputation as a spectacular advocate at the time.<ref>Watson Andrew (2019), 'A spectacular quartet of leading barristers' in ''Speaking in Court.'' Palgrave Macmillan.https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-10395-8_8</ref>\n\nSmith was made a [[baronet]] in 1918. Following abolition of the Walton seat in constituency boundary changes, Smith was returned at the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|December 1918 general election]] for neighbouring [[Liverpool West Derby (UK Parliament constituency)|West Derby Division]], only to be elevated to the House of Lords two months later.<ref name=\"odnb4\">{{cite book|title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Volume 51|pages=116}}</ref>\n\n==Postwar Coalition: Lord Chancellor==\n[[File:F. E. Smith as Lord Chancellor.jpg|thumb|upright|Sir F. E. Smith, newly created [[Earl of Birkenhead|Lord Birkenhead]], on his appointment as [[Lord Chancellor]]]]\nIn 1919, he was created '''Baron Birkenhead''', of Birkenhead in the County of Cheshire following his appointment as [[Lord Chancellor]] by [[David Lloyd George|Lloyd George]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31201|page=2735|date=25 February 1919}}</ref> At the age of 47, he was the youngest Lord Chancellor since [[George Jeffreys, 1st Baron Jeffreys|Judge Jeffreys]].{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} The ''[[Morning Post]]'' dismissed his appointment as \"carrying a joke beyond the limits of pleasantry\", while the [[George V|King]] urged Lloyd George to reconsider.{{sfn|Campbell|1991|p=460}} Birkenhead proved an excellent Lord Chancellor, but tales of his drunkenness begin from this time, very likely as he grew bored with the job and as it dawned on him that he had probably ruled himself out from the premiership by accepting a peerage.{{sfn|Harris|2013|pp=277-81}}\n\nThat year, in the House of Lords debate on the [[Amritsar Massacre]], he courageously denounced Tories who declared [[Reginald Dyer|General Dyer]] (the responsible officer) a hero.<ref name=odnb3>{{cite book |title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |volume=51 |page=117}}</ref> He played a key role in the passage of several key legal reforms, including the reform of English land law which was to come to fruition in [[Law of Property Act 1925|the mid-1920s]].{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} He also unsuccessfully championed a reform of the divorce laws, which he judged caused great misery and which favoured the wealthy.\n\nDespite his Unionist background, Smith played an important role in the negotiations that led to the signature of the [[Anglo-Irish Treaty]] in 1921, which led to the formation of the [[Irish Free State]] the following year.{{sfn|Harris|2013|pp=275}} Much of the treaty was drafted by Smith. His support for this, and his warm relations with the Irish nationalist leaders [[Arthur Griffith]] and [[Michael Collins (Irish leader)|Michael Collins]], angered some of his former Unionist associates, notably Sir Edward Carson. Upon signing the Treaty he remarked to Collins, \"I may have just signed my political death warrant\", to which Collins dryly and with prescient accuracy replied, \"I have just signed my actual death warrant\". Collins was killed by opponents of the treaty eight months after the signing, during the [[Irish Civil War]].{{sfn|Aitken|1963|pp=96\u2013123}}\n\nAlso in 1921, he was responsible for the [[House of Lords]] rejecting a proposal, put forward by [[Frederick Alexander Macquisten]], MP for [[Argyllshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Argyllshire]], to criminalise lesbianism. During the debate, Birkenhead argued that 999 women out of a thousand had \"never even heard a whisper of these practices\".<ref>{{cite book |last=Doan |first=Laura |title=Fashioning Sapphism: The Origins of a Modern English Lesbian Culture |url=https://archive.org/details/fashioningsapphi00doan |url-access=registration |publisher=Columbia University Press |year=2001 |place=New York |isbn=0-231-11007-3 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/fashioningsapphi00doan/page/56 56\u201360]}}</ref><ref>{{cite hansard |jurisdiction=UK |title=Commons Amdendment, HL Deb 15 August 1921 vol 43 cc567-77 |url= http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1921/aug/15/commons-amendment-2#S5LV0043P0_19210815_HOL_114 |house=House of Lords |date=15 August 1921 |column=574 |speaker=The Lord Chancellor |position=574}}</ref>\n\nSmith was created '''Viscount Birkenhead''', of Birkenhead in the [[County of Chester]], in the [[1921 Birthday Honours]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=32346 |date=4 June 1921 |page=4529 |supp=y}}</ref> then '''Viscount Furneaux''', of [[Charlton, Northamptonshire|Charlton]] in the [[County of Northampton]], and '''Earl of Birkenhead''' in 1922. By 1922 Birkenhead and Churchill had become the leading figures of the [[David Lloyd George|Lloyd George]] Coalition. The [[Anglo-Irish Treaty]], the attempt to go to war with [[Turkey]] over [[Chanak Crisis|Chanak]] (which was later vetoed by the governments of the Dominions) and a general whiff of moral and financial corruption which had come to surround the Coalition were all hallmarks of his tenure in office.\n\nA scandal erupted in 1922 when it became known that Lloyd George, through the agency of [[Maundy Gregory]],<ref name=camp/> had awarded honours and titles such as a baronetcy to rich businessmen in return for cash in the range of \u00a310,000 and more.<ref>{{cite book |first=Travis L |last=Crosby |title=The Unknown David Lloyd George: A Statesman in Conflict |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=MIW9AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA330 |year=2014 |place= |publisher=IB Tauris |page=330 |isbn=978-1-78076-485-6}}</ref> At an earlier meeting before Parliament broke up for the summer, and more famously at the [[Carlton Club]] meeting in October 1922, Birkenhead's hectoring of the junior ministers and backbenchers was one of the factors leading to the withdrawal of support from the Coalition.{{sfn|Aitken|1963|pp=200\u2013203}}\n\n==Out of office: 1922-24==\nLike many of the senior members of the Coalition, Birkenhead did not hold office in the [[Bonar Law]] and Baldwin governments of 1922\u201324. Unlike the others Birkenhead was rude and open in his contempt for the new governments. He bore no grudge against Bonar Law but criticised [[Leslie Wilson (politician)|Leslie Wilson]] and Lord Curzon. He sneered that Wilson and Sir [[George Younger, 1st Viscount Younger of Leckie|George Younger]] were \"the cabin boys\" who had taken over the ship, he referred to [[James Gascoyne-Cecil, 4th Marquess of Salisbury|Lords Salisbury]] and [[Lord Selborne|Selborne]] as \"the [[Dolly Sisters]]\" after two starlets of the era and remarked that the new Cabinet was one of \"second-class brains\", to which came the reply from [[Robert Cecil, 1st Viscount Cecil of Chelwood|Lord Robert Cecil]]<ref>the quote is also sometimes attributed to Stanley Baldwin</ref> that this was better than \"second-class characters\". He remarked that he had lost the Woolsack but was still \u201ccaptain of [his] own soul\u201d to which a wag retorted that this was \u201ca small command of which no-one will want to deprive him\u201d.<ref>Harris 2013 pp.286-7</ref>\n\nIn the House of Lords he accused the Foreign Secretary [[Lord Curzon]] (who had deserted the Coalition in its final hours and thus retained his office under [[Bonar Law]]) of making unauthorised promises of support to [[Greece]] in her [[Greco-Turkish War (1919\u201322)|war against Turkey]]; he was forced to apologise when Curzon produced the key documents which he had circulated to the Cabinet, and which Birkenhead had initialled as read. [[Grace Curzon, Marchioness Curzon of Kedleston|Lady Curzon]] retaliated by [[Cut (etiquette)|cutting]] Birkenhead at a ball, but as she remarked to her husband in a letter, he was \"too drunk to notice\" the snub.\n\nIn May 1923, [[Stanley Baldwin]] succeeded Bonar Law as Prime Minister. He remarked to his new Cabinet, referring to Birkenhead\u2019s exclusion, that they were \u201ca Cabinet of faithful husbands\u201d \u2013 this referred to Birkenhead\u2019s general character rather than simply his marital infidelities.<ref>Lloyd George and Robert Horne were also notorious womanisers - see their articles for details</ref><ref>Charmley 1993, p. 203</ref>\n\nEven a famous speech, the Rectorial Address to [[Glasgow University]] on 7 November 1923,<ref>\"Idealism in International Politics.\" Reprinted in: ''The Speeches of Lord Birkenhead.'' London, 1929. p. 204-217. According to Paul Johnson (''Heroes: From Alexander the Great and Julius Caesar to Churchill and de Gaulle.'' New York, 2007. p. 207), \"The speech was, in its own way, as sensational as his maiden, and required the same kind of courage.\"</ref> in which Birkenhead told undergraduates that the world still offered \"glittering prizes\" to those with \"stout hearts and sharp swords\", now seemed out of kilter with the less aggressive and more self-consciously moral style of politics advocated by the new generation of Conservative politicians such as Stanley Baldwin and [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Edward Wood]], the future Lord Halifax. Birkenhead regarded the [[League of Nations]] as idealistic nonsense, and thought that international relations should be guided by \u201cself-interest\u201d, lest Britain decline like [[Spanish Empire|Imperial Spain]].<ref>Charmley 1993, pp203-4</ref> Rather, he believed that the power of nations would still be determined by their military strength.<ref>Haris 2013, p.332</ref>\n\nBy this time Birkenhead was regarded with distaste by much of the grassroots Conservative Party. [[J. C. C. Davidson|J.C.C. Davidson]] reported back to [[Conservative Campaign Headquarters|Central Office]] (18 November 1923) on his recent re-adoption as candidate for [[Hemel Hempstead (UK Parliament constituency)|Hemel Hempstead]] that many members were unwilling to support him without an assurance that he would not support Birkenhead\u2019s return to the Cabinet, lest this cost local votes at [[1923 United Kingdom general election|the upcoming election]]. He commented that this was proof that Puritanism was deep in the English blood, and not just in that of Nonconformist chapel-goers. [[Neville Chamberlain]] recorded in his diary (18 November 1923) that Birkenhead had \u201cso often and so deeply shocked the moral sense of the country by his drunkenness and loose living character that our Govt which rests largely on public confidence in our character would be seriously tarnished by association with such a man\u201d.<ref>Charmley 1993, pp203-4 </ref>\n\n==Secretary of State for India: 1924-28==\nAfter the December 1923 General Election, at which Baldwin lost his majority and a hung Parliament was returned, Birkenhead briefly intrigued for another Lloyd George coalition government. In order to discourage them from associating with Lloyd George, Baldwin quickly invited former coalitionists Austen Chamberlain, Birkenhead and Balfour to join the Shadow Cabinet.<ref>Harris 2013, pp.301-2</ref> Birkenhead persuaded his friend Churchill to stand (unsuccessfully, as an independent \u201cConstitutionalist\u201d) in the March [[1924 Westminster Abbey by-election]]. This was part of Churchill's move back towards rejoining the Conservative Party.<ref>Harris 2013, p.303</ref>.\n\nA 1924 entry in [[Evelyn Waugh]]'s diary states that an English High Court judge, presiding in a [[sodomy]] case, sought advice on sentencing from Lord Birkenhead. \"Could you tell me,\" he asked, \"what do you think one ought to give a man who allows himself to be buggered?\" Birkenhead replied without hesitation, \"Oh, thirty shillings or two pounds; whatever you happen to have on you.\"<ref>Cited in ''[[The Times]]'' 23 May 2006, Law supplement p.7</ref>\n\nDespite winning a large majority at the [[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924 election]], Baldwin formed a broad new (second) government by appointing former coalitionists such as Birkenhead, Austen Chamberlain and former Liberal Winston Churchill to senior Cabinet posts; this was to discourage them from associating with Lloyd George to revive the 1916-22 Coalition.<ref>Charmley 1993, pp. 202-3</ref> Birkenhead and Chamberlain lobbied Baldwin to reappoint another former coalitionist, [[Robert Horne, 1st Viscount Horne of Slamannan|Robert Horne]], to the Exchequer, but Baldwin refused and appointed Churchill instead.<ref>Charmley 1993, p. 200</ref> \n\nFrom 1924 to 1928 Birkenhead served as [[Secretary of State for India]]. His views on pre-partition India's independence movement were gloomy. He thought India's Hindu-Muslim religious divide insurmountable and sought to block advances in native participation in provincial governments that had been granted by the 1919 [[Montagu-Chelmsford Reforms]]. His parliamentary private secretary recalled much time ostensibly on India Office business seemed to be spent playing [[golf]].<ref name=odnb2>{{cite book |title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |volume=51 |page=118}}</ref>\n\nBirkenhead endorsed his old political opponent [[H.H. Asquith]], rather than his Cabinet colleague [[George Cave, 1st Viscount Cave|Lord Cave]], in the [[1925 University of Oxford Chancellor election]]. He wrote to ''[[The Times]]'' on 19 May, describing Asquith as the \u201cgreatest living Oxonian\u201d, but his support may have done more harm than good, because of his association with the discredited Lloyd George Coalition, and because of his open scepticism both of religion and of the League of Nations. It was quipped that Asquith was \u201ca [[Bed warmer|warming-pan]]\u201d for Birkenhead\u2019s views (a learned Oxford joke, referring to the legend that the [[James Francis Edward Stuart|Old Pretender]] had been an impostor baby rather than a rightful heir to the throne). Lord Cave was elected.<ref>Koss 1985, pp. 274-275</ref>\n\nHe was engaged outside the office in negotiating for the government with the [[Trades Union Congress]] to try to avert the [[1926 General Strike]] and he strongly supported the 1927 [[Trade Disputes and Trade Unions Act 1927|Trades Disputes Act]] which required union members to contract into the political levies.<ref name=odnb2/> It was in his government role that in October 1927 he unveiled the [[Neuve-Chapelle Indian Memorial]] to Indian Army soldiers of no known grave killed on the Western Front in the 1914\u201318 War.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.cwgc.org/find-a-cemetery/cemetery/144000/NEUVE%20CHAPELLE%20MEMORIAL |title=Neuve-Chapelle Memorial |publisher=[[Commonwealth War Graves Commission|CWGC]] |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nLord Cave resigned as Lord Chancellor early in 1928. Birkenhead apparently did not want to return to his old job, but neither did Baldwin offer it to him. According to Neville Chamberlain\u2019s diary (28 March 1928), this was because \u201che might be seen drunk in the street\u201d ([[Douglas Hogg, 1st Viscount Hailsham|Lord Hailsham]] was appointed instead).<ref>Charmley 1993, pp. 232-3</ref> Birkenhead retired from the Cabinet in October 1928 to make money in business.<ref>Charmley p.234</ref>\n\n==Later life and assessments==\nBirkenhead's increasingly pompous oratory caused [[David Low (cartoonist)|David Low]] to caricature him in the 1920s as \"Lord Burstinghead\".<ref name=odnb3/> After retiring from politics, he became Rector of the [[University of Aberdeen]], a director of [[Tate & Lyle]],{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} a director of [[Imperial Chemical Industries]],<ref name=camp/> and [[High Steward (academia)|High Steward]] of the [[University of Oxford]]. In a 1983 biography review, William Camp \u2014 who had written a 1960 biography of the man \u2014 opined that \"F.E. was the quintessential male chauvinist who, almost with his dying breath, dragged himself to the Lords in July 1930 to attack the right of peeresses to take their seats.\"<ref name=camp>{{cite news |url= http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/26th-november-1983/26/that-crooked-charmer-smith |title=That crooked charmer, Smith |newspaper=The Spectator |date=26 Nov 1983 |page=26}}</ref>\n\nBirkenhead wrote a series of articles (later republished in ''Last Essays'': 1930) about \"the peril to India\", in which he criticised the Indian Nationalist leaders as \"a collection ... of very inferior [[Alexander Kerensky|Kerenskis]]\" and asserted that it was widely accepted that without British rule India would collapse into anarchy. He attacked the [[Edward Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Irwin Declaration]] as \"so ambiguous that it is impossible to select from it any clear and unambiguous proposal\".<ref>Charmley 1993, p.245</ref>\n\nIn the opinion of [[Winston Churchill]], who was a friend: \"He had all the canine virtues in a remarkable degree \u2013 courage, fidelity, vigilance, love of chase.\" As for [[Margot Asquith]], who was not a friend, she thought: \"F. E. Smith is very clever, but sometimes his brains go to his head.\" Of Birkenhead's loyalty, Churchill added: \"If he was with you on Monday, he would be the same on Tuesday. And on Thursday, when things looked blue, he would still be marching forward with strong reinforcements.\"\n\n[[Gilbert Frankau]] recalled in his own autobiography ''Self Portrait'', that in 1928 [[Thomas Horder, 1st Baron Horder|Sir Thomas Horder]] confided: \"Birkenhead's pure eighteenth-century. He belongs to the days of [[Charles James Fox|Fox]] and [[William Pitt the younger|Pitt]]. Physically, he has all the strength of our best yeoman stock. Mentally, he's a colossus. But he'll tear himself to pieces by the time he's sixty.\"<ref name=frankau>{{cite book |last=Frankau |first=Gilbert |title=Self Portrait, A Novel of His Own Life |year=1941 |place= |publisher=The Book Club |pages=262\u2013263}}</ref>\n\nBirkenhead died in London aged 58 from [[pneumonia]] caused by [[cirrhosis of the liver]]. After cremation at [[Golders Green Crematorium]], his ashes were buried in the parish churchyard at [[Charlton, Northamptonshire]].<ref name=\"odnb2\"/>\n\n===Commemoration===\nAs \"Lord Birkenhead\", he is dramatised in the film ''[[Chariots of Fire]]'', as an official of the [[British Olympic Committee]]. He is played by actor [[Nigel Davenport]].\n\nIn the year of his death, he published his utopian ''The World in 2030 A.D.'' with airbrush illustrations by [[E. McKnight Kauffer]].<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.fulltable.com/VTS/f/fut/t.htm |last=McKnight Kauffer |first=E |title=The World in 2030 |website=fulltable.com |accessdate=}}</ref> The book was the subject of considerable controversy as several passages were alleged to have been copied from earlier works by [[J. B. S. Haldane]].{{sfn|Campbell|1991|p=828}}\n\n==Works==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* ''International Law in the Far East'', 2nd ed. 1908.\n* ''The Licensing Bill'', 1908.\n* ''International Law'', 4th ed. 1911.\n* ''Poems by Samuel Johnson, LLD''.\n* ''Toryism until 1832''.\n* ''Speeches, 1906\u20131909'' (2nd ed.).\n* ''The Destruction of Merchant Ships'', 1917.\n* ''My American Visit'', 1918 (2nd edition).\n* ''The Indian Corps in France'' (2nd edition).\n* ''The Story of Newfoundland'', 1920.\n* ''Points of View'', 1922.\n* ''Contemporary Personalities'', 1924.\n* ''America Revisited'', 1924.\n{{col-2}}\n* ''Fourteen English Judges'', 1926.\n* ''Famous Trials of History'', 1926.\n* ''Law, Life and Letters'', 1927.\n* ''More Famous Trials'', 1928.\n* ''The Speeches of Lord Birkenhead'', 1929.\n* ''The World in 2030 AD'', 1930.\n* ''Turning Points in History'', 1930.\n* ''Last Essays'', 1930.\n* (Editor) ''The Five Hundred Best English Letters'', 1931.\n* ''Fifty Famous Fights in Fact and Fiction'', 1932.\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Cases==\n===As counsel===\n* ''R v Casement'' [1917] 1 KB 98, prosecution of [[Roger Casement|Sir Roger Casement]] for [[High treason in the United Kingdom|high treason]]\n\n===As judge===\n* ''[[Margaret Mackworth, 2nd Viscountess Rhondda|Viscountess Rhondda]]'s Claim'' [1922] 2 AC 339, right of peeresses to sit in the [[House of Lords]]\n* [[R v Secretary of State for Home Affairs, ex p O'Brien|R ''v Secretary of State for Home Affairs, ex p O'Brien'']] [1923] AC 691, legality of British policy of internment in Ireland\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = [[File:Coronet of a British Earl.svg|centre|150px]][[File:Birkenhead Escutcheon.png|centre|200px]]\n|escutcheon = Ermine on a pale Gules between four cross crosslets of the second a like cross Or.\n|crest = A cubit arm couped fessways vested Gules cuffed Argent the hand Proper grasping a sword erect also Argent pommel and hilt Or.\n|supporters = Dexter a griffin Or wings per fess Or and Sable, sinister a lion Azure charged on the shoulder with a crozier Or.\n|motto = Faber Me\u00e6 Fortun\u00e6 <ref>{{cite book|title=Burke's Peerage |date=1959}}</ref>}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite book |last=Aitken |first=Max |authorlink=Max Aitken, 1st Baron Beaverbrook |year=1963 |title=The Decline and Fall of Lloyd George |place=London |publisher=Collins}}\n*{{cite book |last=Camp |first=William |year=1960 |title=The Glittering Prizes: A Biographical Study of F. E. Smith |place=London |publisher=MacGibbon & Kee}}\n*{{cite book |last=Campbell |first=John |year=1983 |title=F. E. Smith: First Earl of Birkenhead |place=London |publisher=Jonathan Cape |isbn= |ref=harv}}\n*{{ODNBweb |first=John |last=Campbell |title=Smith, Frederick Edwin, first earl of Birkenhead (1872\u20131930) |origyear=2004 |year=2015 |edition=online |id=36137 }}\n* {{citation | last= Charmley | first= John | title=Churchill: The End of Glory | publisher=Sceptre|date=1995 |origyear=1993| isbn=978- 0340599228}}\n*{{cite book |last=De Groot |first=Gerard |year=|title=Douglas Haig 1861\u20131928 |place=Larkfield, Maidstone |publisher=Unwin Hyman |isbn=}}\n* {{citation | last= Harris | first= Robin | title=The Conservatives - A History | publisher=Corgi|date=2013 | isbn=978-0552170338}}\n*{{cite book |last=Heuston |first=RVF |year=1964 |title=Lives of the Lord Chancellors 1885\u20131940 |url=https://archive.org/details/livesoflordchanc0000heus |url-access=registration |place=Oxford |publisher=Clarendon Press}}\n* {{cite book | last = Koss | first = Stephen | authorlink = Stephen Koss | year = 1985 | title = Asquith | url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=tBGGAAAAIAAJ&dq=Asquith+Stephen+Koss&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj09Ya9-LbOAhXlLMAKHaOeCCQQ6AEIKzAA | location = London | publisher = Hamish Hamilton | isbn = 978-0-231-06155-1| ref = {{sfnRef|Koss}}}}\n*{{cite book |last=Roberts |first=Carl Eric Bechhofer |year=1927 |title=Lord Birkenhead. Being an account of the life of F.E. Smith, first Earl of Birkenhead |place=London |publisher=Mills and Boon}}\n*{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Frederick |authorlink=Frederick Smith, 2nd Earl of Birkenhead |year=1933 |title=Frederick Edwin, Earl of Birkenhead |place=London |publisher=Thornton Butterworth}}\n*{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Frederick |year=1960 |title=F.E.: The Life of F. E. Smith First Earl of Birkenhead |place=London |publisher=Eyre and Spottiswoode}} \u2013 heavily revised edition of the above, with added material on Smith's political career, and much material relating to his legal career excised.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Frederick Edwin Smith, 1st Earl of Birkenhead}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{wikisource author}}\n* {{Gutenberg author |id=Birkenhead,+Frederick+Edwin+Smith,+Earl+of}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Frederick Edwin Smith, 1st Earl of Birkenhead}}\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-fe-smith| F. E. Smith}}\n* {{NPG name|name=F. E. Smith}}\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/016687}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[James Henry Stock]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament for [[Liverpool Walton (UK Parliament constituency)|Liverpool Walton]] | years=[[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]]\u2013[[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Harry Warden Stanley Chilcott|Harry Chilcott]]}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Liverpool West Derby (UK Parliament constituency)|Member of Parliament for Liverpool West Derby]]\n| years = 1918\u20131919\n| before = [[Sir William Rutherford, 1st Baronet|William Rutherford]]\n| after = [[Reginald Hall|Sir Reginald Hall]]\n}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stanley Buckmaster, 1st Viscount Buckmaster|Sir Stanley Buckmaster]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Solicitor General for England and Wales]] | years=1915}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[George Cave, 1st Viscount Cave|Sir George Cave]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Edward Carson, Baron Carson|Sir Edward Carson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Attorney General for England and Wales]] | years=1915\u20131919}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Gordon Hewart, 1st Viscount Hewart|Sir Gordon Hewart]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Robert Finlay, 1st Viscount Finlay|The Lord Finlay]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lord Chancellor|Lord High Chancellor of Great Britain]] | years=1919\u20131922}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[George Cave, 1st Viscount Cave|The Viscount Cave]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sydney Olivier, 1st Baron Olivier|The Lord Olivier]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for India]] | years=1924\u20131928}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[William Peel, 1st Earl Peel|The Viscount Peel]]}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bonar Law]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Rector of the University of Glasgow]] | years=1922\u20131925}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Austen Chamberlain]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Robert Cecil, 1st Viscount Cecil of Chelwood|Viscount Cecil of Chelwood]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Rector of the University of Aberdeen]] | years=1927\u20131930}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Arthur Keith]]}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{s-new | rows= 3 | creation }}\n{{s-ttl | title= [[Earl of Birkenhead]]'''<br>and ''Viscount Furneaux'' | years= '''1922\u20131930 }}\n{{s-aft | rows= 3 | after=[[Frederick Smith, 2nd Earl of Birkenhead|Frederick Winston Furneaux Smith]] }}\n|-\n{{s-ttl | title= [[Viscount Birkenhead]] | years= 1921\u20131930 }}\n|-\n{{s-ttl | title= [[Baron Birkenhead]] | years= 1919\u20131930 }}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Samuel George Blythe]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of People on the Cover of Time Magazine: 1920s|Cover of Time Magazine]]\n| years=20 August 1923}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Frederick G. Banting]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Lord Chancellor}}\n{{Rectors of the University of Aberdeen}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Birkenhead, Frederick Edwin Smith, 1st Earl}}\n[[Category:Lord Chancellors of Great Britain|Birkenhead, F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of]]\n[[Category:British Secretaries of State|Birkenhead, F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State for India|Birkenhead, F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies|Smith, F. E.]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Oxford Union]]\n[[Category:People educated at Birkenhead School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Wadham College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Merton College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:English barristers]]\n[[Category:Members of Gray's Inn]]\n[[Category:Rectors of the University of Glasgow|Birkenhead, F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of]]\n[[Category:Rectors of the University of Aberdeen|Birkenhead, F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of]]\n[[Category:People from Birkenhead|Birkenhead, F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of]]\n[[Category:Earls in the Peerage of the United Kingdom|Birkenhead, F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of the United Kingdom|Smith, F. E.]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Commander of the Order of the Star of India|Birkenhead, F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of]]\n[[Category:1872 births|Birkenhead, F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of]]\n[[Category:1930 deaths|Birkenhead, F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of]]\n[[Category:Solicitors General for England and Wales|Smith, F. E.]]\n[[Category:Attorneys General for England and Wales|Smith, F. E.]]\n[[Category:Queen's Counsel 1901\u20132000]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1906\u20131910|Smith, F. E.]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910|Smith, F. E.]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918|Smith, F. E.]]\n[[Category:People of the Victorian era]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Liverpool constituencies|Smith, F. E.]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Legal scholars of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:Queen's Own Oxfordshire Hussars officers]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Members of the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (5)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F._E._Smith,_1st_Earl_of_Birkenhead"}
{"title_page": "J\u00f3zef Retinger", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Polish diplomat and activist}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger\n|image             = File:Jozef Retinger.jpg\n|image_size        = \n|caption           = J\u00f3zef Retinger, recovering from a poisoning attempt c.1944<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n|birth_date        = {{birth date|1888|04|17|df=y}}\n|birth_place       = [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria]]\n|death_date        = {{death date and age|df=yes|1960|06|12|1888|04|17}}\n|death_place       = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n|citizenship       = Polish\n|nationality       = Polish\n|ethnicity         = \n|field             = Economics, international relations, politics\n|work_institutions = [[Sorbonne University]] Phd, [[London School of Economics]], [[Polish government-in-exile]]\n|doctoral_advisor  =\n|doctoral_students =\n|known_for         = [[Bilderberg Group]], [[European Movement International]]\n|author_abbrev_bot =\n|author_abbrev_zoo =\n|influences        = [[Jesuits]], [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]]\n|influenced        = [[Joseph Conrad]], foundation of [[European Union]], the [[Bilderberg Group]]\n|prizes            = [[Nobel Peace Prize]] Nomination 1958\n|footnotes         =\n|signature         =\n}}\n'''J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger''' ([[Krak\u00f3w]], 17 April 1888 {{spaced ndash}} 12 June 1960, [[London]]; [[World War II]] [[nom de guerre|noms de guerre]] ''Salamandra'', \"Salamander\", and ''Brzoza'', \"Birch Tree\") was a [[Poles|Polish]] diplomat, international political adviser and activist, and writer.<ref name = \"JR\">{{cite book|title=Joseph Retinger - Memoirs of an Eminence Grise|editor=John Pomian|publisher=Sussex University Press/ Chatto & Windus|date= 1972|url=https://ia800905.us.archive.org/5/items/MemoirsOfAnEminenceGrise1972/Memoirs%20of%20an%20Eminence%20Grise%2C%201972.pdf}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[World War I]], Retinger was politically active in [[Austria-Hungary]] and Russia on behalf of the Polish independence movement. After the [[Russian Revolution]], he had to retreat to [[Central America]], where he became an economic adviser. After the outbreak of  [[World War II]], he was principal adviser to the [[Polish government-in-exile]].<ref name=\"Oleks\">{{cite web|title=The Most Mysterious Man in 20th-Century Politics|author=Oleksiak, Wojciech|publisher=Culture.pl|date=2016-12-14|url=https://culture.pl/en/article/the-most-mysterious-man-in-20th-century-politics|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> A Freemason with a reputation as a [[grey eminence]], he went on to cofound the [[European Movement]], which led to establishment of the [[European Union]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pieczewski|first1=Andrzej|title=Joseph Retinger's conception of and contribution to the early process of European integration|journal=European Review of History|date=11 Aug 2010|volume=17|issue=4|pages=581\u2013604|doi=10.1080/13507486.2010.495766}}</ref> and was instrumental in forming the [[Bilderberg Group]]. In 1958 he was nominated for the [[Nobel Peace Prize]].\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Emilian Czyrnia\u0144ski.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Emilian Czyrnia\u0144ski]], Retinger's maternal grandfather, 1878 photo by [[Walery Rzewuski]]]]\n[[File:Wierchy-1925---W\u0142adys\u0142aw-Zamoyski-(1853-1924).png|thumb|150px|[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]] (1853-1924)]]\n[[File:Misa Sert.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Misia Sert|Misia Godebska Sert]], Retinger's Parisian cousin]]\nJ\u00f3zef Retinger was born in [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Poland]] (then part of [[Austria-Hungary]]), the youngest of five children: his father had a daughter, Aniela, from a first marriage to Helena Jawornicka.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\">{{cite web|title=J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|url=https://kangur.uek.krakow.pl//biblioteka/retinger/B.%20Podgorski%20-%20J.H.%20Retinger%201888-1960.pdf|lang=pl|page=5|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> His mother was Maria Krystyna [[Emil Czyrnia\u0144ski|Czyrnia\u0144ska]], daughter of a [[Greek Catholic Church|Greek Catholic]] [[Lemkos|Lemko]] professor of chemistry at the [[Jagiellonian University]]. His father, J\u00f3zef Stanis\u0142aw Retinger, was the personal legal counsel and successful adviser to French-born Count [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]]. Retinger's great grandfather, Filip Rettinger, was a Jewish tailor from [[Tarn\u00f3w]] who with his family converted to Catholicism in 1827.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Sypek, Antoni|title=\u017bydowskie konwersje na chrze\u015bcija\u0144stwo w Tarnowie, w latach 1785-1900|journal= Rocznik Tarnowski|date= 2013| page= 128|trans-title= Jewish conversions to christianity in Tarn\u00f3w in 1785-1900}} </ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Minakowski, Marek Jerzy.|title=Tw\u00f3rca UE M\u0105\u017c Krewnej Kaczy\u0144skiego to \u017byd z D\u0119bicy|lang=pl|url=https://minakowski.pl/tworca-ue-maz-krewnej-kaczynskiego-to-zyd-z-debicy/|access-date=2020-03-03|trans-title=The Creator of the European Union the Husband of Kaczy\u0144ski's Relative was a Jew from D\u0119bica}}</ref> When his lawyer grandson died, Count Zamoyski took the promising youngster, J\u00f3zef, into his household and paid for him to attend the [[Bart\u0142omiej Nowodworski High School]] in Krak\u00f3w. Retinger's eldest brother, Emil, became a commander in the [[Polish Navy]], while his son, {{Interlanguage link|Witold Retinger|pl}}, was stationed in the [[United Kingdom]] during [[World War II]] (1943-45), as a member then leader of [[No. 308 Polish Fighter Squadron|Squadron 308]] of the [[Polish Air Forces in France and Great Britain|Polish Air Force]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rafweb.org/Squadrons/Sqn300-318.htm|title=History of No.'s 300\u2013318 Squadrons at RAF Web|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Retinger's brother, Juliusz, taught [[physiological chemistry]] at the [[University of Chicago]] and [[University of Wilno]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Polish Biographical Dictionary|title-link= Polish Biographical Dictionary|volume= 127|page= 152|lang=pl}}</ref> Retinger himself initially considered a career in the priesthood, but three months in the Jesuit [[novitiate]] in [[Rome]] confirmed he would not be suited to the life.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n\nFurther financed by Count Zamoyski in 1906, Retinger entered simultaneously the [[Ecole des sciences politiques]] and the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]] in [[Paris]] and two years later, aged twenty, became the youngest person ever to earn a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in literature from there.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> While in the French capital, armed with introductions from Zamoyski and his own relative, the salonni\u00e8re and pianist [[Misia Sert]], he moved in intellectual circles and was befriended by among others, [[Andr\u00e9 Gide]], [[Fran\u00e7ois Mauriac]], [[Bernard Grasset]], [[Jean Giraudoux]], [[Erik Satie]] and [[Maurice Ravel]]. His early literary ambitions were stopped in their tracks when he presented his first novel, ''\"Les Souffleurs\"'' to Andr\u00e9 Gide for his opinion. Gide told him: ''Joseph, you will never be a writer.''<ref name = \"JR\"/>{{rp|pages=11\u201313}} \n\nHe next went to [[Munich]] to study [[comparative psychology]] for a year. From there, encouraged by Zamoyski, in 1910 he moved to [[England]], where he entered the [[London School of Economics]] for a year's study and began a lobbying operation on behalf of the Polish cause and its populations scattered across three ailing empires. Formally he became Director of the London Office of the Polish National Committee (1912\u20131914).<ref>{{cite web|title=Jozef Retinger - cv|url=https://www.cvce.eu/en/obj/joseph_retinger-en-9d454c22-957c-49ef-8c7b-be5f98d676fc.htmlE|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|first1=Wojciech|last1=Roszkowski|first2=Jan|last2=Kofman|title=Biographical Dictionary of Central and Eastern Europe in the Twentieth Century|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date=2016|isbn=9781317475934|chapter-url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=RnKlDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA2377|access-date=2017-07-25|chapter=Retinger J\u00f3zef}}</ref> During this time he continued to move in \u00e9lite circles and  thanks to an introduction by [[Arnold Bennett]] whom he had met in Paris, Retinger developed a close friendship with his older Polish compatriot, the already well established novelist, [[Joseph Conrad]].<ref name=\":0\"/> Retinger urged Conrad to visit Poland, and on 28 July 1914, the day [[World War I]] broke out, Retinger, his wife Otolia, and Conrad, his wife, and their two sons arrived in Krak\u00f3w, the two men's childhood stamping grounds (they were alumni of the same [[secondary school]]). Due to the closeness of the Russian border (Russia was then allied to Great Britain), the Conrads soon sought greater safety in the [[Tatra Mountains]] resort of [[Zakopane]].<ref>[[Zdzis\u0142aw Najder]], ''Joseph Conrad: A Life'', Rochester, New York, Camden House, 2007, {{ISBN|978-1-57113-347-2}}, pp. 459\u201363.</ref> Retinger would write about Conrad in his 1943 book, ''Conrad and His Contemporaries''. Historian [[Norman Davies]] suggests that it was probably Conrad who introduced the \"polyglot and polymath\" Retinger to the British intelligence services.<ref name=\"Davies\">{{cite book|author=Davies, Norman|title=Rising '44: The Battle for Warsaw|title-link=Rising '44|year=2003|place= London|publisher= Pan Books|isbn=0-333-90568-7| page= 53}}</ref> Later Retinger became a personal friend of Major-General Sir [[Colin Gubbins]], wartime head of [[Special Operations Executive|SOE]], and after the war an [[Special Intelligence Service|MI6]] \"asset\".<ref name=\"wilford\">{{cite book|title=The CIA, the British Left and the Cold War: Calling the Tune? Studies in Intelligence|author= Wilford, Hugh|publisher=Routledge|date= 2013|page=242|isbn=978-1135294779}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Dorril, Stephen|title= A Critical Review: MI6: Fifty years of special operations. Doctoral thesis|publisher= University of Huddersfield|date=2010|url=http://eprints.hud.ac.uk/id/eprint/9763/1/sdorrilfinalthesis.pdf|page=27}}</ref>\n\n===World War I===\n[[File:Joseph Conrad author.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Joseph Conrad]]]]\nWith the clouds of war closing in, the project of writing a play together with Conrad based on the latter's novel, ''[[Nostromo]]'' had to be abandoned as both men hurriedly left Austria Hungary. Retinger would have been eligible for military call up in [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]], but no mention of this is made by his biographers. Instead, he put aside literary endeavours and once more assumed the role of a political lobbyist for Poland, publishing pamphlets and travelling between London, Paris and [[New York City|New York]], aided by Conrad in London.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=10}} In the first years of the war, this was not on the agenda of the major powers. Retinger looked instead for other potential alliances and political leverage which led to meetings with leading [[Zionism|Zionists]] of the time, including [[Chaim Weizmann]], [[Vladimir Zhabotinski]] and [[Nahum Sokolow]] who were seeking international recognition and rights for the [[Jewish diaspora]].<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=11}} In 1916 guided by Zamoyski and with the approval of [[Herbert Asquith]], [[David Lloyd George]] and [[Georges Clemenceau]] with his old Parisian connections, [[Prince Sixtus of Bourbon-Parma|Sixtus]] and [[Prince Xavier of Bourbon-Parma|Xavier de Bourbon Parme]], the Duchess of Montebello and Marquis [[Boni de Castellane]], as well as Zamoyski's friend the Polish [[General of the Jesuits]], [[Wlodimir Led\u00f3chowski|W\u0142odzimierz Led\u00f3chowski]], Retinger became a \"courier\" in the secretive European dynastic negotiation suing for peace with Austria.<ref name= \"Kultura\">{{cite journal|author=Jele\u0144ski, K.A.|title=Prekursor anachroniczny|journal=[[Kultura|Kultura Paryska]]|location=Paris|date=1961|lang=pl|trans-title= Anachronistic Precursor (Obituary)|pages=190-193|url=http://static.kulturaparyska.com/attachments/51/96/79311ebf90d26ec65a78e3b802589c43f76cb880.pdf#page=97}}</ref> It became known as the ''[[Sixtus Affair]]'' but was a failure, due to Germany's refusal to cooperate thus making Austria more dependent on it.<ref>{{cite book|title=Informal Alliance: The Bilderberg Group and Transatlantic Relations during the Cold War, 1952-1968|series=  Routledge Studies in Modern History|author=Gijswijt, Thomas W.|chapter=J\u00f3zef Retinger - Informal diplomat|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date= 2018|isbn=978-1-3511-8102-0}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book |author1 = Demblin, August | author2 = Demblin, Alexander | title = Minister gegen Kaiser : Aufzeichnungen eines \u00f6sterreichisch-ungarischen Diplomaten \u00fcber Aussenminister Czernin und Kaiser Karl |lang= de| date = 1997 | publisher = B\u00f6hlau | place = Vienna | isbn = 3-205-98762-4 | trans-title=Minister versus Kaiser: The designs of an Austro-Hungarian Diplomat to outwit Foreign Minister Czernin and [[Charles I of Austria|Kaiser Charles]]}}</ref> In 1917 he met [[Boy Capel|Arthur \"Boy\" Capel]], the half-French dilettante, polo player and \"sponsor\" of [[Coco Chanel]]. Capel is said to have planted in Retinger's mind the idea of a world federal government based on an Anglo-French alliance.<ref>{{cite journal|author= Biskupski, M. B.|title= Spy, Patriot or Internationalist? The Early Career of J\u00f3zef Retinger, Polish Patriarch of the European Union|journal= The Polish Review, Vol. 43, No. 1|date= 1998|pages= 23\u201367}}</ref> After concerns for his personal safety due to his \"political meddling\" in Austria-Hungary and in the emergent [[Soviet Union]], in 1918 Retinger was banned from France, and sought sanctuary in [[Spain]] for several months.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=12}}\n\n==Mexican years==\n[[File:Jane Anderson 1917.JPG|thumb|left|150px|US journalist [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]] 1917]] \nHe travelled on to [[Cuba]] and then to [[Mexico]], where he became an unofficial political adviser to union organizer [[Luis Morones]] whom he fortuitously met crossing the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]], and to President [[Plutarco El\u00edas Calles]].<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/><ref name=\"Oleks\"/> A glimpse of Retinger, newly divorced and love lorn for the American journalist, [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]], appears in the biography of another American woman, the communist sympathiser [[Katherine Anne Porter]], a member of the Morones circle. In it he is described as a \"Polish intriguer\" and \"British Marxist\". In 1921 while on an obscure mission to the [[United States]] to buy saddles, Retinger was arrested and imprisoned in [[Laredo, Texas|Laredo]] and Porter was despatched from Mexico to get him released.<ref name= \"Stout\">{{cite book|title=Katherine Anne Porter: A Sense of the Times - Minds of the new South|author=Stout, Janis P.|publisher=University of Virginia Press|date= 1995|pages=47\u201351|isbn= 978-0-813915685}}</ref> That same year Retinger had proposed that Katherine Porter and her friend Mary Doherty accompany him to Europe to do \"collaborative work\", an offer that was spurned.<ref name= \"Stout\"/>{{rp|pages=94-95}} Retinger helped advance Mexico's nationalization of its oil industry in 1928.<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\">{{cite journal|author=Ethridge, Marcus E.|title= Review of M.B.B. Biskupski, \"War and Diplomacy in East and West: A Biography of J\u00f3zef Retinger\", London, Routledge, 2017, ISBN: 978-1-138-21845-1|journal= [[The Polish Review]]| volume= 64|date= 2019|issue= 1| page= 95|doi= 10.5406/polishreview.64.1.0094}} Ethridge's full review is on pp. 94\u201395</ref> His activities in Mexico lasted a total of almost seven years and only ended with Calles's fall from power in 1936. They inspired Retinger to write three volumes on the tumultuous events of that Latin American republic.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/> The Mexican years were punctuated by trips back to Europe where he took on the role of Representative in the United Kingdom of the Polish Socialist Party (1924\u20131928). In 1926 he married his second wife, Stella, with whom he travelled to Mexico on one occasion. After her death in 1933 his two daughters were left in the care of their maternal grandmother and were estranged from him until the 1950s.\n\nIn the rest of the interwar period, he published many contributions in periodicals, such as the Polish ''Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie'' (Literary News), on literary and political subjects.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n\n==Building blocks on the table==\n[[File:W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski, 1923.jpg|thumb|150px|[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]], Polish prime minister in 1923]]\nDuring [[World War II]], Retinger who was in [[London]], was involved in arranging for Polish troops to be transferred to Britain from France. He was bidden by Winston Churchill personally to escort [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]] by plane to England from France which had just capitulated to the invading Germans.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=16}} He became principal adviser and confidant to the Prime Minister of the [[Polish Government in Exile]] now re-established in London.<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>{{rp|page= 95}}<ref>{{cite web|title=London Gazette|date=1942-12-04|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/35811/page/5301/data.pdf|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> In fact, their political relationship went back to 1916 and was strengthened during [[Wladyslaw Sikorski]]'s earlier brief stint as prime minister, 1922-23 in newly independent Poland, and came to greater fruition when both men were later in exile in London.<ref name=\"Lane\">{{cite book|title=Poland and European Integration: The Ideas and Movements of Polish Exiles in the West, 1939\u201391|author1=Lane, Thomas |author2=Wolanski, Marian|publisher=Springer|date= 2009|page=18|isbn=978-0-2302-71784}}</ref>\n\nSikorski's dependence on Retinger was the greater as he did not have mastery of [[English language|English]]. At this time Retinger was despatched to talk with other exiled government representatives in London, who included [[Marcel-Henri Jaspar]], [[Paul Van Zeeland]], [[Paul-Henri Spaak]] in preparation for a post-war geopolitical landscape.<ref>{{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1|page=455}}</ref> He went on to posit a \"Sikorski Plan\" consisting of two stages, the first of which was signed in January 1942 and proposed a Polish-Czech confederation.<ref>{{cite book|author=Walter Lipgens|title=Documents on the history of European integration: Plans for European union in Great Britain and in exile, 1939\u20131945 (including 107 documents in their original languages on 3 microfiches)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X3TsVCAt9F4C&pg=PA648|accessdate=10 August 2011|year=1985|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-009724-5|page=648}}</ref> The idea was to expand it into a [[wikt:Central Europe|Central Europe]]an confederation with Poland and [[Lithuania]], [[Czechoslovakia]] as its nucleus around which would be grouped [[Romania]], [[Hungary]], Yugoslavia and [[Greece]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Schmidt, Andrea|title=From Intermarium to the Three Seas Initiative: The Implications of the Polish Orientation Over the Central and Eastern European Region on Hungarian Policy in Baltic-Black Sea Regionalisms: Patchworks and Networks at Europe's Eastern Margins|editor1=Bogdanova, Olga |editor2=Makarychev, Andrey|publisher=Springer Nature|date= 2019|page=157|isbn= 978-3-0302-48789}}</ref> The agenda behind this was to create a common political blue-print for smaller countries abutting larger European powers and became the basis of a Belgian-Dutch union which would mirror the Polish-Czech arrangement.\n\nThis scheme of Retinger's caused problems between London and [[Moscow]]. In order not to tread on Soviet toes, the British altered their position and refused to back Sikorski's negotiations with the eight smaller European states. In his speech on the Council of Europe, [[Winston Churchill]] [https://www.winstonchurchill.org/resources/speeches/1941-1945-war-leader/national-address/ BBC radio broadcast] on 21 March 1943 referred to the necessity of smaller nations forming groupings, but that it was too early to go into detail. The most Retinger was able to achieve was to push through the [[Sikorski-Mayski Agreement]], signed on 30 July 1941, which provided for the formation of the [[Anders' army]], thus ridding Stalin of the immediate human problem posed by the hundreds of thousands of Polish [[Prisoner of war|POW]]s and deportees from the [[Occupation of Poland (1939\u201345)|Soviet occupied]] [[Kresy Zachodnie|Kresy]] regions of the former [[Second Polish Republic]], who after an arduous odyssey across thousands of miles would eventually end up as the [[United Kingdom]]'s human problem.<ref>{{cite book|author=Anders, Lt.-General W\u0142adys\u0142aw|title= An Army in Exile|publisher= MacMillan & Co. Ltd|date=1949|page=73}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Polish Underground Army, the Western Allies, and the Failure of Strategic Unity in World War II|author=Peszke, Michael Alfred|publisher=McFarland|date= 2015|isbn=978-1-4766-10276|page=70}}</ref> This trade-off adumbrated the [[Tehran Conference|Tehran]] and [[Yalta Conference]]s.<ref>{{cite book|title=Identity in Flux. The Polish Community in Britain|author=Sword, Keith|place=London|publisher=School of Slavonic and East European Studies - SSEES Occasional Papers No. 36| date=1996|isbn=0-903425-60-2|pages=24\u201330|url=https://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/id/eprint/10078280/1/SSEES0012.pdf|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Brushes with death==\nRetinger narrowly avoided perishing in the sea off [[Gibraltar]] with [[Wladyslaw Sikorski's death controversy|W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]], in July 1943, but for the fact that he was not needed to accompany the premier on a troop inspection in the Middle East and would be better employed in London. The spare seat on the plane went to Sikorski's daughter who died with her father.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> Retinger was devastated by this turn of events. His relationship with Sikorski's successor, [[Stanislaw Mikolajczyk]] was much more ambivalent, but he obtained his consent for a special mission to Poland under [[Special Operations Executive|SOE]] in April 1944.<ref>Bu\u0142hak, W\u0142adys\u0142aw. \"The Foreign Office and the [[Special Operations Executive]] and the Expedition of J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger to Poland, April\u2013July 1944\", ''[[The Polish Review]]'', vol. 61, no. 3, 2016, pp. 33\u201357.</ref>\n\nWith an SOE brief and without prior training, Retinger, aged 56, parachuted into [[German-occupied Poland|occupied Poland]] with 2nd Lt. [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt]], (see [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt#Operation \"Salamander\"|Operation Salamander]]), to meet with Polish underground figures, to deliver money to the Polish underground, and to \"explain to his fellow Poles in the homeland 'how are we going to lose this war'\".<ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\">{{cite book|last1=Eringer|first1=Robert|author-link=Robert Eringer|title=The Global Manipulators|publisher=Pentacle Books|asin=B00546KTEM|oclc=26551991}}</ref>{{rp|pages=16\u201322}} <ref name = \"JR\"/>{{rp|page=265}}<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>  Following at least one assassination attempt on him, Retinger expressed his frustration thus:\n\n{{blockquote|You know why I came.  The [Underground] [[Government Delegation for Poland|Delegate]] knows as well.... They know that I only want to convince them that it will be necessary in the future to cooperate with the Communists, because no English are coming here, only Russians.  If we do not get along with them somehow, it will be a terrible tragedy, because we well know what [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin]] and the [[NKVD]] [Interior Ministry of the Soviet Union] are. And it's about trying to make people here understand this fact. And they want to murder me!}}<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>\n\nThe latter quip was a reference to elements in the [[Polish Underground Army]], the [[Armia Krajowa|AK]] who were convinced Retinger was not serving the interests of his country and should therefore be \"removed\". One apparent attempt to liquidate him in Poland was on the grounds of a \"death sentence\" to be carried out on the alleged orders of general [[Kazimierz Sosnkowski]]. It was foiled by the intervention of an old friend and [[Armia Krajowa|AK fighter]], Tadeusz Gebethner.<ref>{{cite web|title=The story of Tadeusz Gebethner|url=https://sprawiedliwi.org.pl/en/stories-of-rescue/story-tadeusz-gebethner|publisher=sprawiedliwi.org.pl |access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> There was also an attempt during his visit in occupied Poland to poison him, which failed. On his return to London, he spent some time in the [[Dorchester Hotel]] in London's [[Park Lane, London|Park Lane]] recovering from his ordeal of the trip, which left him lame in one leg for the rest of his life, possibly due to the [[Polyneuritis]] brought on by the poison. His first visitor at the Dorchester was Sir [[Anthony Eden]], the foreign secretary.<ref name=\"Davies\"/><ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\"/>\n\nImmediately after the war, in 1945-6 Retinger travelled to [[Warsaw]] with emergency aid for the capital's population. It consisted largely of tons of British Army surplus, such as blankets and field-kitchens.<ref name= \"Kultura\"/> When his erstwhile military escort from \"operation Salamander\", [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt|Tadeusz Chciuk]] and his new wife, Ewa, were arrested in Poland as subversives by the Polish Communist security service, Retinger appealed over their heads directly to [[Vyacheslav Molotov|Molotov]] in [[Moscow]] to have them released. Apparently the personal intervention succeeded. In 1948 the Chciuks became refugees in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jozef Retinger (1888-1960)|author=Chciuk-Celt, Jan|url=http://pdf.amazingdiscoveries.org/References/RB/275%20PDFs/jozef-hieronim-retinger-slide-79.pdf|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n===Unwanted intrusion===\nDark days followed World War II when tensions rose between former Western and Eastern allies and in April 1946 Retinger's flat in [[Bayswater]], West London, was broken into and his and his secretary's files ransacked by persons unknown. He reported the matter to [[Scotland Yard]], but the [[Metropolitan Police Service|Metropolitan Police]] were not overly bothered. As a result, Retinger escalated his complaint and ended up being interviewed by the Britain's security services. His view was that the newly communist embassy of the [[Polish People's Republic]] were responsible for the break-in.<ref>{{cite book|author=Moss, Eloise|title=Night Raiders: Burglary and the Making of Modern Urban Life in London, 1860-1968|publisher=Oxford University Press|date= 2019|pages=186-87|isbn=978-0-1925-7677-4}}</ref>\n\nFrom the moment Winston Churchill had made his \"[[Iron Curtain]]\" speech in [[Fulton, Missouri]], in April 1946, Retinger turned his efforts into a modified European project he had harboured for decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.winstonchurchill.org/i4a/pages/index.cfm?pageid=429 |title=Sinews of Peace (Iron Curtain) |accessdate=2007-02-26 |last=Churchill |first=Winston |publisher=Churchill Centre |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070207054810/http://www.winstonchurchill.org/i4a/pages/index.cfm?pageid=429 |archivedate=7 February 2007 }}</ref><ref name= \"Kultura\"/>\n\n==Vision for Europe==\n[[File:Krakow-Jozef Retinger plaque.jpg|thumb|right|[[Krak\u00f3w]] plaque commemorating Retinger, \"great pioneer of European unity\".]]\nAfter World War II, Retinger feared another devastating war in Europe, this time fought between \"Russia\" and \"the Anglo-Saxons\".<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/> He became a leading advocate of [[European unification]] as a means of securing peace.<ref>{{cite web|author=Retinger, J. H.|title= The European Continent? Address given to the Royal Institute of Foreign Affairs in London|url=https://www.cvce.eu/content/publication/2008/2/19/534c684a-8924-445a-8181-58360f939f56/publishable_en.pdf|publisher=CVCE|date= 7 May 1946|access-date=2020-03-27}} Correction: although the original states Royal Institute of Foreign Affairs, it should read [[Royal Institute of International Affairs]], known today as \"[[Chatham House]]\", this is likely a copyediting error at CVCE (ed.).</ref> He helped found both the [[European Movement]] and the [[Council of Europe]], somewhat to the dismay of the philosopher Count [[Richard Coudenhove-Kalergi]], the post-[[World War I]] [[Anti-communism|anti-bolshevist]] founder of the [[Paneuropean Union]] movement.<ref name=\"wilford\"/>{{rp|pages=227\u2013228}}<ref>{{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1|page=165}}</ref> \n\nRetinger, with his connections in Holland, Belgium, and [[Switzerland]] (he was a friend of [[Denis de Rougemont]]), took his cue from [[Winston Churchill]]'s 1947 [[Zurich]] speech and found fertile ground with thirteen British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] members of Parliament who backed the idea of a loose European association of states. Working in particular with Britain's [[Duncan Sandys]], incidentally Churchill's son-in-law, he took on the lion's share of the work and became Honorary Secretary General of the [[European Movement]]. He organised the 1948 [[Congress of Europe|Hague Congress]] which brought together the two camps of those for a unified Europe and those in favour of a federal Europe.<ref name=\"Lane\"/> During the congress, Retinger networked assiduously among the delegates, who included the Vatican diplomat, [[Giovanni Montini]], the future [[Pope Paul VI]]. Ensuing discussions led eventually to the formation in 1951 of a [[European Coal and Steel Community]].<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>  \n\n===Creator of Bilderberg=== \nRetinger was the initiator and architect of the informal [[Bilderberg Group|Bilderberg]] conferences in 1952-54 and was their general secretary until his premature death in London in 1960. A founding member of the Bilderberg Group, later British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Foreign Secretary, [[Denis Healey]], described the secretive Bilderberg meetings as the \"brainchild\" of Retinger.<ref>{{cite web|title=Denis Healey on Bilderberg|url=https://www.worldsocialism.org/spgb/socialist-standard/2002/2000s/no-1175-july-2002/denis-healey-bilderberg/|publisher=worldsocialism.org|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Aubourg, Valerie|title=Organizing Atlanticism: the Bilderberg group and the Atlantic institute, 1952\u20131963|journal=[[Intelligence and National Security]]|volume=18, (2)|date=2003|pages= 92-105 |doi=10.1080/02684520412331306760}}</ref> Despite eschewing any distinctions or medals throughout his life, in 1958 he was nominated for the Nobel Peace Prize.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.nobelprize.org/nomination/archive/show.php?id=15660 |title =Nomination for Nobel Peace Prize: Joseph Retinger |author =Nobelprize.org |publisher =Nobel Media AB 2014 |website = Nomination Database| date = |access-date = 2014-10-09}}</ref> He died in poverty of lung cancer.<ref name =\"BP\">{{cite web|title=J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|url=https://kangur.uek.krakow.pl//biblioteka/retinger/B.%20Podgorski%20-%20J.H.%20Retinger%201888-1960.pdf|lang=pl|page=53|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> He was buried at [[North Sheen Cemetery]] in the presence of five British cabinet ministers as well as of his two younger daughters who were finally reconciled with him.<ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\"/>{{rp|pages=16\u201322}} According to the oration of Sir [[Edward Beddington-Behrens]], Retinger not only had special access to [[10 Downing Street]] but also to the [[White House]].<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> \n[[File:Gr\u00f3b J\u00f3zefa Hieronima Retingera.jpg|thumb|right|Retinger's grave, [[North Sheen Cemetery]], London]]\nRetinger's long time personal assistant and the editor of his posthumous memoirs, John Pomian, actually {{Interlanguage link|Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz|pl}}, was another Polish emigr\u00e9 in London, later a director of the Heim gallery in London's [[St James's]], owned by the influential Polish art historian and philanthropist, [[Andrzej Ciechanowiecki]].<ref>{{cite journal | url = http://nekrologi.wyborcza.pl/0,11,,373783,Jan-Pomiana-B%C5%82awdziewicza-kondolencje.html | title =Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz | trans-title=Obituary of Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz|journal = Wyborcza.pl |date=2015| lang = pl | access-date = 2016-10-28}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRetinger married twice. In 1912 he wed the well-born Otolia Zubrzycka (divorced 1921, died 1984), with whom he had a daughter, Malina. In 1926 he wed Stella Morel (died 1933), daughter of French-born pacifist and [[Dundee]] member of Parliament [[E.D. Morel]] and Mary, n\u00e9e Richardson, with whom he had two daughters, Maria and Stasia. \n\nDuring the Great War and after, Retinger appears to have fallen under the spell of several women, especially the American journalist [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]], a supposed lover of Joseph Conrad.<ref name= \"JM\">{{cite book|title=Joseph Conrad: A Biography|author= Meyers, Jeffrey|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|date= 2001|page=361|isbn=978-0-8154-11123}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=The Athens Observer|first=Donald E.|last=Wilkes|title=Jane Anderson: The Nazi Georgia Peach|url=http://digitalcommons.law.uga.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1019&context=fac_pm|date=May 18, 1995|page=5|accessdate=24 August 2013}}</ref> Retinger's own liaison with Anderson brought about the breakdown of Retinger's marriage to Otolia and drove a wedge between him and his friend Conrad.<ref name= \"JM\"/>{{rp|page=293}} However Conrad biographer, John Stape, gives an alternative version for the cooling of relations between the two men, suggesting instead that as Retinger's enthusiasms were not shared by the novelist, shortly after the war, without his charming wife by his side, Retinger's proneness to exaggeration and tactlessness made him less socially acceptable.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Several Lives of Joseph Conrad|author= Stape, John|publisher=Random House|date= 2010|pages=187\u2013188|isbn=978-1409006824}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nOver sixty years after his death, the left-leaning Retinger continues to attract fascination and controversy with, on one hand, admirers of his political skill, his apparently selfless single-mindedness and his lasting institutional legacy in Europe and beyond.<ref>{{cite book|author=Wisnewski, Gerhard|title=The Bilderbergers Puppet-Masters of Power?: An Investigation into Claims of Conspiracy at the Heart of Politics, Business and the Media|translator=J. Collis|trans-title=Drahtzieher der Macht (2010)|date=2014|place=West Sussex|publisher=Clairview Books|isbn=978-1-90557075-1|pages=63\u201366}}</ref> On the other hand, detractors impugn his influence due to alleged connections with deeply secret and malign factions for which there is so far no reliable evidence.<ref>{{cite journal|author=K\u0119der, Wojciech|title=Recenzje: Bogdan Podg\u00f3rski, J\u00f3zef Retinger prywatny polityk, Universitas, Krak\u00f3w 2013, ss. 417.\n|journal=Studia Sandomierskie 23|date= 2016|pages=303\u2013314|lang=pl|trans-title=Review of Bogdan Podg\u00f3rski, ''J\u00f3zef Retinger private politician''. Krak\u00f3w: Universitas. 2013, pages 417.|url=https://journals.indexcopernicus.com/api/file/viewByFileId/84684.pdf}}\n</ref> He remains an enigma and probably the one significant contributor to post-war European peace without a monument.<ref name = \"BP\"/>{{rp|page=60}} \n\nIn 2000 [[The Daily Telegraph]]'s [[Ambrose Evans-Pritchard]] revealed from declassified US Government records that:\n{{blockquote|The leaders of the European Movement \u2013 Retinger, the visionary [[Robert Schuman]] and the former Belgian prime minister [[Paul-Henri Spaak]] \u2013 were all treated as hired hands by their American sponsors. The US role was handled as a covert operation. ACUE\u2019s funding came from the [[Ford Foundation|Ford]] and [[Rockefeller Foundation]]s as well as business groups with close ties to the US government.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/1356047/Euro-federalists-financed-by-US-spy-chiefs.html|title=Euro-federalists financed by US Spy Chief|author= Ambrose Evans-Pritchard|date=18 September 2000|publisher= The Daily Telegraph|author-link=Ambrose Evans-Pritchard}}</ref>}} The finding, in the context of the [[Cold War]], was subsequently analysed in greater detail by ''[[Le Figaro Magazine|Le Figaro]]'' commentator, {{Interlanguage link|R\u00e9mi Kauffer|fr}} in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kauffer, R\u00e9mi|title=Quand la CIA finan\u00e7ait la construction europ\u00e9enne - Par R\u00e9mi Kauffer, Source : Historia 2003|date=12 June 2019|url=http://www.comite-valmy.org/spip.php?article516|publisher=Comit\u00e9 Valmy|lang=fr|trans-title=When the CIA financed the construction of Europe by R\u00e9mi Kauffer, source: Historia 2003|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> However, as Hugh Wilford demonstrates, the initiative to win American backing for a \"United States of Europe\" did not come either from [[Allen Dulles]], deputy, then chief of the [[CIA]], nor from Senator [[William Fulbright]], chairman of the [[ACUE]], but from the lobbying Europeans themselves guided by disparate motives, namely Coudenhove-Kalergi and Retinger who eclipsed him due to his close connection with [[Winston Churchill]] on European matters.<ref name=\"wilford\"/> Retinger's plan was that the [[United States]] had to be integral to the political and economic support for a war damaged [[Western Europe]]. As \"head of casting\" for his project, he set about finding key Americans who would collaborate with him, among whom at that time was [[Charles Douglas Jackson]], [[Time Inc.|Time-Life]] publisher in the 1940s and one time head of propaganda at the White House.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Bilderberg Conspiracy: Inside the World\u2019s Most Powerful Secret Society|author=Jeffers, H. Paul|chapter= 1|publisher= Kensington Publishing Corp.|date= 2012|isbn= 978-0-8065-3595-1}}</ref>\n\n== Selected works==\nBy J. H. Retinger:\n* {{cite book|date= 1908|title=Le conte fantastique dans le romantisme fran\u00e7ais|place= Gen\u00e8ve|publisher= Slatkine Reprints, 1973|trans-title=Fantastical Tales in the French Romantic Tradition|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite book|title=Histoire de la litt\u00e9rature fran\u00e7aise du romantisme \u00e0 nos jours|place= Paris|publisher=[[Bernard Grasset| B. Grasset]]|date= 1911|trans-title=The History of French Literature from Romanticism to the Present Day|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite book|title= The Poles and Prussia|place=London|date=1913|url=https://explore.library.leeds.ac.uk/special-collections-explore/334918/the_poles_and_prussia?subject=%22Polish%20question%22&resultOffset=2}} available at University of Leeds Library\n* {{cite book|title=La Pologne et l'\u00c9quilibre europ\u00e9en|place= Paris|date= 1916|trans-title=Poland and the Stability of Europe|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite book|title=Morones of Mexico; a history of the labour movement in that country|place=London|publisher= The Labour Pub. Co. Ltd.|date= 1926}}\n* {{cite book|title=Tierra mexicana; the history of land and agriculture in ancient and modern Mexico|place= London|publisher= N. Douglas|date= 1928}}\n* {{cite book|title=Polacy w cywilizacjach zagranicznych|trans-title= Poles in Foreign Civilizations|place=Warsaw|date= 1934|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite journal|title= Historja i polityka: Nowy czynnik w dyplomacji mi\u0119dzynarodowej|journal=Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie (50)|date= 4 December 1938|trans-title=History and Politics: A new factor in international diplomacy|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite journal|title= Historja i polityka: Zast\u00f3j w mi\u0119dzynarodowej dzia\u0142alno\u015bci Rosji|journal=Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie (51)|date= 11 December 1938|trans-title=History and Politics: Suspension of Russian activity in international relations|lang=pl}} \n* {{cite book|title=All about Poland: facts, figures, documents|place= London|publisher= Minerva Pub. Co.|date= 1941}}\n* {{cite book|title=Conrad and His Contemporaries |year=1942 |publisher=Roy |location=New York|orig-year=First published by Minerva, London, 1941}}\n*  {{cite book|title= The European Continent? Address given to the Royal Institute of International Affairs in London|url=https://www.cvce.eu/content/publication/2008/2/19/534c684a-8924-445a-8181-58360f939f56/publishable_en.pdf|date= 7 May 1946|place=London}}\n*  {{cite book|title=The Bilderberg Group|place= Hertfordshire, UK|date= 1959}}\n*  {{cite book|title=Under Polish eyes|place=United Kingdom|publisher= Joseph Conrad Society|date= 1975}}\n\nAbout Retinger:\n* {{cite journal|author=Poraj, Stanis\u0142aw|title= The knight among nations|journal= Tydzie\u0144 Literacki Polski Zbrojnej, 2 (24)|lang=pl|date= 19 June 1938}}\n* {{cite book|author=[[Denis de Rougemont|de Rougemont, Denis]]|date= 1961|title=A Biographical Sketch. In Tribute to a Great European|editor= Retinger, J.H.|pages=20\u201350|place= Geneva|publisher= Centre Europe\u00e9n de la Culture|lang=}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Siemaszko, Zbigniew Sebastian|date=1967|title= Retinger w Polsce 1944 r.|place=Paris|journal= Zeszyty Historyczne, 12|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|title=J\u00f3zef Retinger: Memoirs of an Eminence Grise|editor=Pomian, John|publisher= Sussex University Press/Chatto & Windus|date= 1972| isbn=0-85621-002-1|oclc=844436367}}.\n* {{cite book|author=[[Jan Nowak-Jeziora\u0144ski|Nowak, Jan]]|title= Kurier z Warszawy|place= London|publisher= Odnowa|date= 1978|lang=pl|isbn= 0-903705-37-0}}\n* {{cite book|publisher=[[Polski S\u0142ownik Biograficzny]]|title= J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|volume= XXXI|date= 1988-1989|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|title=In remembrance of Joseph Retinger 1988-1960, Initiator of the European League for Economic Cooperation|publisher= [[European League for Economic Cooperation]]|place= Brussels|date= 1996}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Grosbois, Thierry|date= 1999|title=L'action de J\u00f3zef Retinger en faveur de l'id\u00e9e europ\u00e9enne 1940-46|journal= Revue Europ\u00e9enne d'Histoire| volume= 6|issue= 34|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Kalicki, W\u0142odzimierz|date=2010|title=Gracz, kt\u00f3ry budowa\u0142 Europ\u0119|trans-title=The Player who built Europe|journal= Gazeta Wyborcza |issue=219|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|authors=\t[[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt|Marek Celt]], Jan Chciuk-Celt|title=Parachuting into Poland, 1944: Memoir of a Secret Mission with Jozef Retinger|publisher=McFarland|date= 2013|isbn=978-1-4766-03384}}\n* {{cite book|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|title= J\u00f3zef Retinger \u2013 prywatny polityk|trans-title=J\u00f3zef Retinger - a private politician|publisher= Universitas|date= 2013|lang=pl|isbn=97883-242-2351-0}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of governments in exile during World War II]]\n*[[European Movement]]\n*[[European Union]]\n*[[List of Poles#Diplomats|List of Poles]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|author=Bines, Jeffrey|title=Poland's S.O.E: A British Perspective: the Story of the Polish Country Section of the Special Operations Executive 1940-1946 Including the British Military Mission Number Four to Poland 1939|publisher=Polish Underground Movement Study Trust|date= 2018|place=London|isbn=978-0-9928-03056}} \n* {{cite journal|author= Biskupski, M.B.|title=Spy, Patriot or Internationalist? The Early Career of J\u00f3zef Retinger, Polish Patriarch of European Union|journal=[[The Polish Review]]| volume= 43|date= 1998|issue=1| pages= 23\u201367}} \n* {{cite journal|author=Bu\u0142hak, W\u0142adys\u0142aw|title=The Foreign Office and the Special Operations Executive and the Expedition of J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger to Poland, April\u2013July 1944|journal=The Polish Review| volume= 61|date= 2016|issue=3| pages= 33\u201357|doi=10.5406/polishreview.61.3.0033}}\n* {{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=J\u00f3zef H. Retinger \u2013 pomys\u0142odawca i wsp\u00f3\u0142tw\u00f3rca Grupy Bilderbergu|trans-title=Joseph Retinger: Visionary Co-founder of the [[Bilderberg Group]]|lang=pl|journal= Studia polityczne|publisher= ISP PAN|volume= 10|date= 2000}} \n* {{cite journal|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=Dzia\u0142alno\u015b\u0107 J.H. Retingera na rzecz zjednoczonej Europy|trans-title=Joseph Retinger\u2019s Work for a United Europe|journal= Studia Europejskie|publisher= Centrum Europejskie Uniwersytetu Warszawskiego|volume=  16|date= 2000|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=Dzia\u0142alno\u015b\u0107 J\u00f3zefa Hieronima Retingera na rzecz integracji europejskiej|lang=pl|trans-title= Joseph Retinger\u2019s Work for European Integration|publisher= Wydawnictwo Adam Marsza\u0142ek|place= Toru\u0144|date= 2008|isbn=978-83-7611-184-1}}\n* {{cite book|author= Hampson, Robert|title=Conrad's Secrets|publisher=\tPalgrave Macmillan|date= 2012|isbn=978-0-2305-0783-8}} \n* {{cite journal|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=Joseph Retinger's Vision of [a] United Europe After World War II: Central and Eastern European Question|journal= [[The Polish Review]]| volume= 60|date= 2015 |issue=4|pages= 49\u201366|doi=10.5406/polishreview.60.4.0049}}\n* {{cite book|author=Wisnewski, Gerhard|title=The Bilderbergers Puppet-Masters of Power?: An Investigation into Claims of Conspiracy at the Heart of Politics, Business and the Media|translator=J. Collis|trans-title=Drahtzieher der Macht (2010)|date=2014|place=West Sussex|publisher=Clairview Books|isbn=978-1-90557075-1|pages=63\u201366}}\n* {{cite book|title=Informal Alliance: The Bilderberg Group and Transatlantic Relations during the Cold War, 1952-1968|series=  Routledge Studies in Modern History|author=Gijswijt, Thomas W.|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date= 2018|isbn=978-1-3511-8102-0}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20161027232624/http://home.teleport.com/~flyheart/retinger.htm Biography of Jozef Retinger]\n*[https://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/205254911 The Polish Soviet Relations During The Second World War, photographs held by the [[Imperial War Museum]] including of Dr. J\u00f3zef Retinger on 30.07.1941]\n*[http://www.bilderberg.org/bildhist.htm#Memoirs Chapter 4, European Unity.] from ''Memoirs of An Eminence Grise'' by John Pomian,\n*[http://bilderbergmeetings.co.uk/jozef-retinger/ Bilderberg website on Retinger's life in brief]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Retinger, Jozef}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Poland to Russia]]\n[[Category:Council of Europe]]\n[[Category:Members of the Steering Committee of the Bilderberg Group]]\n[[Category:Polish politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Freemasons]]\n[[Category:European integration pioneers]]\n[[Category:Geopoliticians]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Polish diplomats]]\n[[Category:Polish spies]]\n[[Category:Secret Intelligence Service personnel]]\n[[Category:Special Operations Executive personnel]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish writers]]\n[[Category:Exophonic writers]]\n[[Category:Polish essayists]]\n[[Category:Male essayists]]\n[[Category:Polish political writers]]\n[[Category:Polish people of World War II]]\n[[Category:People of World War II]]\n[[Category:History of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Polish people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Polish people of Rusyn descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Polish diplomat and activist}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger\n|image             = File:Jozef Retinger.jpg\n|image_size        = \n|caption           = J\u00f3zef Retinger, recovering from a poisoning attempt c.1944<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n|birth_date        = {{birth date|1888|04|17|df=y}}\n|birth_place       = [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria]]\n|death_date        = {{death date and age|df=yes|1960|06|12|1888|04|17}}\n|death_place       = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n|citizenship       = Polish\n|nationality       = Polish\n|ethnicity         = \n|field             = Economics, international relations, politics\n|work_institutions = [[Sorbonne University]] Phd, [[London School of Economics]], [[Polish government-in-exile]]\n|doctoral_advisor  =\n|doctoral_students =\n|known_for         = [[Bilderberg Group]], [[European Movement International]]\n|author_abbrev_bot =\n|author_abbrev_zoo =\n|influences        = [[Jesuits]], [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]]\n|influenced        = [[Joseph Conrad]], foundation of [[European Union]], the [[Bilderberg Group]]\n|prizes            = [[Nobel Peace Prize]] Nomination 1958\n|footnotes         =\n|signature         =\n}}\n'''J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger''' ([[Krak\u00f3w]], 17 April 1888 {{spaced ndash}} 12 June 1960, [[London]]; [[World War II]] [[nom de guerre|noms de guerre]] ''Salamandra'', \"Salamander\", and ''Brzoza'', \"Birch Tree\") was a [[Poles|Polish]] diplomat, international political adviser and activist, and writer.<ref name = \"JR\">{{cite book|title=Joseph Retinger - Memoirs of an Eminence Grise|editor=John Pomian|publisher=Sussex University Press/ Chatto & Windus|date= 1972|url=https://ia800905.us.archive.org/5/items/MemoirsOfAnEminenceGrise1972/Memoirs%20of%20an%20Eminence%20Grise%2C%201972.pdf}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[World War I]], Retinger was politically active in [[Austria-Hungary]] and Russia on behalf of the Polish independence movement. After the [[Russian Revolution]], he had to retreat to [[Central America]], where he became an economic adviser. After the outbreak of  [[World War II]], he was principal adviser to the [[Polish government-in-exile]].<ref name=\"Oleks\">{{cite web|title=The Most Mysterious Man in 20th-Century Politics|author=Oleksiak, Wojciech|publisher=Culture.pl|date=2016-12-14|url=https://culture.pl/en/article/the-most-mysterious-man-in-20th-century-politics|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> A Freemason with a reputation as a [[grey eminence]], he went on to cofound the [[European Movement]], which led to establishment of the [[European Union]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pieczewski|first1=Andrzej|title=Joseph Retinger's conception of and contribution to the early process of European integration|journal=European Review of History|date=11 Aug 2010|volume=17|issue=4|pages=581\u2013604|doi=10.1080/13507486.2010.495766}}</ref> and was instrumental in forming the [[Bilderberg Group]]. In 1958 he was nominated for the [[Nobel Peace Prize]].\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Emilian Czyrnia\u0144ski.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Emilian Czyrnia\u0144ski]], Retinger's maternal grandfather, 1878 photo by [[Walery Rzewuski]]]]\n[[File:Wierchy-1925---W\u0142adys\u0142aw-Zamoyski-(1853-1924).png|thumb|150px|[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]] (1853-1924)]]\n[[File:Misa Sert.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Misia Sert|Misia Godebska Sert]], Retinger's Parisian cousin]]\nJ\u00f3zef Retinger was born in [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Poland]] (then part of [[Austria-Hungary]]), the youngest of five children: his father had a daughter, Aniela, from a first marriage to Helena Jawornicka.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\">{{cite web|title=J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|url=https://kangur.uek.krakow.pl//biblioteka/retinger/B.%20Podgorski%20-%20J.H.%20Retinger%201888-1960.pdf|lang=pl|page=5|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> His mother was Maria Krystyna [[Emil Czyrnia\u0144ski|Czyrnia\u0144ska]], daughter of a [[Greek Catholic Church|Greek Catholic]] [[Lemkos|Lemko]] professor of chemistry at the [[Jagiellonian University]]. His father, J\u00f3zef Stanis\u0142aw Retinger, was the personal legal counsel and successful adviser to French-born Count [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Zamoyski]]. Retinger's great grandfather, Filip Rettinger, was a Jewish tailor from [[Tarn\u00f3w]] who with his family converted to Catholicism in 1827.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Sypek, Antoni|title=\u017bydowskie konwersje na chrze\u015bcija\u0144stwo w Tarnowie, w latach 1785-1900|journal= Rocznik Tarnowski|date= 2013| page= 128|trans-title= Jewish conversions to christianity in Tarn\u00f3w in 1785-1900}} </ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Minakowski, Marek Jerzy.|title=Tw\u00f3rca UE M\u0105\u017c Krewnej Kaczy\u0144skiego to \u017byd z D\u0119bicy|lang=pl|url=https://minakowski.pl/tworca-ue-maz-krewnej-kaczynskiego-to-zyd-z-debicy/|access-date=2020-03-03|trans-title=The Creator of the European Union the Husband of Kaczy\u0144ski's Relative was a Jew from D\u0119bica}}</ref> When his lawyer grandson died, Count Zamoyski took the promising youngster, J\u00f3zef, into his household and paid for him to attend the [[Bart\u0142omiej Nowodworski High School]] in Krak\u00f3w. Retinger's eldest brother, Emil, became a commander in the [[Polish Navy]], while his son, {{Interlanguage link|Witold Retinger|pl}}, was stationed in the [[United Kingdom]] during [[World War II]] (1943-45), as a member then leader of [[No. 308 Polish Fighter Squadron|Squadron 308]] of the [[Polish Air Forces in France and Great Britain|Polish Air Force]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rafweb.org/Squadrons/Sqn300-318.htm|title=History of No.'s 300\u2013318 Squadrons at RAF Web|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Retinger's brother, Juliusz, taught [[physiological chemistry]] at the [[University of Chicago]] and [[University of Wilno]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Polish Biographical Dictionary|title-link= Polish Biographical Dictionary|volume= 127|page= 152|lang=pl}}</ref> Retinger himself initially considered a career in the priesthood, but three months in the Jesuit [[novitiate]] in [[Rome]] confirmed he would not be suited to the life.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n\nFurther financed by Count Zamoyski in 1906, Retinger entered simultaneously the [[Ecole des sciences politiques]] and the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]] in [[Paris]] and two years later, aged twenty, became the youngest person ever to earn a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in literature from there.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> While in the French capital, armed with introductions from Zamoyski and his own relative, the salonni\u00e8re and pianist [[Misia Sert]], he moved in intellectual circles and was befriended by among others, [[Andr\u00e9 Gide]], [[Fran\u00e7ois Mauriac]], [[Bernard Grasset]], [[Jean Giraudoux]], [[Erik Satie]] and [[Maurice Ravel]]. His early literary ambitions were stopped in their tracks when he presented his first novel, ''\"Les Souffleurs\"'' to Andr\u00e9 Gide for his opinion. Gide told him: ''Joseph, you will never be a writer.''<ref name = \"JR\"/>{{rp|pages=11\u201313}} \n\nHe next went to [[Munich]] to study [[comparative psychology]] for a year. From there, encouraged by Zamoyski, in 1910 he moved to [[England]], where he entered the [[London School of Economics]] for a year's study and began a lobbying operation on behalf of the Polish cause and its populations scattered across three ailing empires. Formally he became Director of the London Office of the Polish National Committee (1912\u20131914).<ref>{{cite web|title=Jozef Retinger - cv|url=https://www.cvce.eu/en/obj/joseph_retinger-en-9d454c22-957c-49ef-8c7b-be5f98d676fc.htmlE|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|first1=Wojciech|last1=Roszkowski|first2=Jan|last2=Kofman|title=Biographical Dictionary of Central and Eastern Europe in the Twentieth Century|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date=2016|isbn=9781317475934|chapter-url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=RnKlDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA2377|access-date=2017-07-25|chapter=Retinger J\u00f3zef}}</ref> During this time he continued to move in \u00e9lite circles and  thanks to an introduction by [[Arnold Bennett]] whom he had met in Paris, Retinger developed a close friendship with his older Polish compatriot, the already well established novelist, [[Joseph Conrad]].<ref name=\":0\"/> Retinger urged Conrad to visit Poland, and on 28 July 1914, the day [[World War I]] broke out, Retinger, his wife Otolia, and Conrad, his wife, and their two sons arrived in Krak\u00f3w, the two men's childhood stamping grounds (they were alumni of the same [[secondary school]]). Due to the closeness of the Russian border (Russia was then allied to Great Britain), the Conrads soon sought greater safety in the [[Tatra Mountains]] resort of [[Zakopane]].<ref>[[Zdzis\u0142aw Najder]], ''Joseph Conrad: A Life'', Rochester, New York, Camden House, 2007, {{ISBN|978-1-57113-347-2}}, pp. 459\u201363.</ref> Retinger would write about Conrad in his 1943 book, ''Conrad and His Contemporaries''. Historian [[Norman Davies]] suggests that it was probably Conrad who introduced the \"polyglot and polymath\" Retinger to the British intelligence services.<ref name=\"Davies\">{{cite book|author=Davies, Norman|title=Rising '44: The Battle for Warsaw|title-link=Rising '44|year=2003|place= London|publisher= Pan Books|isbn=0-333-90568-7| page= 53}}</ref> Later Retinger became a personal friend of Major-General Sir [[Colin Gubbins]], wartime head of [[Special Operations Executive|SOE]], and after the war an [[Special Intelligence Service|MI6]] \"asset\".<ref name=\"wilford\">{{cite book|title=The CIA, the British Left and the Cold War: Calling the Tune? Studies in Intelligence|author= Wilford, Hugh|publisher=Routledge|date= 2013|page=242|isbn=978-1135294779}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Dorril, Stephen|title= A Critical Review: MI6: Fifty years of special operations. Doctoral thesis|publisher= University of Huddersfield|date=2010|url=http://eprints.hud.ac.uk/id/eprint/9763/1/sdorrilfinalthesis.pdf|page=27}}</ref>\n\n===World War I===\n[[File:Joseph Conrad author.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Joseph Conrad]]]]\nWith the clouds of war closing in, the project of writing a play together with Conrad based on the latter's novel, ''[[Nostromo]]'' had to be abandoned as both men hurriedly left Austria Hungary. Retinger would have been eligible for military call up in [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]], but no mention of this is made by his biographers. Instead, he put aside literary endeavours and once more assumed the role of a political lobbyist for Poland, publishing pamphlets and travelling between London, Paris and [[New York City|New York]], aided by Conrad in London.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=10}} In the first years of the war, this was not on the agenda of the major powers. Retinger looked instead for other potential alliances and political leverage which led to meetings with leading [[Zionism|Zionists]] of the time, including [[Chaim Weizmann]], [[Vladimir Zhabotinski]] and [[Nahum Sokolow]] who were seeking international recognition and rights for the [[Jewish diaspora]].<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=11}} In 1916 guided by Zamoyski and with the approval of [[Herbert Asquith]], [[David Lloyd George]] and [[Georges Clemenceau]] with his old Parisian connections, [[Prince Sixtus of Bourbon-Parma|Sixtus]] and [[Prince Xavier of Bourbon-Parma|Xavier de Bourbon Parme]], the Duchess of Montebello and Marquis [[Boni de Castellane]], as well as Zamoyski's friend the Polish [[General of the Jesuits]], [[Wlodimir Led\u00f3chowski|W\u0142odzimierz Led\u00f3chowski]], Retinger became a \"courier\" in the secretive European dynastic negotiation suing for peace with Austria.<ref name= \"Kultura\">{{cite journal|author=Jele\u0144ski, K.A.|title=Prekursor anachroniczny|journal=[[Kultura|Kultura Paryska]]|location=Paris|date=1961|lang=pl|trans-title= Anachronistic Precursor (Obituary)|pages=190-193|url=http://static.kulturaparyska.com/attachments/51/96/79311ebf90d26ec65a78e3b802589c43f76cb880.pdf#page=97}}</ref> It became known as the ''[[Sixtus Affair]]'' but was a failure, due to Germany's refusal to cooperate thus making Austria more dependent on it.<ref>{{cite book|title=Informal Alliance: The Bilderberg Group and Transatlantic Relations during the Cold War, 1952-1968|series=  Routledge Studies in Modern History|author=Gijswijt, Thomas W.|chapter=J\u00f3zef Retinger - Informal diplomat|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date= 2018|isbn=978-1-3511-8102-0}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book |author1 = Demblin, August | author2 = Demblin, Alexander | title = Minister gegen Kaiser : Aufzeichnungen eines \u00f6sterreichisch-ungarischen Diplomaten \u00fcber Aussenminister Czernin und Kaiser Karl |lang= de| date = 1997 | publisher = B\u00f6hlau | place = Vienna | isbn = 3-205-98762-4 | trans-title=Minister versus Kaiser: The designs of an Austro-Hungarian Diplomat to outwit Foreign Minister Czernin and [[Charles I of Austria|Kaiser Charles]]}}</ref> In 1917 he met [[Boy Capel|Arthur \"Boy\" Capel]], the half-French dilettante, polo player and \"sponsor\" of [[Coco Chanel]]. Capel is said to have planted in Retinger's mind the idea of a world federal government based on an Anglo-French alliance.<ref>{{cite journal|author= Biskupski, M. B.|title= Spy, Patriot or Internationalist? The Early Career of J\u00f3zef Retinger, Polish Patriarch of the European Union|journal= The Polish Review, Vol. 43, No. 1|date= 1998|pages= 23\u201367}}</ref> After concerns for his personal safety due to his \"political meddling\" in Austria-Hungary and in the emergent [[Soviet Union]], in 1918 Retinger was banned from France, and sought sanctuary in [[Spain]] for several months.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=12}}\n\n==Mexican years==\n[[File:Jane Anderson 1917.JPG|thumb|left|150px|US journalist [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]] 1917]] \nHe travelled on to [[Cuba]] and then to [[Mexico]], where he became an unofficial political adviser to union organizer [[Luis Morones]] whom he fortuitously met crossing the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]], and to President [[Plutarco El\u00edas Calles]].<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/><ref name=\"Oleks\"/> A glimpse of Retinger, newly divorced and love lorn for the American journalist, [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]], appears in the biography of another American woman, the communist sympathiser [[Katherine Anne Porter]], a member of the Morones circle. In it he is described as a \"Polish intriguer\" and \"British Marxist\". In 1921 while on an obscure mission to the [[United States]] to buy saddles, Retinger was arrested and imprisoned in [[Laredo, Texas|Laredo]] and Porter was despatched from Mexico to get him released.<ref name= \"Stout\">{{cite book|title=Katherine Anne Porter: A Sense of the Times - Minds of the new South|author=Stout, Janis P.|publisher=University of Virginia Press|date= 1995|pages=47\u201351|isbn= 978-0-813915685}}</ref> That same year Retinger had proposed that Katherine Porter and her friend Mary Doherty accompany him to Europe to do \"collaborative work\", an offer that was spurned.<ref name= \"Stout\"/>{{rp|pages=94-95}} Retinger helped advance Mexico's nationalization of its oil industry in 1928.<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\">{{cite journal|author=Ethridge, Marcus E.|title= Review of M.B.B. Biskupski, \"War and Diplomacy in East and West: A Biography of J\u00f3zef Retinger\", London, Routledge, 2017, ISBN: 978-1-138-21845-1|journal= [[The Polish Review]]| volume= 64|date= 2019|issue= 1| page= 95|doi= 10.5406/polishreview.64.1.0094}} Ethridge's full review is on pp. 94\u201395</ref> His activities in Mexico lasted a total of almost seven years and only ended with Calles's fall from power in 1936. They inspired Retinger to write three volumes on the tumultuous events of that Latin American republic.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/> The Mexican years were punctuated by trips back to Europe where he took on the role of Representative in the United Kingdom of the Polish Socialist Party (1924\u20131928). In 1926 he married his second wife, Stella, with whom he travelled to Mexico on one occasion. After her death in 1933 his two daughters were left in the care of their maternal grandmother and were estranged from him until the 1950s.\n\nIn the rest of the interwar period, he published many contributions in periodicals, such as the Polish ''Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie'' (Literary News), on literary and political subjects.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>\n\n==Building blocks on the table==\n[[File:W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski, 1923.jpg|thumb|150px|[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]], Polish prime minister in 1923]]\nDuring [[World War II]], Retinger who was in [[London]], was involved in arranging for Polish troops to be transferred to Britain from France. He was bidden by Winston Churchill personally to escort [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]] by plane to England from France which had just capitulated to the invading Germans.<ref name = \"Podg\u00f3rski\"/>{{rp|page=16}} He became principal adviser and confidant to the Prime Minister of the [[Polish Government in Exile]] now re-established in London.<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>{{rp|page= 95}}<ref>{{cite web|title=London Gazette|date=1942-12-04|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/35811/page/5301/data.pdf|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> In fact, their political relationship went back to 1916 and was strengthened during [[Wladyslaw Sikorski]]'s earlier brief stint as prime minister, 1922-23 in newly independent Poland, and came to greater fruition when both men were later in exile in London.<ref name=\"Lane\">{{cite book|title=Poland and European Integration: The Ideas and Movements of Polish Exiles in the West, 1939\u201391|author1=Lane, Thomas |author2=Wolanski, Marian|publisher=Springer|date= 2009|page=18|isbn=978-0-2302-71784}}</ref>\n\nSikorski's dependence on Retinger was the greater as he did not have mastery of [[English language|English]]. At this time Retinger was despatched to talk with other exiled government representatives in London, who included [[Marcel-Henri Jaspar]], [[Paul Van Zeeland]], [[Paul-Henri Spaak]] in preparation for a post-war geopolitical landscape.<ref>{{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1|page=455}}</ref> He went on to posit a \"Sikorski Plan\" consisting of two stages, the first of which was signed in January 1942 and proposed a Polish-Czech confederation.<ref>{{cite book|author=Walter Lipgens|title=Documents on the history of European integration: Plans for European union in Great Britain and in exile, 1939\u20131945 (including 107 documents in their original languages on 3 microfiches)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X3TsVCAt9F4C&pg=PA648|accessdate=10 August 2011|year=1985|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-009724-5|page=648}}</ref> The idea was to expand it into a [[wikt:Central Europe|Central Europe]]an confederation with Poland and [[Lithuania]], [[Czechoslovakia]] as its nucleus around which would be grouped [[Romania]], [[Hungary]], Yugoslavia and [[Greece]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Schmidt, Andrea|title=From Intermarium to the Three Seas Initiative: The Implications of the Polish Orientation Over the Central and Eastern European Region on Hungarian Policy in Baltic-Black Sea Regionalisms: Patchworks and Networks at Europe's Eastern Margins|editor1=Bogdanova, Olga |editor2=Makarychev, Andrey|publisher=Springer Nature|date= 2019|page=157|isbn= 978-3-0302-48789}}</ref> The agenda behind this was to create a common political blue-print for smaller countries abutting larger European powers and became the basis of a Belgian-Dutch union which would mirror the Polish-Czech arrangement.\n\nThis scheme of Retinger's caused problems between London and [[Moscow]]. In order not to tread on Soviet toes, the British altered their position and refused to back Sikorski's negotiations with the eight smaller European states. In his speech on the Council of Europe, [[Winston Churchill]] [https://www.winstonchurchill.org/resources/speeches/1941-1945-war-leader/national-address/ BBC radio broadcast] on 21 March 1943 referred to the necessity of smaller nations forming groupings, but that it was too early to go into detail. The most Retinger was able to achieve was to push through the [[Sikorski-Mayski Agreement]], signed on 30 July 1941, which provided for the formation of the [[Anders' army]], thus ridding Stalin of the immediate human problem posed by the hundreds of thousands of Polish [[Prisoner of war|POW]]s and deportees from the [[Occupation of Poland (1939\u201345)|Soviet occupied]] [[Kresy Zachodnie|Kresy]] regions of the former [[Second Polish Republic]], who after an arduous odyssey across thousands of miles would eventually end up as the [[United Kingdom]]'s human problem.<ref>{{cite book|author=Anders, Lt.-General W\u0142adys\u0142aw|title= An Army in Exile|publisher= MacMillan & Co. Ltd|date=1949|page=73}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Polish Underground Army, the Western Allies, and the Failure of Strategic Unity in World War II|author=Peszke, Michael Alfred|publisher=McFarland|date= 2015|isbn=978-1-4766-10276|page=70}}</ref> This trade-off adumbrated the [[Tehran Conference|Tehran]] and [[Yalta Conference]]s.<ref>{{cite book|title=Identity in Flux. The Polish Community in Britain|author=Sword, Keith|place=London|publisher=School of Slavonic and East European Studies - SSEES Occasional Papers No. 36| date=1996|isbn=0-903425-60-2|pages=24\u201330|url=https://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/id/eprint/10078280/1/SSEES0012.pdf|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Brushes with death==\nRetinger narrowly avoided perishing in the sea off [[Gibraltar]] with [[Wladyslaw Sikorski's death controversy|W\u0142adys\u0142aw Sikorski]], in July 1943, but for the fact that he was not needed to accompany the premier on a troop inspection in the Middle East and would be better employed in London. The spare seat on the plane went to Sikorski's daughter who died with her father.<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> Retinger was devastated by this turn of events. His relationship with Sikorski's successor, [[Stanislaw Mikolajczyk]] was much more ambivalent, but he obtained his consent for a special mission to Poland under [[Special Operations Executive|SOE]] in April 1944.<ref>Bu\u0142hak, W\u0142adys\u0142aw. \"The Foreign Office and the [[Special Operations Executive]] and the Expedition of J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger to Poland, April\u2013July 1944\", ''[[The Polish Review]]'', vol. 61, no. 3, 2016, pp. 33\u201357.</ref>\n\nWith an SOE brief and without prior training, Retinger, aged 56, parachuted into [[German-occupied Poland|occupied Poland]] with 2nd Lt. [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt]], (see [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt#Operation \"Salamander\"|Operation Salamander]]), to meet with Polish underground figures, to deliver money to the Polish underground, and to \"explain to his fellow Poles in the homeland 'how are we going to lose this war'\".<ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\">{{cite book|last1=Eringer|first1=Robert|author-link=Robert Eringer|title=The Global Manipulators|publisher=Pentacle Books|asin=B00546KTEM|oclc=26551991}}</ref>{{rp|pages=16\u201322}} <ref name = \"JR\"/>{{rp|page=265}}<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>  Following at least one assassination attempt on him, Retinger expressed his frustration thus:\n\n{{blockquote|You know why I came.  The [Underground] [[Government Delegation for Poland|Delegate]] knows as well.... They know that I only want to convince them that it will be necessary in the future to cooperate with the Communists, because no English are coming here, only Russians.  If we do not get along with them somehow, it will be a terrible tragedy, because we well know what [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin]] and the [[NKVD]] [Interior Ministry of the Soviet Union] are. And it's about trying to make people here understand this fact. And they want to murder me!}}<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/>\n\nThe latter quip was a reference to elements in the [[Polish Underground Army]], the [[Armia Krajowa|AK]] who were convinced Retinger was not serving the interests of his country and should therefore be \"removed\". One apparent attempt to liquidate him in Poland was on the grounds of a \"death sentence\" to be carried out on the alleged orders of general [[Kazimierz Sosnkowski]]. It was foiled by the intervention of an old friend and [[Armia Krajowa|AK fighter]], Tadeusz Gebethner.<ref>{{cite web|title=The story of Tadeusz Gebethner|url=https://sprawiedliwi.org.pl/en/stories-of-rescue/story-tadeusz-gebethner|publisher=sprawiedliwi.org.pl |access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> There was also an attempt during his visit in occupied Poland to poison him, which failed. On his return to London, he spent some time in the [[Dorchester Hotel]] in London's [[Park Lane, London|Park Lane]] recovering from his ordeal of the trip, which left him lame in one leg for the rest of his life, possibly due to the [[Polyneuritis]] brought on by the poison. His first visitor at the Dorchester was Sir [[Anthony Eden]], the foreign secretary.<ref name=\"Davies\"/><ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\"/>\n\nImmediately after the war, in 1945-6 Retinger travelled to [[Warsaw]] with emergency aid for the capital's population. It consisted largely of tons of British Army surplus, such as blankets and field-kitchens.<ref name= \"Kultura\"/> When his erstwhile military escort from \"operation Salamander\", [[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt|Tadeusz Chciuk]] and his new wife, Ewa, were arrested in Poland as subversives by the Polish Communist security service, Retinger appealed over their heads directly to [[Vyacheslav Molotov|Molotov]] in [[Moscow]] to have them released. Apparently the personal intervention succeeded in 1948. The Chciuks became refugees in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jozef Retinger (1888-1960)|author=Chciuk-Celt, Jan|url=http://pdf.amazingdiscoveries.org/References/RB/275%20PDFs/jozef-hieronim-retinger-slide-79.pdf|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n===Unwanted intrusion===\nDark days followed World War II when tensions rose between former Western and Eastern allies and in April 1946 Retinger's flat in [[Bayswater]], West London, was broken into and his and his secretary's files ransacked by persons unknown. He reported the matter to [[Scotland Yard]], but the [[Metropolitan Police Service|Metropolitan Police]] were not overly bothered. As a result, Retinger escalated his complaint and ended up being interviewed by the Britain's security services. His view was that the newly communist embassy of the [[Polish People's Republic]] were responsible for the break-in.<ref>{{cite book|author=Moss, Eloise|title=Night Raiders: Burglary and the Making of Modern Urban Life in London, 1860-1968|publisher=Oxford University Press|date= 2019|pages=186-87|isbn=978-0-1925-7677-4}}</ref>\n\nFrom the moment Winston Churchill had made his \"[[Iron Curtain]]\" speech in [[Fulton, Missouri]], in April 1946, Retinger turned his efforts into a modified European project he had harboured for decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.winstonchurchill.org/i4a/pages/index.cfm?pageid=429 |title=Sinews of Peace (Iron Curtain) |accessdate=2007-02-26 |last=Churchill |first=Winston |publisher=Churchill Centre |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070207054810/http://www.winstonchurchill.org/i4a/pages/index.cfm?pageid=429 |archivedate=7 February 2007 }}</ref><ref name= \"Kultura\"/>\n\n==Vision for Europe==\n[[File:Krakow-Jozef Retinger plaque.jpg|thumb|right|[[Krak\u00f3w]] plaque commemorating Retinger, \"great pioneer of European unity\".]]\nAfter World War II, Retinger feared another devastating war in Europe, this time fought between \"Russia\" and \"the Anglo-Saxons\".<ref name=\"Marcus E. Ethridge 2017\"/> He became a leading advocate of [[European unification]] as a means of securing peace.<ref>{{cite web|author=Retinger, J. H.|title= The European Continent? Address given to the Royal Institute of Foreign Affairs in London|url=https://www.cvce.eu/content/publication/2008/2/19/534c684a-8924-445a-8181-58360f939f56/publishable_en.pdf|publisher=CVCE|date= 7 May 1946|access-date=2020-03-27}} Correction: although the original states Royal Institute of Foreign Affairs, it should read [[Royal Institute of International Affairs]], known today as \"[[Chatham House]]\", this is likely a copyediting error at CVCE (ed.).</ref> He helped found both the [[European Movement]] and the [[Council of Europe]], somewhat to the dismay of the philosopher Count [[Richard Coudenhove-Kalergi]], the post-[[World War I]] [[Anti-communism|anti-bolshevist]] founder of the [[Paneuropean Union]] movement.<ref name=\"wilford\"/>{{rp|pages=227\u2013228}}<ref>{{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1|page=165}}</ref> \n\nRetinger, with his connections in Holland, Belgium, and [[Switzerland]] (he was a friend of [[Denis de Rougemont]]), took his cue from [[Winston Churchill]]'s 1947 [[Zurich]] speech and found fertile ground with thirteen British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] members of Parliament who backed the idea of a loose European association of states. Working in particular with Britain's [[Duncan Sandys]], incidentally Churchill's son-in-law, he took on the lion's share of the work and became Honorary Secretary General of the [[European Movement]]. He organised the 1948 [[Congress of Europe|Hague Congress]] which brought together the two camps of those for a unified Europe and those in favour of a federal Europe.<ref name=\"Lane\"/> During the congress, Retinger networked assiduously among the delegates, who included the Vatican diplomat, [[Giovanni Montini]], the future [[Pope Paul VI]]. Ensuing discussions led eventually to the formation in 1951 of a [[European Coal and Steel Community]].<ref name=\"Oleks\"/>  \n\n===Creator of Bilderberg=== \nRetinger was the initiator and architect of the informal [[Bilderberg Group|Bilderberg]] conferences in 1952-54 and was their general secretary until his premature death in London in 1960. A founding member of the Bilderberg Group, later British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Foreign Secretary, [[Denis Healey]], described the secretive Bilderberg meetings as the \"brainchild\" of Retinger.<ref>{{cite web|title=Denis Healey on Bilderberg|url=https://www.worldsocialism.org/spgb/socialist-standard/2002/2000s/no-1175-july-2002/denis-healey-bilderberg/|publisher=worldsocialism.org|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Aubourg, Valerie|title=Organizing Atlanticism: the Bilderberg group and the Atlantic institute, 1952\u20131963|journal=[[Intelligence and National Security]]|volume=18, (2)|date=2003|pages= 92-105 |doi=10.1080/02684520412331306760}}</ref> Despite eschewing any distinctions or medals throughout his life, in 1958 he was nominated for the Nobel Peace Prize.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.nobelprize.org/nomination/archive/show.php?id=15660 |title =Nomination for Nobel Peace Prize: Joseph Retinger |author =Nobelprize.org |publisher =Nobel Media AB 2014 |website = Nomination Database| date = |access-date = 2014-10-09}}</ref> He died in poverty of lung cancer.<ref name =\"BP\">{{cite web|title=J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|url=https://kangur.uek.krakow.pl//biblioteka/retinger/B.%20Podgorski%20-%20J.H.%20Retinger%201888-1960.pdf|lang=pl|page=53|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> He was buried at [[North Sheen Cemetery]] in the presence of five British cabinet ministers as well as of his two younger daughters who were finally reconciled with him.<ref name=\"The Global Manipulators\"/>{{rp|pages=16\u201322}} According to the oration of Sir [[Edward Beddington-Behrens]], Retinger not only had special access to [[10 Downing Street]] but also to the [[White House]].<ref name=\"Oleks\"/> \n[[File:Gr\u00f3b J\u00f3zefa Hieronima Retingera.jpg|thumb|right|Retinger's grave, [[North Sheen Cemetery]], London]]\nRetinger's long time personal assistant and the editor of his posthumous memoirs, John Pomian, actually {{Interlanguage link|Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz|pl}}, was another Polish emigr\u00e9 in London, later a director of the Heim gallery in London's [[St James's]], owned by the influential Polish art historian and philanthropist, [[Andrzej Ciechanowiecki]].<ref>{{cite journal | url = http://nekrologi.wyborcza.pl/0,11,,373783,Jan-Pomiana-B%C5%82awdziewicza-kondolencje.html | title =Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz | trans-title=Obituary of Jan Pomian-B\u0142awdziewicz|journal = Wyborcza.pl |date=2015| lang = pl | access-date = 2016-10-28}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRetinger married twice. In 1912 he wed the well-born Otolia Zubrzycka (divorced 1921, died 1984), with whom he had a daughter, Malina. In 1926 he wed Stella Morel (died 1933), daughter of French-born pacifist and [[Dundee]] member of Parliament [[E.D. Morel]] and Mary, n\u00e9e Richardson, with whom he had two daughters, Maria and Stasia. \n\nDuring the Great War and after, Retinger appears to have fallen under the spell of several women, especially the American journalist [[Jane Anderson (American journalist)|Jane Anderson]], a supposed lover of Joseph Conrad.<ref name= \"JM\">{{cite book|title=Joseph Conrad: A Biography|author= Meyers, Jeffrey|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|date= 2001|page=361|isbn=978-0-8154-11123}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=The Athens Observer|first=Donald E.|last=Wilkes|title=Jane Anderson: The Nazi Georgia Peach|url=http://digitalcommons.law.uga.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1019&context=fac_pm|date=May 18, 1995|page=5|accessdate=24 August 2013}}</ref> Retinger's own liaison with Anderson brought about the breakdown of Retinger's marriage to Otolia and drove a wedge between him and his friend Conrad.<ref name= \"JM\"/>{{rp|page=293}} However Conrad biographer, John Stape, gives an alternative version for the cooling of relations between the two men, suggesting instead that as Retinger's enthusiasms were not shared by the novelist, shortly after the war, without his charming wife by his side, Retinger's proneness to exaggeration and tactlessness made him less socially acceptable.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Several Lives of Joseph Conrad|author= Stape, John|publisher=Random House|date= 2010|pages=187\u2013188|isbn=978-1409006824}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nOver sixty years after his death, the left-leaning Retinger continues to attract fascination and controversy with, on one hand, admirers of his political skill, his apparently selfless single-mindedness and his lasting institutional legacy in Europe and beyond.<ref>{{cite book|author=Wisnewski, Gerhard|title=The Bilderbergers Puppet-Masters of Power?: An Investigation into Claims of Conspiracy at the Heart of Politics, Business and the Media|translator=J. Collis|trans-title=Drahtzieher der Macht (2010)|date=2014|place=West Sussex|publisher=Clairview Books|isbn=978-1-90557075-1|pages=63\u201366}}</ref> On the other hand, detractors impugn his influence due to alleged connections with deeply secret and malign factions for which there is so far no reliable evidence.<ref>{{cite journal|author=K\u0119der, Wojciech|title=Recenzje: Bogdan Podg\u00f3rski, J\u00f3zef Retinger prywatny polityk, Universitas, Krak\u00f3w 2013, ss. 417.\n|journal=Studia Sandomierskie 23|date= 2016|pages=303\u2013314|lang=pl|trans-title=Review of Bogdan Podg\u00f3rski, ''J\u00f3zef Retinger private politician''. Krak\u00f3w: Universitas. 2013, pages 417.|url=https://journals.indexcopernicus.com/api/file/viewByFileId/84684.pdf}}\n</ref> He remains an enigma and probably the one significant contributor to post-war European peace without a monument.<ref name = \"BP\"/>{{rp|page=60}} \n\nIn 2000 [[The Daily Telegraph]]'s [[Ambrose Evans-Pritchard]] revealed from declassified US Government records that:\n{{blockquote|The leaders of the European Movement \u2013 Retinger, the visionary [[Robert Schuman]] and the former Belgian prime minister [[Paul-Henri Spaak]] \u2013 were all treated as hired hands by their American sponsors. The US role was handled as a covert operation. ACUE\u2019s funding came from the [[Ford Foundation|Ford]] and [[Rockefeller Foundation]]s as well as business groups with close ties to the US government.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/1356047/Euro-federalists-financed-by-US-spy-chiefs.html|title=Euro-federalists financed by US Spy Chief|author= Ambrose Evans-Pritchard|date=18 September 2000|publisher= The Daily Telegraph|author-link=Ambrose Evans-Pritchard}}</ref>}} The finding, in the context of the [[Cold War]], was subsequently analysed in greater detail by ''[[Le Figaro Magazine|Le Figaro]]'' commentator, {{Interlanguage link|R\u00e9mi Kauffer|fr}} in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kauffer, R\u00e9mi|title=Quand la CIA finan\u00e7ait la construction europ\u00e9enne - Par R\u00e9mi Kauffer, Source : Historia 2003|date=12 June 2019|url=http://www.comite-valmy.org/spip.php?article516|publisher=Comit\u00e9 Valmy|lang=fr|trans-title=When the CIA financed the construction of Europe by R\u00e9mi Kauffer, source: Historia 2003|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> However, as Hugh Wilford demonstrates, the initiative to win American backing for a \"United States of Europe\" did not come either from [[Allen Dulles]], deputy, then chief of the [[CIA]], nor from Senator [[William Fulbright]], chairman of the [[ACUE]], but from the lobbying Europeans themselves guided by disparate motives, namely Coudenhove-Kalergi and Retinger who eclipsed him due to his close connection with [[Winston Churchill]] on European matters.<ref name=\"wilford\"/> Retinger's plan was that the [[United States]] had to be integral to the political and economic support for a war damaged [[Western Europe]]. As \"head of casting\" for his project, he set about finding key Americans who would collaborate with him, among whom at that time was [[Charles Douglas Jackson]], [[Time Inc.|Time-Life]] publisher in the 1940s and one time head of propaganda at the White House.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Bilderberg Conspiracy: Inside the World\u2019s Most Powerful Secret Society|author=Jeffers, H. Paul|chapter= 1|publisher= Kensington Publishing Corp.|date= 2012|isbn= 978-0-8065-3595-1}}</ref>\n\n== Selected works==\nBy J. H. Retinger:\n* {{cite book|date= 1908|title=Le conte fantastique dans le romantisme fran\u00e7ais|place= Gen\u00e8ve|publisher= Slatkine Reprints, 1973|trans-title=Fantastical Tales in the French Romantic Tradition|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite book|title=Histoire de la litt\u00e9rature fran\u00e7aise du romantisme \u00e0 nos jours|place= Paris|publisher=[[Bernard Grasset| B. Grasset]]|date= 1911|trans-title=The History of French Literature from Romanticism to the Present Day|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite book|title= The Poles and Prussia|place=London|date=1913|url=https://explore.library.leeds.ac.uk/special-collections-explore/334918/the_poles_and_prussia?subject=%22Polish%20question%22&resultOffset=2}} available at University of Leeds Library\n* {{cite book|title=La Pologne et l'\u00c9quilibre europ\u00e9en|place= Paris|date= 1916|trans-title=Poland and the Stability of Europe|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite book|title=Morones of Mexico; a history of the labour movement in that country|place=London|publisher= The Labour Pub. Co. Ltd.|date= 1926}}\n* {{cite book|title=Tierra mexicana; the history of land and agriculture in ancient and modern Mexico|place= London|publisher= N. Douglas|date= 1928}}\n* {{cite book|title=Polacy w cywilizacjach zagranicznych|trans-title= Poles in Foreign Civilizations|place=Warsaw|date= 1934|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite journal|title= Historja i polityka: Nowy czynnik w dyplomacji mi\u0119dzynarodowej|journal=Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie (50)|date= 4 December 1938|trans-title=History and Politics: A new factor in international diplomacy|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite journal|title= Historja i polityka: Zast\u00f3j w mi\u0119dzynarodowej dzia\u0142alno\u015bci Rosji|journal=Wiadomo\u015bci Literackie (51)|date= 11 December 1938|trans-title=History and Politics: Suspension of Russian activity in international relations|lang=pl}} \n* {{cite book|title=All about Poland: facts, figures, documents|place= London|publisher= Minerva Pub. Co.|date= 1941}}\n* {{cite book|title=Conrad and His Contemporaries |year=1942 |publisher=Roy |location=New York|orig-year=First published by Minerva, London, 1941}}\n*  {{cite book|title= The European Continent? Address given to the Royal Institute of International Affairs in London|url=https://www.cvce.eu/content/publication/2008/2/19/534c684a-8924-445a-8181-58360f939f56/publishable_en.pdf|date= 7 May 1946|place=London}}\n*  {{cite book|title=The Bilderberg Group|place= Hertfordshire, UK|date= 1959}}\n*  {{cite book|title=Under Polish eyes|place=United Kingdom|publisher= Joseph Conrad Society|date= 1975}}\n\nAbout Retinger:\n* {{cite journal|author=Poraj, Stanis\u0142aw|title= The knight among nations|journal= Tydzie\u0144 Literacki Polski Zbrojnej, 2 (24)|lang=pl|date= 19 June 1938}}\n* {{cite book|author=[[Denis de Rougemont|de Rougemont, Denis]]|date= 1961|title=A Biographical Sketch. In Tribute to a Great European|editor= Retinger, J.H.|pages=20\u201350|place= Geneva|publisher= Centre Europe\u00e9n de la Culture|lang=}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Siemaszko, Zbigniew Sebastian|date=1967|title= Retinger w Polsce 1944 r.|place=Paris|journal= Zeszyty Historyczne, 12|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|title=J\u00f3zef Retinger: Memoirs of an Eminence Grise|editor=Pomian, John|publisher= Sussex University Press/Chatto & Windus|date= 1972| isbn=0-85621-002-1|oclc=844436367}}.\n* {{cite book|author=[[Jan Nowak-Jeziora\u0144ski|Nowak, Jan]]|title= Kurier z Warszawy|place= London|publisher= Odnowa|date= 1978|lang=pl|isbn= 0-903705-37-0}}\n* {{cite book|publisher=[[Polski S\u0142ownik Biograficzny]]|title= J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger (1888-1960)|volume= XXXI|date= 1988-1989|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|title=In remembrance of Joseph Retinger 1988-1960, Initiator of the European League for Economic Cooperation|publisher= [[European League for Economic Cooperation]]|place= Brussels|date= 1996}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Grosbois, Thierry|date= 1999|title=L'action de J\u00f3zef Retinger en faveur de l'id\u00e9e europ\u00e9enne 1940-46|journal= Revue Europ\u00e9enne d'Histoire| volume= 6|issue= 34|lang=fr}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Kalicki, W\u0142odzimierz|date=2010|title=Gracz, kt\u00f3ry budowa\u0142 Europ\u0119|trans-title=The Player who built Europe|journal= Gazeta Wyborcza |issue=219|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|authors=\t[[Tadeusz Chciuk-Celt|Marek Celt]], Jan Chciuk-Celt|title=Parachuting into Poland, 1944: Memoir of a Secret Mission with Jozef Retinger|publisher=McFarland|date= 2013|isbn=978-1-4766-03384}}\n* {{cite book|author=Podg\u00f3rski, Bogdan|title= J\u00f3zef Retinger \u2013 prywatny polityk|trans-title=J\u00f3zef Retinger - a private politician|publisher= Universitas|date= 2013|lang=pl|isbn=97883-242-2351-0}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of governments in exile during World War II]]\n*[[European Movement]]\n*[[European Union]]\n*[[List of Poles#Diplomats|List of Poles]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|author=Bines, Jeffrey|title=Poland's S.O.E: A British Perspective: the Story of the Polish Country Section of the Special Operations Executive 1940-1946 Including the British Military Mission Number Four to Poland 1939|publisher=Polish Underground Movement Study Trust|date= 2018|place=London|isbn=978-0-9928-03056}} \n* {{cite journal|author= Biskupski, M.B.|title=Spy, Patriot or Internationalist? The Early Career of J\u00f3zef Retinger, Polish Patriarch of European Union|journal=[[The Polish Review]]| volume= 43|date= 1998|issue=1| pages= 23\u201367}} \n* {{cite journal|author=Bu\u0142hak, W\u0142adys\u0142aw|title=The Foreign Office and the Special Operations Executive and the Expedition of J\u00f3zef Hieronim Retinger to Poland, April\u2013July 1944|journal=The Polish Review| volume= 61|date= 2016|issue=3| pages= 33\u201357|doi=10.5406/polishreview.61.3.0033}}\n* {{cite book|title=MI6: Inside the Covert World of Her Majesty's Secret Intelligence Service|author= Dorril, Stephen|publisher=Simon and Schuster|date= 2002|isbn=978-0-7432-1778-1}}\n* {{cite journal|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=J\u00f3zef H. Retinger \u2013 pomys\u0142odawca i wsp\u00f3\u0142tw\u00f3rca Grupy Bilderbergu|trans-title=Joseph Retinger: Visionary Co-founder of the [[Bilderberg Group]]|lang=pl|journal= Studia polityczne|publisher= ISP PAN|volume= 10|date= 2000}} \n* {{cite journal|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=Dzia\u0142alno\u015b\u0107 J.H. Retingera na rzecz zjednoczonej Europy|trans-title=Joseph Retinger\u2019s Work for a United Europe|journal= Studia Europejskie|publisher= Centrum Europejskie Uniwersytetu Warszawskiego|volume=  16|date= 2000|lang=pl}}\n* {{cite book|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=Dzia\u0142alno\u015b\u0107 J\u00f3zefa Hieronima Retingera na rzecz integracji europejskiej|lang=pl|trans-title= Joseph Retinger\u2019s Work for European Integration|publisher= Wydawnictwo Adam Marsza\u0142ek|place= Toru\u0144|date= 2008|isbn=978-83-7611-184-1}}\n* {{cite book|author= Hampson, Robert|title=Conrad's Secrets|publisher=\tPalgrave Macmillan|date= 2012|isbn=978-0-2305-0783-8}} \n* {{cite journal|author=Pieczewski, Andrzej|title=Joseph Retinger's Vision of [a] United Europe After World War II: Central and Eastern European Question|journal= [[The Polish Review]]| volume= 60|date= 2015 |issue=4|pages= 49\u201366|doi=10.5406/polishreview.60.4.0049}}\n* {{cite book|author=Wisnewski, Gerhard|title=The Bilderbergers Puppet-Masters of Power?: An Investigation into Claims of Conspiracy at the Heart of Politics, Business and the Media|translator=J. Collis|trans-title=Drahtzieher der Macht (2010)|date=2014|place=West Sussex|publisher=Clairview Books|isbn=978-1-90557075-1|pages=63\u201366}}\n* {{cite book|title=Informal Alliance: The Bilderberg Group and Transatlantic Relations during the Cold War, 1952-1968|series=  Routledge Studies in Modern History|author=Gijswijt, Thomas W.|place=London|publisher=Routledge|date= 2018|isbn=978-1-3511-8102-0}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20161027232624/http://home.teleport.com/~flyheart/retinger.htm Biography of Jozef Retinger]\n*[https://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/205254911 The Polish Soviet Relations During The Second World War, photographs held by the [[Imperial War Museum]] including of Dr. J\u00f3zef Retinger on 30.07.1941]\n*[http://www.bilderberg.org/bildhist.htm#Memoirs Chapter 4, European Unity.] from ''Memoirs of An Eminence Grise'' by John Pomian,\n*[http://bilderbergmeetings.co.uk/jozef-retinger/ Bilderberg website on Retinger's life in brief]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Retinger, Jozef}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Poland to Russia]]\n[[Category:Council of Europe]]\n[[Category:Members of the Steering Committee of the Bilderberg Group]]\n[