{"title_page": "Barnacle Geese Myth", "text_new": "[[File:From Topographia Hibernica British Library MS 13 B VIII.jpg|thumb|From Topographia Hibernica British Library MS 13 B VIII]] \nA [[myth]] about the origins of  the [[Barnacle goose]] is that the Barnacle Geese emerge fully formed from the common [[Barnacle]] (Cirripedia).<ref> Not to be confused with the [[Goose Barnacle]]</ref> The migration patterns of may birds including the Barnacle Geese were not fully known until the late 19th or early 20th centuries. <ref>There are three patterns of migration known. 1. Breeding in eastern [[Greenland]], wintering on the [[Hebrides]] of western [[Scotland]] and in western [[Ireland]], population about 40,000. 2. Breeding on [[Svalbard]],  wintering on the [[Solway Firth]] on the England/Scotland border,     population about 24,000. 3. Breeding on [[Novaya Zemlya]], wintering in the Netherlands, population about 130,000\n\nResearch published in  2019 suggests that due to climatic conditions, the migration patterns are changing. (See, Tombre, I M;\u00a0 Oudman, T;\u00a0 Shimmings, P; Griffin, L. 2019. 'Northward range expansion in spring staging barnacle geese is a response to climatic change \u2026\u2026', Global Change Biology: 1-14.) This may result on fewer geese wintering in Scotland.  It is not possible to estimate how many geese would have migrated to  Scotland in the sixteenth century.</ref> Early medieval accounts of migration often drew on popular myths to explain why some birds seemed to disappear and then reappear during the year. <ref>A similar situation arose with the common eel. (''Anguilla anguilla'') It is still unknown for certain these how eels breed.  It is assumed that they do so in the Sargasso Sea. Myths regarding eels have been part of the Irish tradition since the time of Gerald of Wales who is largely responsible for the propagation of the Barnacle Geese myth. See. McCarthy, T. Kieran. 2014. 'Eels and People in Ireland: From Mythology to International Eel Stock Conservation.' in Katsumi Tsukamoto and Mari Kuroki (eds.), ''Eels and Humans'' (Springer Japan: Tokyo). (https://doi.org/10.1007/978-4-431-54529-3_2); also,  Gerald of Wales and John O'Meara. ''The History and Topography of Ireland''. (https://nls.ldls.org.uk/welcome.html?ark:/81055/vdc_100048951405.0x000001)\n\n5/06/2019, In the United Kingdom, the BBC carried an item concerning the Loch Ness Monster that concluded that this monster may be an eel. See, https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-highlands-islands-49495145</ref> The origins of the myth go back to the 2nd century BCE. The myth was popularised in the early 12th century by [[Gerald of Wales]]. Subsequent descriptions in medieval [[Bestiary|Bestiaries]] caused may scholars and historians to repeat and enlarge on the myth.\n\n== Pope Pius II ==\nIn 1435, Aeneas Silvius Bartholomeus <ref> Better known as Pope Pius II,  Enea Silvio Bartolomeo Piccolomini (1405-1464). He wrote two books,  \u201cFlorence A. Gragg, and Leona C. Gabel. 1988. Secret memoirs of a Renaissance Pope : the commentaries of Aeneas Sylvius Piccolomini, Pius II : an abridgement (Folio Society: London) and, \u201cPiccolomini, Aeneas Silvius, Robert Brown, Nancy Bisaha, and ProQuest (Firm). \"Europe (c. 1400-1458)\u201d</ref>, travelled to Scotland to encourage [[James I of Scotland]] to assist the French in the \u201c[[Hundred Years' War (1415\u201353)|Hundred Years War]]\u201d. He spent several months travelling around Britain. and recorded these travels in his book entitled \"''de Europa''\". A short section of the book is devoted to Scotland and Ireland.  He described James as \u201c ''\u2026 a sickly man weighed down by a fat punch ..''\u201d. He noted the cold inhospitable climate of Scotland and \u201c ''.. semi-naked paupers who were begging outside churches (and) went away happily after receiving stones as alms\u2026''\u201d. <ref>  Pope Pius probably saw the gift of coal to beggars and Bedesmen. Bedesmen  were often given coal or peat to heat the rooms in their Hospital accommodation.  </ref> Continuing in this vein, he records the following story:\n\n''\" \u2026I \u2026 heard that in Scotland there was once a tree growing on the bank of a river which produced fruits shaped like ducks. <ref> There are differences in the original sources for this story. In some the Latin \"aves\" - \"bird\" is used; in others it is \"Anetarum\" derived from \"anatum\" - \"duck\"', coming from \"anas/anatis\"; in others, \"anserum\" - \"goose\" </ref> <ref> see also, http://mdz-nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:bvb:12-bsb10159158-6 - fol.55v, line 5</ref> \"When these were nearly ripe, they dropped down of their own accord, some onto the earth, and some into the water. Those that landed on the earth rotted away, but those that sank into the water instantly came to life, swam out from below the water, and immediately  flew into the air, equipped with feathers and wings. When I eagerly investigated this matter, I learned that miracles always recede further into the distance and that the famous tree was to be found not in Scotland but in the Orkney islands\u2026\"''\n\nIt is believed that this story from Pope Pius II is the first recorded account of the Barnacle Geese myth in Scotland. <ref> See the following sources for details of the story told by Pope Pius II in \"de Europa\" and \"Commentaries\". Pius, Florence A. Gragg, and Leona C. Gabel. 1988. Secret memoirs of a Renaissance Pope : the commentaries of Aeneas Sylvius Piccolomini, Pius II : an abridgement (Folio Society: London); Piccolomini, Aeneas Silvius, Robert Brown, Nancy Bisaha, and ProQuest (Firm). \"Europe (c. 1400-1458).\" - at - http://ebookcentral.proquest.com/lib/abdn/detail.action?docID=3135080''; and, \"Cosmographia, 1509, (Paris)\". The book by Nancy Bisaha and Robert Brown \" Europe (c. 1400-1458) contains an extensive bibliography.? The biography of Pope Pius II, Ady, Cecilia M. 1913. Pius II (Aeneas Silvius Piccolomini) : the Humanist Pope (Methuen: London). contains a Bibliography and  an account of the Barnacle Geese story - p. 44. </ref>\n\n== Hector Boece ==\nSome 75 years later,  [[Hector Boece]] in his \"S''cotorum Historiae a Prima Gentis Origine''\" <ref> Boece, H. and G. Ferrerio (1574). Scotorum historiae a prima gentis origine ... libri XIX. Parisiis, Du Puys. The earliest version of this work about the history of Scotland dates from 1527. </ref> gave further credence to this story with an account of a discussion he had with his friend and colleague Canon Alexander Galloway <ref>[[Canon Alexander Galloway]] was an eminent scholar and canon priest in [[St Machar's Cathedral]] in Old Aberdeen. He is best remembered as a liturgist, master of works and academic to [[Bishops of Aberdeen]] from Elphinstone to Gordon. </ref> on an island in what is now called the Western Isles <ref> sometimes called Thule</ref>. The event, if it occurred,  was sometime between c.1506x1520. Boece allows Galloway in the narrative to give two contrasting accounts of the geese story.  Boece records:\n\n<blockquote>''\" \u2026. It remains for me (Boece) to discuss those geese commonly called clacks, (claiks)   which are commonly but wrongly imagined to be born on trees in these islands, on the basis of what I have learned from my diligent investigation of this thing. \u2026.. I will not hesitate to describe something I myself witnessed seven years ago\u2026 Alexander Galloway, parson of Kinkell, who, besides being a man of outstanding probity, is possessed of an unmatched zeal for studying wonders\u2026 When he was pulling up some driftwood and saw that seashells were clinging to it from one end to the other, he was surprised by the unusual nature of the thing, and, out of a zeal to understand it, opened them up, whereupon he was more amazed than ever, for within them he discovered, not sea creatures, but rather birds, of a size similar to the shells that contained them \u2026. small shells contained birds of a proportionately small size\u2026.. So, he quickly ran to me, whom he knew to be gripped with a great curiosity for investigating suchlike matters and revealed the entire thing to me\u2026..\u201d''</blockquote>\n\n<ref> There are a number of editions of Boece\u2019s History of Scotland. John Bellenden and Raphael Holinshead provide the basis many editions. The 1575 edition by John Ferrier is used for reference in this entry. A modern translation from the Latin is provided by  Dana Sutton http://www.philological.bham.ac.uk/boece/  is also used. Two sources are recommended for the \u201cClaik Geese\u201d story: Alasdair M. Stewart, 'Hector Boece and \u201cClaik\u201d Geese', Northern Scotland, 8 (First Series) (1988);  and, Edward Heron Allen, Barnacles in Nature and in Myth (London,1928). NB: The Mar Lodge edition of Historia does not contain the story of the geese. This volume is now in the Morgan Library and Museum, New York. A recent edition of Boece's story about the Barnacle Geese can be found in, Dana F. Sutton, Hector Boethius, - Scotorum Historia (1575 version) http://www.philological.bham.ac.uk/boece/, 2010), Ch. 33 & 34. The text above is a translation from Alasdair M. Stewart (1988), pp. 17-23.</ref>\nThe Claik or Clack Geese <ref> Barnacle Geese are known in [[Scots language]] as \u201cClaik Geese\u201d. \u201cClaik\u201d is the Scots word for a barnacle. See, \"Claik goose n. comb.\". Dictionary of the Scots Language. 2004. Scottish Language Dictionaries Ltd. <http://www.dsl.ac.uk/entry/snd/claik_goose>,  [Accessed 1 Nov 2017];  The OED gives a wider variety of explanation including the sound made by Barnacle Geese (Anas leucopsis)\"claik, n.\" OED Online, Oxford University Press, June 2017</ref> as they were known to Boece survived scrutiny during the [[Scottish Enlightenment]]. The age of the myth and the lack of empirical evidence on [[Bird migration]] led to several other accounts of the origins of Barnacle Geese being common until the 20th century.\n\n== See also ==\nThere is a comprehensive database of Wikipedia pages relevant to Barnacle Geese starting at [[Bird migration]]. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n[[Category:Geese|barnacle goose]]\n[[Category:Ireland]]\n[[Category:Irish mythology]]\n[[Category:Nature|mythology]]\n[[Category:Scottish mythology]]\n[[Category:Wales]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:From Topographia Hibernica British Library MS 13 B VIII.jpg|thumb|From Topographia Hibernica British Library MS 13 B VIII]] \nA [[myth]] about the origins of  the [[Barnacle goose]] is that the Barnacle Geese emerge fully formed from the common [[Barnacle]] (Cirripedia).<ref> Not to be confused with the [[Goose Barnacle]]</ref> The migration patterns of may birds including the Barnacle Geese were not fully known until the late 19th or early 20th centuries. <ref>There are three patterns of migration known. 1. Breeding in eastern [[Greenland]], wintering on the [[Hebrides]] of western [[Scotland]] and in western [[Ireland]], population about 40,000. 2. Breeding on [[Svalbard]],  wintering on the [[Solway Firth]] on the England/Scotland border,     population about 24,000. 3. Breeding on [[Novaya Zemlya]], wintering in the Netherlands, population about 130,000\n\nResearch published in  2019 suggests that due to climatic conditions, the migration patterns are changing. (See, Tombre, I M;\u00a0 Oudman, T;\u00a0 Shimmings, P; Griffin, L. 2019. 'Northward range expansion in spring staging barnacle geese is a response to climatic change \u2026\u2026', Global Change Biology: 1-14.) This may result on fewer geese wintering in Scotland.  It is not possible to estimate how many geese would have migrated to  Scotland in the sixteenth century.</ref> Early medieval accounts of migration often drew on popular myths to explain why some birds seemed to disappear and then reappear during the year. <ref>A similar situation arose with the common eel. (''Anguilla anguilla'') It is still unknown for certain these how eels breed.  It is assumed that they do so in the Sargasso Sea. Myths regarding eels have been part of the Irish tradition since the time of Gerald of Wales who is largely responsible for the propagation of the Barnacle Geese myth. See. McCarthy, T. Kieran. 2014. 'Eels and People in Ireland: From Mythology to International Eel Stock Conservation.' in Katsumi Tsukamoto and Mari Kuroki (eds.), ''Eels and Humans'' (Springer Japan: Tokyo). (https://doi.org/10.1007/978-4-431-54529-3_2); also,  Gerald of Wales and John O'Meara. ''The History and Topography of Ireland''. (https://nls.ldls.org.uk/welcome.html?ark:/81055/vdc_100048951405.0x000001)\n\n5/06/2019, In the United Kingdom, the BBC carried an item concerning the Loch Ness Monster that concluded that this monster may be an eel. See, https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-highlands-islands-49495145</ref> The origins of the myth go back to the 2nd century BCE. The myth was popularised in the early 12th century by [[Gerald of Wales]]. Subsequent descriptions in medieval [[Bestiary|Bestiaries]] caused may scholars and historians to repeat and enlarge on the myth.\n\n=== Pope Pius II ===\nIn 1435, Aeneas Silvius Bartholomeus <ref> Better known as Pope Pius II,  Enea Silvio Bartolomeo Piccolomini (1405-1464). He wrote two books,  \u201cFlorence A. Gragg, and Leona C. Gabel. 1988. Secret memoirs of a Renaissance Pope : the commentaries of Aeneas Sylvius Piccolomini, Pius II : an abridgement (Folio Society: London) and, \u201cPiccolomini, Aeneas Silvius, Robert Brown, Nancy Bisaha, and ProQuest (Firm). \"Europe (c. 1400-1458)\u201d</ref>, travelled to Scotland to encourage [[James I of Scotland]] to assist the French in the \u201c[[Hundred Years' War (1415\u201353)|Hundred Years War]]\u201d. He spent several months travelling around Britain. and recorded these travels in his book entitled \"''de Europa''\". A short section of the book is devoted to Scotland and Ireland.  He described James as \u201c ''\u2026 a sickly man weighed down by a fat punch ..''\u201d. He noted the cold inhospitable climate of Scotland and \u201c ''.. semi-naked paupers who were begging outside churches (and) went away happily after receiving stones as alms\u2026''\u201d. <ref>  Pope Pius probably saw the gift of coal to beggars and Bedesmen. Bedesmen  were often given coal or peat to heat the rooms in their Hospital accommodation.  </ref> Continuing in this vein, he records the following story:\n\n''\" \u2026I \u2026 heard that in Scotland there was once a tree growing on the bank of a river which produced fruits shaped like ducks. <ref> There are differences in the original sources for this story. In some the Latin \"aves\" - \"bird\" is used; in others it is \"Anetarum\" derived from \"anatum\" - \"duck\"', coming from \"anas/anatis\"; in others, \"anserum\" - \"goose\" </ref> <ref> see also, http://mdz-nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:bvb:12-bsb10159158-6 - fol.55v, line 5</ref> \"When these were nearly ripe, they dropped down of their own accord, some onto the earth, and some into the water. Those that landed on the earth rotted away, but those that sank into the water instantly came to life, swam out from below the water, and immediately  flew into the air, equipped with feathers and wings. When I eagerly investigated this matter, I learned that miracles always recede further into the distance and that the famous tree was to be found not in Scotland but in the Orkney islands\u2026\"''\n\nIt is believed that this story from Pope Pius II is the first recorded account of the Barnacle Geese myth in Scotland. <ref> See the following sources for details of the story told by Pope Pius II in \"de Europa\" and \"Commentaries\". Pius, Florence A. Gragg, and Leona C. Gabel. 1988. Secret memoirs of a Renaissance Pope : the commentaries of Aeneas Sylvius Piccolomini, Pius II : an abridgement (Folio Society: London); Piccolomini, Aeneas Silvius, Robert Brown, Nancy Bisaha, and ProQuest (Firm). \"Europe (c. 1400-1458).\" - at - http://ebookcentral.proquest.com/lib/abdn/detail.action?docID=3135080''; and, \"Cosmographia, 1509, (Paris)\". The book by Nancy Bisaha and Robert Brown \" Europe (c. 1400-1458) contains an extensive bibliography.? The biography of Pope Pius II, Ady, Cecilia M. 1913. Pius II (Aeneas Silvius Piccolomini) : the Humanist Pope (Methuen: London). contains a Bibliography and  an account of the Barnacle Geese story - p. 44. </ref>\n\n=== Hector Boece ===\nSome 75 years later,  [[Hector Boece]] in his \"S''cotorum Historiae a Prima Gentis Origine''\" <ref> Boece, H. and G. Ferrerio (1574). Scotorum historiae a prima gentis origine ... libri XIX. Parisiis, Du Puys. The earliest version of this work about the history of Scotland dates from 1527. </ref> gave further credence to this story with an account of a discussion he had with his friend and colleague Canon Alexander Galloway <ref>[[Canon Alexander Galloway]] was an eminent scholar and canon priest in [[St Machar's Cathedral]] in Old Aberdeen. He is best remembered as a liturgist, master of works and academic to [[Bishops of Aberdeen]] from Elphinstone to Gordon. </ref> on an island in what is now called the Western Isles <ref> sometimes called Thule</ref>. The event, if it occurred,  was sometime between c.1506x1520. Boece allows Galloway in the narrative to give two contrasting accounts of the geese story.  Boece records:\n\n<blockquote>''\" \u2026. It remains for me (Boece) to discuss those geese commonly called clacks, (claiks)   which are commonly but wrongly imagined to be born on trees in these islands, on the basis of what I have learned from my diligent investigation of this thing. \u2026.. I will not hesitate to describe something I myself witnessed seven years ago\u2026 Alexander Galloway, parson of Kinkell, who, besides being a man of outstanding probity, is possessed of an unmatched zeal for studying wonders\u2026 When he was pulling up some driftwood and saw that seashells were clinging to it from one end to the other, he was surprised by the unusual nature of the thing, and, out of a zeal to understand it, opened them up, whereupon he was more amazed than ever, for within them he discovered, not sea creatures, but rather birds, of a size similar to the shells that contained them \u2026. small shells contained birds of a proportionately small size\u2026.. So, he quickly ran to me, whom he knew to be gripped with a great curiosity for investigating suchlike matters and revealed the entire thing to me\u2026..\u201d''</blockquote>\n\n<ref> There are a number of editions of Boece\u2019s History of Scotland. John Bellenden and Raphael Holinshead provide the basis many editions. The 1575 edition by John Ferrier is used for reference in this entry. A modern translation from the Latin is provided by  Dana Sutton http://www.philological.bham.ac.uk/boece/  is also used. Two sources are recommended for the \u201cClaik Geese\u201d story: Alasdair M. Stewart, 'Hector Boece and \u201cClaik\u201d Geese', Northern Scotland, 8 (First Series) (1988);  and, Edward Heron Allen, Barnacles in Nature and in Myth (London,1928). NB: The Mar Lodge edition of Historia does not contain the story of the geese. This volume is now in the Morgan Library and Museum, New York. A recent edition of Boece's story about the Barnacle Geese can be found in, Dana F. Sutton, Hector Boethius, - Scotorum Historia (1575 version) http://www.philological.bham.ac.uk/boece/, 2010), Ch. 33 & 34. The text above is a translation from Alasdair M. Stewart (1988), pp. 17-23.</ref>\nThe Claik or Clack Geese <ref> Barnacle Geese are known in [[Scots language]] as \u201cClaik Geese\u201d. \u201cClaik\u201d is the Scots word for a barnacle. See, \"Claik goose n. comb.\". Dictionary of the Scots Language. 2004. Scottish Language Dictionaries Ltd. <http://www.dsl.ac.uk/entry/snd/claik_goose>,  [Accessed 1 Nov 2017];  The OED gives a wider variety of explanation including the sound made by Barnacle Geese (Anas leucopsis)\"claik, n.\" OED Online, Oxford University Press, June 2017</ref> as they were known to Boece survived scrutiny during the [[Scottish Enlightenment]]. The age of the myth and the lack of empirical evidence on [[Bird migration]] led to several other accounts of the origins of Barnacle Geese being common until the 20th century.\n\n==== See also ====\nThere is a comprehensive database of Wikipedia pages relevant to Barnacle Geese starting at [[Bird migration]]. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n[[Category:Geese|barnacle goose]]\n[[Category:Ireland]]\n[[Category:Irish mythology]]\n[[Category:Nature|mythology]]\n[[Category:Scottish mythology]]\n[[Category:Wales]]\n", "name_user": "Prana1111", "label": "safe", "comment": "only 2 equals signs are needed for creating sections", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barnacle_Geese_Myth"}
{"title_page": "Andrea Pirlo", "text_new": "{{redirect|Pirlo|the Italian alcoholic beverage|Pirlo (aperitivo)}}\n{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Italian association football player}}\n{{good article}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name               = Andrea Pirlo\n| image              = Andrea Pirlo NYCFC.JPG\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Pirlo playing for [[New York City FC|New York City]] in 2016\n| fullname           = Andrea Pirlo<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/tournament/competition/01/22/85/78/fwc_2010_squadlists.pdf |title=FIFA World Cup South Africa 2010: List of Players: Italy |format=PDF |page=15 |publisher=FIFA |date=4 June 2010 |accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1979|5|19|df=y}}<ref name=\"Italy - A. Pirlo - Profile - Soccerway\"/>\n| birth_place        = [[Flero]], Italy\n| height             = 1.77 m<ref name=\"FIFA Confederations Cup Brazil 2013 Player Profile: Andrea Pirlo\"/>\n| position           = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1        = 1992\u20131995 |youthclubs1 = [[Brescia Calcio|Brescia]]\n| years1             = 1995\u20131998 |clubs1      = [[Brescia Calcio|Brescia]]          |caps1 = 47  |goals1 = 6 <!-- LEAGUE APPEARANCES AND GOALS ONLY !-->\n| years2             = 1998\u20132001 |clubs2      = [[Inter Milan]]                     |caps2 = 22  |goals2 = 0 <!-- LEAGUE APPEARANCES AND GOALS ONLY !-->\n| years3             = 1999\u20132000 |clubs3      = \u2192 [[Reggina Calcio|Reggina]] (loan) |caps3 = 28  |goals3 = 6 <!-- LEAGUE APPEARANCES AND GOALS ONLY !-->\n| years4             = 2001      |clubs4      = \u2192 [[Brescia Calcio|Brescia]] (loan) |caps4 = 10  |goals4 = 0 <!-- LEAGUE APPEARANCES AND GOALS ONLY !-->\n| years5             = 2001\u20132011 |clubs5      = [[A.C. Milan]]                      |caps5 = 284 |goals5 = 32 <!-- LEAGUE APPEARANCES AND GOALS ONLY !-->\n| years6             = 2011\u20132015 |clubs6      = [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]          |caps6 = 119 |goals6 = 16 <!-- LEAGUE APPEARANCES AND GOALS ONLY !-->\n| years7             = 2015\u20132017 |clubs7      = [[New York City FC|New York City]]  |caps7 = 60  |goals7 = 1 <!-- LEAGUE APPEARANCES AND GOALS ONLY !-->\n| totalcaps = 570  |totalgoals = 61 <!-- LEAGUE APPEARANCES AND GOALS ONLY !-->\n| nationalyears1 = 1994      |nationalteam1 = [[Italy national under-15 football team|Italy U15]]            |nationalcaps1 = 3   |nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1995      |nationalteam2 = [[Italy national under-16 football team|Italy U16]]            |nationalcaps2 = 6   |nationalgoals2 = 2\n| nationalyears3 = 1995      |nationalteam3 = [[Italy national under-17 football team|Italy U17]]            |nationalcaps3 = 4   |nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 1995\u20131997 |nationalteam4 = [[Italy national under-18 football team|Italy U18]]            |nationalcaps4 = 18  |nationalgoals4 = 7\n| nationalyears5 = 1998\u20132002 |nationalteam5 = [[Italy national under-21 football team|Italy U21]]            |nationalcaps5 = 37  |nationalgoals5 = 15\n| nationalyears6 = 2000\u20132004 |nationalteam6 = [[Italy Olympic football team|Italy Olympic]]                  |nationalcaps6 = 9   |nationalgoals6 = 1\n| nationalyears7 = 2002\u20132015 |nationalteam7 = [[Italy national football team|Italy]]                         |nationalcaps7 = 116 |nationalgoals7 = 13\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalSport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{ITA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition |[[Football at the Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Football at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2004 Athens]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition |[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|Winner|[[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 Germany]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UEFA European Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[UEFA Euro 2012|2012 Poland\u2013Ukraine]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition |[[FIFA Confederations Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|3rd|[[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup|2013 Brazil]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UEFA European Under-21 Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|Winner|[[2000 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2000 Slovakia]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''Andrea Pirlo''' {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic|Ufficiale OMRI]]}}<ref name=omri1/><ref name=omri2/> ({{IPA-it|an\u02c8dr\u025b\u02d0a \u02c8pirlo}}; born 19 May 1979) is an Italian former professional [[association football|footballer]]. Pirlo was usually deployed as a [[Midfielder#Deep-lying playmaker|deep-lying playmaker]] in [[Midfielder|midfield]] for both his club and national teams and he is widely regarded as one of the greatest ever exponents of this position due to his vision, ball control, technique, creativity and passing ability, as well as for being a [[Direct free kick|free-kick]] specialist.<ref name=\"Soccerlens.com\">{{cite web |url=http://soccerlens.com/born-again-how-the-deep-lying-midfielder-position-is-reviving-careers/32421/ |title=Born Again: How the Deep-Lying Midfielder Position is Reviving Careers |website=Soccerlens |date=31 July 2009 |accessdate=15 May 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo Player Profile - ESPN FC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/player/11888/andrea-pirlo |title=Andrea Pirlo: Player Profile |website=ESPN FC |accessdate=4 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"A.C. Milan Hall of Fame: Andrea Pirlo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.acmilan.com/en/andrea-pirlo |title=A.C. Milan Hall of Fame: Andrea Pirlo |publisher=A.C. Milan |accessdate=31 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nPirlo began his club career as an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]] with his hometown club [[Brescia Calcio|Brescia]], whom he helped win a [[Serie B]] title and subsequent promotion to Serie A in 1997. His promising performances led to a move to [[Inter Milan]] in 1998, but he struggled to gain playing time at his new club, and was sent on loan in 1999. Despite successful spells with [[Reggina Calcio|Reggina]] and a return to Brescia, Pirlo was still unable to break into Inter's starting line-up and was sold to cross-city rivals [[A.C. Milan]] in 2001. At Milan, manager [[Carlo Ancelotti]] decided to transition Pirlo into a deep-lying playmaker to orchestrate the team's attacks. Pirlo excelled in his new role and soon developed into a world-class midfielder, and won a plethora of trophies, including two [[UEFA Champions League]]s, two [[UEFA Super Cup]]s, two [[Serie A]] titles, a [[FIFA Club World Cup]], a [[Supercoppa Italiana]], and a [[Coppa Italia]].<ref name=\"A.C. Milan Hall of Fame: Andrea Pirlo\"/> After joining [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] on a free transfer in 2011, who had gone trophyless since 2003, he added four more Serie A titles, which he won consecutively, as well as two Supercoppa Italiana titles, and a Coppa Italia. After playing in Italy for over 20 seasons, Pirlo joined [[Major League Soccer]] franchise [[New York City FC|New York City]] in 2015, helping the team to reach the playoffs in his second and third seasons before retiring in 2017.\n\nAt international level, Pirlo is the [[Italy national football team records#Appearances|fifth-most]] [[Cap (sports)|capped]] player in the history of the Italian national team with [[List of footballers with 100 or more caps|116 caps]] between 2002 and 2015. He played for the Italian youth teams at [[Italy national under-15 football team|U15]], [[Italy national under-18 football team|U18]] and [[Italy national under-21 football team|U21]] level, [[Captain (association football)|captaining]] and leading the latter to victory in the [[2000 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] as the Golden Player and Top Scorer of the tournament. He joined the Italian senior team in September 2002 and captained the Olympic team to a bronze medal in the [[Football at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2004 Olympics]]. Later, he was instrumental in the senior team's victory in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]]. He was named [[Man of the Match]] three times, including the [[2006 FIFA World Cup Final|final]], more than any other player in the tournament, and ultimately won the Bronze Ball (awarded to the third best player of the tournament) also being elected to the [[FIFA World Cup 2006#All-star team|Team of the Tournament]]. He was also elected as part of the [[UEFA Euro 2012]] [[UEFA European Championship Teams of the Tournament#Poland and Ukraine 2012|Team of the Tournament]] after leading Italy to the [[UEFA Euro 2012 Final|final]], winning three Man of the Match awards in the process, the most of any player along with [[Andr\u00e9s Iniesta]]. He has also represented the Italian senior team at the [[UEFA Euro 2004|2004]] and [[UEFA Euro 2008|2008]] [[UEFA European Championships]], the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010]] and [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014]] [[FIFA World Cup]]s and the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup|2009]] and [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup|2013]] [[FIFA Confederations Cup]]s, finishing third in the latter edition in Brazil, where he was also elected to the [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup#Awards|Team of the Tournament]].\n\nPirlo came in third, second, fourth and third twice more in the [[International Federation of Football History & Statistics]] [[IFFHS World's Best Playmaker|World Playmaker of the Year]] awards in 2006, 2007, 2012, 2013 and 2015, respectively.<ref name=\"iffhs.de\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iffhs.de/?d847e4a95e99a54f84d85fe8f55005fdcdc3bfcdc0aec70aeecf8a3e12 |title=IFFHS |publisher=International Federation of Football History & Statistics |author=Ingo Faulhaber |accessdate=15 May 2012}}</ref> He placed fourth in the [[UEFA Best Player in Europe Award#2011.E2.80.9312|2012 UEFA Best Player in Europe Award]]<ref name=\"uefa.com\">{{cite news |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefa/uefa-best-player-award/news/newsid=1842518.html |title=Iniesta, Messi, Ronaldo up for Best Player Award |publisher=UEFA |date=14 August 2012 |accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref> and seventh in the [[UEFA Best Player in Europe Award#2014.E2.80.9315|2015]] edition.<ref name=\"Best Player in Europe\">{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2270699.html |title=Best Player in Europe: Messi, Ronaldo or Su\u00e1rez |publisher=UEFA |date=12 August 2015 |accessdate=12 August 2015}}</ref> He placed seventh in the [[2007 FIFA World Player of the Year|2007 FIFA World Player]], fifth in the [[2007 Ballon d'Or]] and seventh in the [[2012 FIFA Ballon d'Or]] award. He was also named as part of the 2006 [[FIFPro]] World XI and the [[UEFA Team of the Year|2012 UEFA Team of the Year]].<ref name=\"FIFPro World XI 2006\">{{cite web |title=FIFPro World XI 2006 |url=http://www.fifpro.org/fifpro_world/award_history/2006 |publisher=FIFPro |accessdate=24 August 2012}}</ref> In 2012, 2013 and 2014, Pirlo was also elected as [[Serie A Footballer of the Year]] and was also named as part of the [[Serie A team of the Year]].<ref name=\"Serie A Team of the Year\">{{cite web |title=Serie A Team of the Year |url=http://forzaitalianfootball.com/2013/01/gran-gala-del-calcio-2012-winners/ |accessdate=30 January 2013}}</ref> After helping Juventus to the [[2015 UEFA Champions League Final]], he was named to the [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League#Squad of the season|squad of the season]]. In 2012, Pirlo was named the eighth best footballer in the world by ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://talenticalcio.it/classifica-100-migliori-calciatori-2012-stilata-the-guardian/7691/ |title=Classifica 100 migliori calciatori del 2012 stilata dal The Guardian |language=Italian |accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref> In 2013, [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] ranked him the fifth best player in Europe.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11667/8772182/Messi-and-Ronaldo-joined-by-Ribery-in-top-three-of-new-list-of-Europe-s-top-50-stars |title=Messi and Ronaldo joined by Ribery in top three of new list of Europe's top 50 stars |publisher=Sky Sports |date=12 June 2013 |accessdate=14 June 2013}}</ref> In 2015, ''[[France Football]]'' rated him as one of the 10 best footballers in the world who were over the age of 36.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.francefootball.fr/news/Le-top-10-des-meilleurs-vieux/559763 |title=Le top 10 des meilleurs vieux|trans-title=The top 10 of the best oldies |website=France Football |language=French |author1=Thomas Simon |date=19 May 2015 |accessdate=4 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nAmazing fact\n\nPirlo has a static caravan at his favourite holiday destination \nDumbarton in Scotland\n\n==Club career==\n===1994\u20132001: Early years and realisation of role===\nPirlo was born in [[Flero]], Italy, in the province of [[Brescia]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lastampa.it/2012/12/24/sport/calcio/qui-juve/pirlo-da-bimbo-non-desideravo-altro-che-diventare-un-campione-di-calcio-vJgzFaH6AoesbESiMrBSyK/pagina.html |title=Genio d\u2019artista e cuore da mediano Pirlo: \"Sono nato per avere la palla\" |newspaper=La Stampa |language=Italian |date=24 December 2012 |accessdate=3 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204074126/http://www.lastampa.it/2012/12/24/sport/calcio/qui-juve/pirlo-da-bimbo-non-desideravo-altro-che-diventare-un-campione-di-calcio-vJgzFaH6AoesbESiMrBSyK/pagina.html |archive-date=4 February 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He began his career with the Flero youth team,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://brescia.corriere.it/brescia/notizie/sport/12_giugno_26/20120626BRE08_19-201760881812.shtml |title=Pirlo e il cucchiaino d'oro: \"Lo faceva gi\u00e0 da ragazzino\" |newspaper=Corriere della Sera |last1=Passerini |first1=Carlos |date=26 June 2012 |accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref> later moving to Voluntas,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bresciaoggi.it/stories/180_interviste/256541_e_ora_vincer_con_la_juvema_ho_il_brescia_nel_cuore/?refresh_ce#scroll=336 |title=E ora vincer\u00f2 con la Juve, ma ho il Brescia nel cuore |newspaper=Bresciaoggi |language=Italian |author=Vincenzo Corbetta |accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref> and subsequently joined the youth sector of local club [[Brescia Calcio|Brescia]] in 1994, where he initially played predominantly as a supporting forward.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/1998/08/06/pirlo-ecco-la-star-dell-estate.html |title=Pirlo, ecco la star dell' estate |newspaper=la Repubblica |author=Corrado Zunino |language=Italian |date=6 August 1998 |accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref> In [[1994\u201395 Serie A|1995]], at the age of 16, Pirlo made his [[Serie A]] debut for Brescia against [[A.C. Reggiana 1919|Reggiana]], on 21 May, becoming Brescia's youngest player to make an appearance in Serie A. He was promoted by his coach [[Mircea Lucescu]].<ref name=\"bresciaoggi.it\">{{cite news |url=http://www.bresciaoggi.it/stories/Sport/342252_pirlo_il_genio_dei_record_ora__400_volte_grande/?refresh_ce#scroll=96 |title=Pirlo, il genio dei record Ora \u00e8 400 volte grande |newspaper=Bresciaoggi |author=Sergio Zanca |accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/juventus/?action=read&idnet=dHV0dG9qdXZlLmNvbS0xMTIwMDA |title=ESCLUSIVA TJ \u2013 Marco Schenardi: \"Lucescu? Un innovatore, tanto da farci una tesi a Coverciano. Ho visto crescere Pirlo, incredibile pensarlo leader\" |website=TUTTOmercatoWEB.com |language=Italian |accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://football-italia.net/20442/memories-16-year-old-star-pirlo |title=Memories of 16-year-old star Pirlo |date=26 June 2012 |accessdate=20 September 2012 |website=Football Italia |publisher=Tiro Media}}</ref> The following season, he did not appear with the senior team, although he was able to capture the [[Torneo di Viareggio]] with the youth team.<ref name=\"bresciaoggi.it\"/> After breaking into the Brescia first team during the [[1996\u201397 Serie B]] season, he helped the club to gain Serie A promotion the following season by winning the [[Serie B]] title.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2001/gennaio/27/Pirlo_Brescia_trova_Baggio_co_0_0101271956.shtml |title=Pirlo al Brescia trova Baggio |newspaper=Corriere della Sera |language=Italian |date=27 January 2001 |accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref> He scored his first goal in Serie A during the [[1997\u201398 Serie A|1997\u201398 season]], in a 4\u20130 home win over [[Vicenza Calcio|Vicenza]] on 19 October 1997.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/1997/10/20/brescia-hubner-neri-cancellano-il-vicenza.html |title=BRESCIA, HUBNER E NERI CANCELLANO IL VICENZA |newspaper=la Repubblica |language=Italian |author=Roberto Bianchin |date=20 October 1997 |accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nDue to his performances with Brescia, Pirlo was spotted by [[Inter Milan]] coach Lucescu, who signed the playmaker. Pirlo was unable to break into the first squad permanently, however, and Inter finished eighth in the [[1998\u201399 Serie A|1998\u201399]] Serie A campaign.<ref name=\"making\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/making-pirlo-early-age-i-knew-i-was-better-others#:Fr_bDGMuLGBWPA |title=The making of Pirlo: \"From an early age, I knew I was better than others\" |website=FourFourTwo |author1=Andrew Murray |date=7 July 2015 |accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> Inter loaned Pirlo to Reggina for the [[1999\u20132000 Serie A|1999\u20132000 season]], alongside young Inter teammates [[Roberto Baronio]] and [[Mohamed Kallon]].<ref name=\"archiviostorico.gazzetta.it\">{{cite news |title=Reggina: Possanzini e Marazzina sulla scia di Pirlo, Baronio e Kallon |url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2000/ottobre/13/Reggina_Possanzini_Marazzina_sulla_scia_ga_0_00101312031.shtml |newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |date=13 October 2000 |accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref> After an impressive season,<ref name=\"archiviostorico.gazzetta.it\"/> he returned to Inter but was once again unable to break into the first team, making just four league appearances.<ref name=\"making\"/> He spent the second half of the [[2000\u201301 Serie A|2000\u201301 season]] on loan at his former club, Brescia, where he played alongside his childhood idol, offensive playmaker [[Roberto Baggio]].<ref name=\"Pirlo al Brescia, magie in coppia con Baggio\">{{cite web |url=http://sport.sky.it/sport/calciomercato/2015/01/12/mercato_story_pirlo_al_brescia_mazzone_baggio.html |title=Mercato story: Pirlo al Brescia, magie in coppia con Baggio |publisher=Sky Sport |language=Italian |author1=Vanni Spinella |date=13 January 2015 |accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"tuttomercatoweb.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/rassegna-stampa/roberto-baggio-pirlo-e-un-fuoriclasse-79874 |title=Roberto Baggio: \"Pirlo \u00e8 un fuoriclasse\" |website=TUTTOmercatoWEB.com |language=Italian |accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://vivoazzurro.it/news/pirlo-tra-tutti-trofei-vinti-scelgo-assolutamente-il-mondiale/ |title=Pirlo: \"Tra tutti i trofei vinti scelgo assolutamente il Mondiale!\" |publisher=Italian Football Federation |language=Italian |accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref> As Baggio occupied the [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfield]] role for Brescia, manager [[Carlo Mazzone]] made a ground-breaking decision, becoming the first coach to deploy Pirlo as a [[Playmaker#Deep-lying playmakers|deep-lying playmaker]], rather than as an offensive midfielder, a deeper creative role in which he particularly excelled, due to his long passing ability.<ref name=\"Pirlo al Brescia, magie in coppia con Baggio\"/><ref name=\"La Repubblica\">{{cite news |url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2008/08/13/da-tardelli-desailly-cambiare-serve.html |title=Da Tardelli a Desailly, cambiare serve |newspaper=la Repubblica |language=Italian |author=Christian Giordano |date=13 August 2008 |accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref> Despite initially struggling against relegation that season,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/campionato/bag/bag/bag.html |title=Baggio, i gol per un sogno \"Il Mondiale, poi smetto\" |newspaper=la Repubblica |language=Italian |author1=Gianni Piva |date=2 March 2001 |accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref> Brescia would eventually manage a comfortable seventh-place finish in Serie A, also reaching the [[2000\u201301 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]] quarter-finals, qualifying for the [[2001 UEFA Intertoto Cup|2001 Intertoto Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/campionato_partite/bresciabari/bresciabari/bresciabari.html |title=Mazzone fa il capolavoro Brescia settimo in classifica |newspaper=la Repubblica |language=Italian |date=17 June 2001 |accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref> A notable moment in Pirlo's Brescia career was his long pass which assisted Baggio's late equaliser against [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] at the [[Stadio delle Alpi]], on 1 April 2001.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/campionato_partite/juventusbrescia/juventusbrescia/juventusbrescia.html |title=La vendetta di Baggio Juve, scudetto lontano |newspaper=la Repubblica |language=Italian |date=1 April 2001 |accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2001/aprile/02/Baggio_taglia_strada_alla_Juve_co_0_0104022880.shtml |title=Baggio taglia la strada alla Juve |newspaper=Corriere della Sera |language=Italian |author1=Roberto Perrone |author2=Guido Vaciago |date=2 April 2001 |accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n===A.C. Milan===\n====2001\u20132004: Domestic and European success====\nAfter three seasons on the Inter books, Pirlo was sold to rivals [[A.C. Milan]] for 33&nbsp;billion [[Italian lire]] (\u20ac17,043,078)<ref>FC Internazionale Milano SpA ''bilancio'' (financial report and accounts) on 30 June 2001, [http://www.registroimprese.it PDF purchased from Italian C.C.I.A.A.] {{in lang|it}}</ref> on 30 June 2001, the last day of 2000\u201301 financial year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.inter.it/aas/news/reader?L=it&N=3284 |title=L'Inter ha ceduto pirlo al Milan |date=30 June 2001 |accessdate=3 February 2010 |publisher=Inter Milan |language=Italian}}</ref> The transfer fee was partially funded by the movement of [[Dra\u017een Brn\u010di\u0107]] in the opposite direction for an undisclosed fee. In the same window Inter swapped [[Cristian Brocchi]] (25&nbsp;billion lire;<ref name=Inter2002bilancio>F.C. Internazionale Milano SpA Report and Accounts on 30 June 2002 {{in lang|it}}, [http://www.registroimprese.it/ CCIAA]</ref> \u20ac12.9&nbsp;million) for [[Andr\u00e9s Guglielminpietro|Guly]] (undisclosed fee; \u20ac8.537&nbsp;million profit)<ref name=\"Milan2002bilancio\">A.C. Milan SpA Report and Accounts on 30 June 2002 {{in lang|it}}</ref> and [[Matteo Bogani]] for [[Paolo Ginestra]]. The deals were later reported by the Italian press to have been undertaken to create \"false profit\" by inflating the players' values in the transfer fees in the swap deal. The exchange involving Ginestra and Bogani created an approximate \u20ac3.5&nbsp;million \"profit\" for both clubs, but this actually manifested itself in terms of useless registration rights.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2002/novembre/06/moda_calciatore_salvabilanci_co_0_0211067362.shtml |title=Va di moda il calciatore salvabilanci |author=Malagutti Vittorio |date=6 November 2002 |accessdate=31 March 2010 |newspaper=Corriere della Sera |language=Italian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://archivio2.unita.it/v2/carta/showoldpdf.asp?anno=2003&mese=03&file=08SPO22a |title=Milan e Inter, plusvalenze incrociate con la vendita dei calciatori |date=8 March 2003 |accessdate=31 March 2010 |newspaper=l'Unit\u00e0 |language=Italian}}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIt was at A.C. Milan, in particular under manager [[Carlo Ancelotti]], where Pirlo made big strides in developing into a world class player, and one of the best [[deep-lying playmaker]]s and set-piece specialists in the world, as he went on to achieve notable domestic and international success during his time with the club. Pirlo later recalled the period he has spent in Milan with Ancelotti: \"He changed my career, putting me in front of the defence. We shared some unforgettable moments. We had a magnificent past together.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.us/juventus/story/2432773/andrea-pirlo-says-carlo-ancelotti-changed-my-career |title=Real Madrid boss Carlo Ancelotti 'changed my career' \u2013 Andrea Pirlo |website=ESPN FC |author=Gen Gladwell |date=4 May 2015 |accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref> After Mazzone's pioneering decision to move Pirlo into a deep-seated playmaking role with Brescia during the previous season,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2001/gennaio/27/Pirlo_Brescia_trova_Baggio_co_0_0101271956.shtml |title=Pirlo al Brescia trova Baggio |newspaper=Corriere della Sera |language=Italian |date=27 January 2001 |accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref> Milan managers [[Fatih Terim]] and, in particular, Carlo Ancelotti further developed this role for him at Milan.<ref name=\"La Repubblica\"/> In Ancelotti's [[Formation (association football)#4\u20133\u20131\u20132|4\u20133\u20131\u20132]] and [[Formation (association football)#4\u20133\u20132\u20131 (the \"Christmas Tree\" formation)|4\u20133\u20132\u20131 formations]], Pirlo was deployed as a deep-lying playmaker in front of the defence,<ref>{{cite web |title=L'albero di Natale di Ancelotti |url=http://www.fifareloaded.com/2013/09/l-di-natale-di-ancelotti.html |accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> which allowed him to play alongside other talented attacking midfielders, such as [[Rivaldo]], [[Rui Costa]] and eventually [[Kak\u00e1]], replacing the gap left by Milan legend [[Demetrio Albertini]] in the deep midfield playmaking role. He would become an integral part of the Rossoneri's midfield, forming a formidable partnership with [[Gennaro Gattuso]], as well as with [[Clarence Seedorf]] and [[Massimo Ambrosini]], who also supported his playmaking role defensively. Pirlo was given the nickname ''the [[metronome]]'' during his time at the club, for the way in which he set the team's rhythm.<ref name=\"A.C. Milan Hall of Fame: Andrea Pirlo\"/><ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo Topics Page\">{{cite news |url=http://content.usatoday.com/topics/photo/People/Athletes/International+Soccer/Andrea+Pirlo/06VCdx06Vk8uu/0 |title=Andrea Pirlo Topics Page |newspaper=USA Today |date=6 February 2008 |accessdate=15 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120915020639/http://content.usatoday.com/topics/photo/People/Athletes/International+Soccer/Andrea+Pirlo/06VCdx06Vk8uu/0 |archive-date=15 September 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo: The Metronome\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/andrea-pirlo-the-metronome-1.926182 |title=Andrea Pirlo: The Metronome |publisher=CBC Sports |author1=Matthew Scianitti |date=18 May 2010 |accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/these-football-times/2015/apr/24/age-position-football-michael-carrick-andrea-pirlo-xabi-alonso |title=The relationship between a player's age and their position on a football pitch |newspaper=The Guardian |author1=Blair Newman |date=24 April 2015 |accessdate=15 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nPirlo made his Milan debut on 20 September 2001, in a 2\u20130 win over [[FC BATE Borisov|BATE Borisov]] in the [[UEFA Cup]], after coming on for [[Massimo Donati]].<ref>{{cite web |title=BATE-Milan (0\u20132) |url=http://it.archive.uefa.com/competitions/uefacup/history/season=2001/round=1551/match=68297/report=ev.html |publisher=UEFA |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140627105136/http://it.archive.uefa.com/competitions/uefacup/history/season=2001/round=1551/match=68297/report=ev.html |url-status=dead |archivedate=27 June 2014 |accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> During his [[2001\u201302 Serie A|first season]] with the club, he helped the team to a fourth-place finish [[2002\u201303 UEFA Champions League qualifying rounds|UEFA Champions League]] qualification spot, also reaching the semi-final of the [[2001\u201302 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]], the club's best ever result in the competition. On 30 March 2002, he scored his first goal with Milan in a 3\u20131 home win over [[Parma F.C.|Parma]], from a [[Direct free kick|free kick]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Pirlo e doppietta di Inzaghi il Milan scavalca il Chievo |url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio_partite/milanparma/milanparma/milanparma.html |newspaper=la Repubblica |accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:A.C. Milan lifting the European Cup after winning the 2002\u201303 UEFA Champions League - 20030528.jpg|upright=1.5|thumb|right|250px|[[A.C. Milan|Milan]] celebrations after defeating [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] 3\u20132 on penalties to win the [[2002\u201303 UEFA Champions League]].]]\n\nPirlo led Serie A in the [[2002\u201303 Serie A|2002\u201303 season]] in four categories \u2013 passes played (2589), ball possession (123 hours played and 39 minutes), successful balls (661), and successful passes (2093); he averaged almost 90 passes per game throughout the season. During this season, his second with the club, he also managed a career best of 9 goals in Serie A, as Milan finished the league in third place, also winning the [[2002\u201303 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]] over [[A.S. Roma|Roma]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio2002_serie_a/milancop/milancop/milancop.html |title=Al Milan anche la Coppa Italia |newspaper=la Repubblica |language=Italian |accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> and the [[2002\u201303 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]], beating out Italian rivals and 2003 Serie A champions Juventus in the [[2003 UEFA Champions League Final|final]] 3\u20132 on penalties, following a 0\u20130 draw after extra-time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://it.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2002/matches/round=1640/match=1045288/postmatch/commentary/index.html |title=Milan vince 3\u20132 ai rigori |publisher=UEFA |language=Italian |accessdate=4 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816210026/http://it.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season%3D2002/matches/round%3D1640/match%3D1045288/postmatch/commentary/index.html |archivedate=16 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio2002_coppe/finalissima/finalissima/finalissima.html |title=Grande Dida, coppa al Milan ma la Juve piange se stessa |newspaper=la Repubblica |language=Italian |accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> The following season saw Pirlo win the [[2003 UEFA Super Cup]] with Milan over [[FC Porto|Porto]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.repubblica.it/2003/h/sezioni/sport/calcio/milpor/milpor/milpor.html |title=Supercoppa, il Milan fa il bis in Europa |newspaper=la Repubblica |language=Italian |accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> although the Rossoneri lost to Juventus on penalties in the [[2003 Supercoppa Italiana]] following a 1\u20131 draw after extra time; during the match, Pirlo scored on a penalty in extra time, and once again in the shoot-out.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.corrieredellosport.it/624/2011/08/03-186967/2003,+Milan+ko%3A+alla+Juve+va+la+Supercoppa+italiana |title=2003, Milan ko: alla Juve va la Supercoppa italiana |newspaper=Corriere dello Sport |language=Italian |date=3 August 2003 |accessdate=4 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727033455/http://www.corrieredellosport.it/624/2011/08/03-186967/2003,+Milan+ko%3A+alla+Juve+va+la+Supercoppa+italiana |archivedate=27 July 2014}}</ref> Milan would also miss out on the [[2003 Intercontinental Cup]], losing out on penalties once again, to [[Boca Juniors]], following a 1\u20131 draw after extra-time; on this occasion, Pirlo missed his penalty in the shoot-out, after previously setting up Milan's opening goal of the match.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablest/toyota03.html |title=Intercontinental Club Cup 2003 |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.corrieredellosport.it/624/2011/12/14-210128/2003,+Il+Milan+ko+ai+rigori+addio+Coppa+Intercontinentale |title=2003, Il Milan ko ai rigori addio Coppa Intercontinentale |newspaper=Corriere dello Sport |language=Italian |date=14 December 2003 |accessdate=4 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727025343/http://www.corrieredellosport.it/624/2011/12/14-210128/2003,+Il+Milan+ko+ai+rigori+addio+Coppa+Intercontinentale |archivedate=27 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.repubblica.it/2003/l/sezioni/sport/calcio/bocafesta/bocafesta/bocafesta.html |title=Milan, troppi errori dal dischetto l'Intercontinentale al Boca |newspaper=la Repubblica |language=Italian |accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> Pirlo would celebrate winning his first Serie A title with Milan during the [[2003\u201304 Serie A|2003\u201304 season]] however,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gazzetta.it/primi_piani/calcio/2004/pp_1.0.356922368.shtml |title=Kak\u00e0 e Shevchenko d'applausi |newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref> following up the scudetto with the [[2004 Supercoppa Italiana]] over [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.corriere.it/Primo_Piano/Sport/2004/08_Agosto/21/supercoppa.shtml |title=Il Milan stravince la Supercoppa italiana |newspaper=Corriere della Sera |language=Italian |date=21 August 2001 |accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2004\u20132006: Struggles====\nMilan finished as runners up in Serie A to Juventus in the [[2004\u201305 Serie A|2004\u201305 season]]. In the [[2004\u201305 UEFA Champions League]], Pirlo finished as one of the second highest assist providers with four assists,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2004/statistics/round=1968/players/type=assists/index.html |title=UEFA Champions League 2004/05 Statistics: Assists |publisher=UEFA |accessdate=19 June 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001203811/http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season%3D2004/statistics/round%3D1968/players/type%3Dassists/index.html |archivedate=1 October 2015}}</ref> as he helped Milan to reach the final.<ref>{{cite web |title=Uefa Champions League 2004\u201305 Statistics |url=http://soccer-europe.com/Archives/UCL/UCL0405/Performers.html |accessdate=22 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101226142104/http://www.soccer-europe.com/Archives/UCL/UCL0405/Performers.html |archivedate=26 December 2010}}</ref> In the [[2005 UEFA Champions League Final]] against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], on 25 May, Pirlo assisted [[Paolo Maldini]]'s opening goal, after 50 seconds, from a free kick, and combined with Kak\u00e1 before the Brazilian unleashed [[Hern\u00e1n Crespo]] with a long pass for Milan's third goal before halftime. In the second half, however, Liverpool made a three-goal comeback, sending the match into extra time. After a 3\u20133 deadlock, the match went to penalties, and Milan were defeated by the English team in the shoot-out. Despite Pirlo's performance throughout the competition and in the final, one of the most forgettable incidents of the season was probably his penalty miss during the shoot-out in the final, as his spot kick was saved by [[Jerzy Dudek]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://it.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2004/overview/index.html |title=2004/05: Il Liverpool beffa il Milan |publisher=UEFA |language=Italian |accessdate=4 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206183420/http://it.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season%3D2004/overview/index.html |archivedate=6 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/history/season=2004/round=1972/match=1086988/index.html |title=Liverpool triumph in Turkey |publisher=UEFA |date=25 May 2005 |accessdate=28 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101231013311/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/history/season%3D2004/round%3D1972/match%3D1086988/index.html |archivedate=31 December 2010}}</ref> Pirlo would later state in his autobiography that the 2005 UEFA Champions League Final defeat on penalties was the worst moment of his career, and that he had considered retiring prematurely following the match:<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/15-04-2014/pirlo-passato-all-inter-hodgson-mi-chiamava-pirla-volevo-smettere-la-delusione-istanbul-col-milan-80455322681.shtml |title=Pirlo e il passato: \"All\u2019Inter Hodgson mi chiamava Pirla. Volevo smettere dopo Istanbul\" |newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |date=15 April 2014 |accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|I thought about quitting because, after Istanbul, nothing made sense any more. The 2005 Champions League final simply suffocated me... We\u2019d invented a new disease with multiple symptoms: \"Istanbul syndrome\". I no longer felt like a player, and that was devastating enough. But even worse, I no longer felt like a man.|Pirlo, in his autobiography ''I Think Therefore I Play'', on Milan's defeat to Liverpool in the 2005 UEFA Champions League Final, in Istanbul.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2604647/ANDREA-PIRLO-EXCLUSIVE-I-quit-losing-Liverpool-Champions-League-final.html |title=ANDREA PIRLO EXCLUSIVE: |newspaper=Daily Mail |accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref>}}\n\nThe following season, Milan once again finished in second place behind Juventus in [[2005\u201306 Serie A|Serie A]] (before their 30-point deduction due to their involvement in the [[2006 Italian football scandal|2006 Calciopoli]] scandal), also reaching the semi-finals of the [[2005\u201306 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]], only to be defeated by eventual champions, [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://it.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2005/clubs/club=50058/matches/index.html |title=2005\u201306 UEFA Champions League |publisher=UEFA |language=Italian |accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref> and the quarter-finals of the [[2005\u201306 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]]. In 2006, Pirlo placed 9th in the [[2006 Ballon d'Or|Ballon d'Or]], which was won by his Italy teammate [[Fabio Cannavaro]],<ref name=\"2006 Ballon d'Or\">{{cite news |url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Primo_Piano/2006/11_Novembre/17/cannavaro.shtml |title=Cannavaro mister Pallone d'Oro |newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |date=11 November 2006 |accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> and was elected to the 2006 [[FIFPro]] World XI.<ref name=\"FIFPro World XI 2006\"/>\n\n====2006\u20132009: Another UEFA Champions League title====\n{{quote|Andrea has demonstrated all his great talent and worth. When we played together, everything started with him. He always had the great gift of being able to visualise and anticipate plays before everyone else. His vision, what he can do with the ball, and what he's able to create, make him a true superstar. Andrea has something which you don't see very often.|[[Roberto Baggio]] on Pirlo in 2007.<ref name=\"tuttomercatoweb.com\"/>}}\n\n[[File:Andrea Pirlo 2008.jpg|thumb|right|Pirlo playing for Milan in 2008.]]\n\nPirlo led Milan in minutes played for the [[2006\u201307 A.C. Milan season|2006\u201307 season]] with 2,782 across 52 appearances, as he went on to win his second [[2006\u201307 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League title]] with Milan, also helping his team to a fourth-place finish in [[2006\u201307 Serie A|Serie A]], and another [[2006\u201307 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]] semi-final. In the second leg of the UEFA Champions League semi-final against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], Pirlo set up Seedorf's goal, as Milan progressed on to the final.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.repubblica.it/2007/05/sezioni/sport/calcio/champions_league/milan-manchester/milan-manchester/milan-manchester.html |title=Un Milan stellare batte il Manchester I rossoneri volano in finale |newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> In the [[2007 UEFA Champions League Final]] in Athens, Pirlo assisted [[Filippo Inzaghi|Inzaghi's]] first goal from a free kick,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.milannews.it/altre-notizie/inzaghi-su-pirlo-indimenticabile-il-suo-assist-involontario-ad-atene-59501 |title=Inzaghi su Pirlo: \"Indimenticabile il suo assist involontario ad Atene\" |publisher=Milan News |language=Italian |accessdate=3 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204081704/http://www.milannews.it/altre-notizie/inzaghi-su-pirlo-indimenticabile-il-suo-assist-involontario-ad-atene-59501 |archivedate=4 February 2015}}</ref> helping Milan to defeat Liverpool 2\u20131, avenging their 2005 final defeat in Istanbul.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://it.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2006/clubs/club=50058/matches/index.html |title=2006\u201307 UEFA Champions League: AC Milan |publisher=UEFA |language=Italian |accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.repubblica.it/2007/05/sezioni/sport/calcio/champions_league/milan-vittoria/milan-vittoria/milan-vittoria.html |title=Champions, il Milan sul tetto dell'Europa Inzaghi cancella l'incubo di Istanbul |newspaper=la Repubblica |language=Italian |accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref> During the [[2007\u201308 Serie A|2007\u201308 season]], Pirlo won his second [[2007 UEFA Super Cup|UEFA Super Cup]] with Milan, assisting Milan's second goal in the final,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefasupercup/history/season=2007/ |title=2007: Milan overcome sombre Sevilla |publisher=UEFA |accessdate=7 July 2015}}</ref> and winning the ''Man of the Match'' award;<ref name=\"UEFA Super Cup Match Press Kit\">{{cite web |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/printoutfiles/competitions/supercup/2009/e/e_2001219_pk.pdf |title=2009 UEFA Super Cup Match Press Kit |publisher=UEFA |date=28 August 2009 |accessdate=4 December 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303232520/http://en.archive.uefa.com/printoutfiles/competitions/supercup/2009/e/e_2001219_pk.pdf |archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref> he also contributed to the club's first ever [[FIFA Club World Cup]] title in [[2007 FIFA Club World Cup|2007]], once again setting-up Milan's second goal in the [[2007 FIFA Club World Cup Final|final]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/jul/07/andrea-pirlo-mls-hipster-footballer |title=A brief guide to \u2026 Andrea Pirlo, the ultimate hipster footballer |newspaper=The Guardian |author1=Scott Murray |date=7 July 2015 |accessdate=7 July 2015}}</ref> In October 2007, he was nominated for the [[2007 Ballon d'Or]], the [[2007 FIFA World Player of the Year|2007]] [[FIFA World Player of the Year]], and the 2007 [[International Federation of Football History & Statistics]] (IFFHS) [[IFFHS World's Best Playmaker|World's Best Playmaker]] Awards, but they were all won by Milan teammate Kak\u00e1, as Pirlo placed 5th in the Ballon d'or, 7th in the FIFA World Player of the Year, and 2nd in the World's Best Playmaker Awards.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/fifa-awards.html#player10 |title=World Player of the Year |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |accessdate=4 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112042845/http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/fifa-awards.html |archivedate=12 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"2007 Ballon d'Or\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/europa-poy07.html |title=European Footballer of the Year (\"Ballon d'Or\") 2007 |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iffhs.de/former-results/ |title=THE WORLD'S BEST PLAYMAKER |publisher=International Federation of Football History & Statistics |accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> Despite a strong start, Milan suffered a dip in form during the second half of the season, finishing the league in fifth place, failing to qualify for the [[2008\u201309 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]];<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/chelsea/5421290/Chelsea-manager-Carlo-Ancelotti-Profile.html |title=Chelsea manager Carlo Ancelotti: Profile |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |author1=Mark Ogden |date=1 June 2009 |accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref> Milan also suffered eliminations in the round of 16 of the [[2007\u201308 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]]<ref name=\"AC Milan\">{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/teamsandplayers/teams/club=50058/profile/index.html |title=AC Milan |publisher=UEFA |accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref> and the [[2007\u201308 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]] that season.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.repubblica.it/2007/08/sezioni/sport/calcio/coppa-italia/ottavi-italia/ottavi-italia.html |title=Coppa Italia, il Catania elimina il Milan Totti 200 volte in gol e la Roma va |newspaper=la Repubblica |language=Italian |date=16 January 2008 |accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref> The following season, Milan managed a second-place finish in [[2008\u201309 Serie A|Serie A]], alongside Juventus, and behind local rivals Inter,<ref name=\"Ancelotti lascia\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/SoleOnLine4/Sport/2009/05/calcio-mercato-kaka-nedved.shtml?uuid=f37f8706-4def-11de-af13-8b0b0be69add |title=Ancelotti lascia, Leonardo nuovo tecnico del Milan |publisher=Il Sole 24 Ore |language=Italian |date=31 May 2009 |accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref> whilst they were eliminated in the round of 32 of the [[2008\u201309 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]],<ref name=\"AC Milan\"/> and the round of 16 of the [[2008\u201309 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Primo_Piano/2008/12/03/mil-laz.shtml |title=La Lazio caccia fuori il Milan |newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |author1=Riccardo Pratesi |date=3 December 2008 |accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2009\u20132011: A second ''Scudetto'' and farewell====\n[[File:Pirlo free kick vs Real Madrid.jpg|upright=1.5|thumb|left|250px|Pirlo (left), with [[A.C. Milan|Milan]], preparing to take a free kick against [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] in the [[2010\u201311 UEFA Champions League]].]]\n\nAfter Kak\u00e1 and Ancelotti left Milan in the summer of 2009,<ref name=\"Ancelotti lascia\"/> [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] tested Milan's resolve by bidding $12&nbsp;million and [[Claudio Pizarro]] for Pirlo. The club rejected the offer and Pirlo was said to be contemplating a transfer request.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/jun/10/andrea-pirlo-kaka-maicon-ibrahimovic-pato-milan |title=Unsettled Andrea Pirlo admits Milan squad have 'taken Kaka's exit badly' |newspaper=The Guardian |date=10 June 2009 |accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref> On 5 August, club owner [[Silvio Berlusconi]] decided not to sell Pirlo, who said he was overjoyed and wanted to end his career at Milan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/10/italy/2009/08/05/1423746/milan-star-pirlo-pleased-chelsea-transfer-saga-is-over |title=Milan Star Pirlo Pleased Chelsea Transfer Saga Is Over |website=Goal.com |date=5 August 2009 |accessdate=15 May 2012}}</ref> On 21 October 2009, Pirlo scored a notable 30-metre goal in Milan's 3\u20132 win over [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] in the [[2009\u201310 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]]; Milan were eventually eliminated in the round of 16.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/oct/21/champions-league-clockwatch-live |title=Champions League: Real Madrid v Milan \u2013 as it happened |newspaper=The Guardian |author=Paolo Bandini |date=21 October 2009 |accessdate=28 June 2012 |location=London}}</ref> Milan finished the season with a 3rd place in [[2009\u201310 Serie A|Serie A]], and a quarter-final finish in the [[2009\u201310 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]] under new manager [[Leonardo Ara\u00fajo|Leonardo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/SPORT/football/05/14/football.leonardo.milan.sacking/ |title=Leonardo and AC Milan part company |publisher=CNN |date=14 May 2010 |accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe following season saw Milan dominate the league. Milan played host to [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]] on 25 September 2010, with Pirlo providing a lifted ball over the top of the defence to set striker [[Zlatan Ibrahimovi\u0107]] free to score the solitary goal of the game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=304842&cc=5901 |title=Report: AC Milan v Genoa \u2013 Italian Serie A |website=ESPN Soccernet |date=25 September 2010 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> On 2 October, Pirlo scored a 40-yard goal against Parma to give Milan their first away win of the [[2010\u201311 A.C. Milan season|2010\u201311 season]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/match/48700/parma-vs-milan/report |title=Parma 0\u20131 AC Milan: Superb Andrea Pirlo strike sends Massimiliano Allegri's men top of Serie A |website=Goal.com |date=2 October 2010 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> On 14 May 2011, Pirlo appeared in his last match for Milan, coming on as a half-time substitute for Ambrosini as the club celebrated their [[2010\u201311 Serie A|Serie A title]] with a 4\u20131 victory over Cagliari.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=304918&cc=5901 |title=Report: AC Milan v Cagliari \u2013 Italian Serie A |website=ESPN Soccernet |date=14 May 2011 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> Four days later, Pirlo confirmed that he would be leaving Milan at the end of the 2010\u201311 season, after a mutual decision not to renew his contract.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11095_6939053,00.html |title=Pirlo leaving Milan |date=18 May 2011 |accessdate=18 May 2011 |publisher=Sky Sports}}</ref> In his last season in Milan, Pirlo appeared in the league just 17 times under manager [[Massimiliano Allegri]], notching just one goal and three assists, winning his second Serie A title with Milan that season, also reaching the round of 16 in the [[2010\u201311 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]], and in the [[2010\u201311 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]] semi-final.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/player/_/id/11888/andrea-pirlo?cc=5901 |title=Andrea Pirlo |website=ESPN Soccernet |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn total with Milan, Pirlo made 401 appearances, scoring 41 goals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.acmilan.com/it/news/show/134072 |title=400 VOLTE ANDREA |publisher=A.C. Milan |language=Italian |accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref> With the club, he won two Serie A titles in 2004 and 2011, as well as two [[UEFA Champions League]] titles in 2003 and 2007, also reaching the final in 2005; he also won a [[Coppa Italia]] in 2003, a [[Supercoppa Italiana]] in 2004, and two [[UEFA Super Cup]]s in 2003 and 2007, as well as playing a key role in Milan's first ever FIFA Club World Cup title in 2007. During this period, Milan also finished as runners up in Serie A in the 2004\u201305 and the 2005\u201306 seasons, as well as finishing second on penalties in the 2003 Supercoppa Italiana, and in the 2003 Intercontinental Cup.<ref name=\"A.C. Milan Hall of Fame: Andrea Pirlo\"/>\n\n===Juventus===\n{{quote| When Andrea told me that he was joining us, the first thing I thought was: \"God exists\". A player of his level and ability, not to mention that he was free, I think it was the signing of the century!|[[Gianluigi Buffon]] on Pirlo's transfer to [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/world-match-centre/nationalleagues/nationalleague=italy-serie-a-2000000026/news/newsid/150/940/7/index.html |title=Buffon: Pirlo was signing of the century |publisher=FIFA |accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref>}}\n\n====2011\u201312 season====\n\nFollowing Pirlo's departure from Milan in 2011, Juventus signed him on a free transfer on a contract until 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.juventus.com/wps/portal/en/news/24maggio2011_PIRLO_UFFICIALE/!ut/p/b1/tZHdToNAEIWfpS_AzO7iQi_Z1tJtATew_O0NoaIGKK0xjdI-vajxkjudSU4yyUm-czJgoCSccUYdl3AowJzq9_alvrTnU338ug2vKPeW8d4niCrboAyV9LXQGVEUcijFJObbhzPjIZSTwakoor8UxEOfBQJlut9sA-GQh4SChgLtKumur_LW3-IOxyDpx114aCR2mUpuRRalxyBq4kivw5H0SPQ6v-p7HHUnSXRRqsniVHirsb2T-S9wJnnM_gs415D8OXAHpj0M1sfjYKHFXMYpmz5JJ7VdDvkKou15eILBvPHn6Gdtb7H4BOHxF2g!/dl4/d5/L2dBISEvZ0FBIS9nQSEh/ |title=Andrea Pirlo signs for Juventus |date=24 May 2010 |accessdate=24 May 2011 |publisher=Juventus F.C. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020164935/http://www.juventus.com/wps/portal/en/news/24maggio2011_PIRLO_UFFICIALE/!ut/p/b1/tZHdToNAEIWfpS_AzO7iQi_Z1tJtATew_O0NoaIGKK0xjdI-vajxkjudSU4yyUm-czJgoCSccUYdl3AowJzq9_alvrTnU338ug2vKPeW8d4niCrboAyV9LXQGVEUcijFJObbhzPjIZSTwakoor8UxEOfBQJlut9sA-GQh4SChgLtKumur_LW3-IOxyDpx114aCR2mUpuRRalxyBq4kivw5H0SPQ6v-p7HHUnSXRRqsniVHirsb2T-S9wJnnM_gs415D8OXAHpj0M1sfjYKHFXMYpmz5JJ7VdDvkKou15eILBvPHn6Gdtb7H4BOHxF2g!/dl4/d5/L2dBISEvZ0FBIS9nQSEh/ |archivedate=20 October 2012}}</ref> His debut with Juventus was in a friendly match against [[Sporting CP]], which they lost 2\u20131. His first competitive match with Juventus was the [[2011\u201312 Serie A]] opening match against Parma at home, in which he tallied two assists, for [[Stephan Lichtsteiner]] and [[Claudio Marchisio]] \u2013 the latter of which was the first ever goal in the Juventus Stadium\u00a0\u2013, and completed 110 passes in a 4\u20131 victory.<ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo still as good as ever\">{{cite web |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2012/05/03/pirlo |title=Andrea Pirlo still as good as ever |website=Sports Illustrated |author=Adam Digby |accessdate=10 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tribalfootball.com/articles/pirlo-outstanding-juventus-debut-parma-victory-1875951 |title=Pirlo outstanding on Juventus debut in Parma victory &#124; Serie A News |publisher=tribalfootball.com |accessdate=28 June 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=ita/news/newsid=1675081.html |title=Juventus pick off Parma, Palermo stun Inter |publisher=UEFA.com |date=11 September 2011 |accessdate=22 August 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/juventus-vs-parma/247621 |title=Juventus 4\u20131 Parma |publisher=Sky Sports |date=11 September 2011 |accessdate=22 August 2019 }}</ref> [[Antonio Conte]] played him alongside younger midfielders Marchisio and new signing [[Arturo Vidal]] in a three-man midfield, which allowed Pirlo to function creatively as a deep-lying playmaker, while Marchisio and Vidal supported him defensively.<ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo still as good as ever\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thehardtackle.com/2012/juventus-corner-marchisio-vidal-pirlo-remains-serie-as-best-midfield/ |title=Juventus\u2019 Corner: Why Marchisio, Vidal And Pirlo Form Serie A's Best Midfield |publisher=The Hard Tackle |author1=Chelston D'souza |date=4 April 2012 |accessdate=15 December 2015}}</ref> Pirlo's first goal for Juventus was a free kick against [[Calcio Catania|Catania]] on 18 February 2012 securing a 3\u20131 victory for Juventus and put the club back at the top of the Serie A table, above his former club Milan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=326969&cc=5901 |title=Report: Juventus v Catania \u2013 Italian Serie A |website=ESPN Soccernet |date=18 February 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> On 18 March, Pirlo scored in a 5\u20130 demolition of [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] and after the game dedicated the win to [[Fabrice Muamba]], who suffered a cardiac arrest playing for [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] during a match against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] the same day.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en-india/news/139/italy/2012/03/18/2974277/juventus-pirlo-dedicates-5-0-victory-against-fiorentina-to |title=Juventus' Pirlo dedicates 5\u20130 victory against Fiorentina to Muamba |website=Goal.com |date=18 March 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2116891/Fabrice-Muamba--Real-Madrid-offer-tributes.html |title=Fabrice Muamba \u2013 Real Madrid offer tributes |newspaper=Daily Mail |date=18 March 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nPirlo finished the season by winning the 2011\u201312 Serie A title, after helping Juventus to secure a 2\u20130 victory over [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en-ie/news/3923/italy/2012/05/06/3085620/juventus-are-back-says-bonucci-after-clinching-serie-a-title |title=Juventus are back, says Bonucci after clinching Serie A title |website=Goal.com |date=6 May 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> He provided the most assists in the Serie A that season, with 13,<ref name=\"Serie A, giocatori, Assist\">{{cite news |url=http://www.corrieredellosport.it/live/SerieA/statistiche/giocatori/assist.shtml |title=Serie A, giocatori, Assist |newspaper=Corriere dello Sport |accessdate=28 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120707234754/http://www.corrieredellosport.it/live/SerieA/statistiche/giocatori/assist.shtml |archivedate=7 July 2012}}</ref> and he also found the back of the net three times in the league.<ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo still as good as ever\"/> Pirlo created over 100 chances and completed 2643 passes that season, with an 87% pass completion rate, completing 500 more passes than any other player in Serie A; the only player in the world to have completed more passes than him that season was [[Xavi]].<ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo still as good as ever\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tuttojuve.com/primo-piano/elogio-di-pirlo-su-sports-illustrated-tutto-merito-di-baggio-93031 |title=Elogio di Pirlo su Sports Illustrated: tutto merito di... Baggio|trans-title=Praise from Pirlo in Sports Illustrated: all of this was thanks to... Baggio |website=TUTTOJUVE.com |language=Italian |author1=Sandro Scarpa |date=4 May 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2015}}</ref> Due to his performances throughout the season, and his key role in leading Juventus to their first Serie A title in nine years, he was named to the [[Serie A Team of the Year]], along with his Juventus midfielder partner Vidal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en-ie/news/3920/features/2012/05/14/3101479/serie-a-team-of-the-season-pirlo-ibrahimovic-di-natale-star |title=Serie A Team of the Season: Pirlo, Ibrahimovic & Di Natale star in the 2011\u201312 campaign |website=Goal.com |date=14 May 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> Pirlo and Juventus also finished runners up to [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]] in the [[2012 Coppa Italia Final|Coppa Italia]] final that season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/match/78417/juventus-vs-napoli/report |title=Juventus 0\u20132 Napoli: Cavani and Hamsik clinch Coppa Italia and dash double dreams of Turin giants |website=Goal.com |date=20 May 2012}}</ref> Pirlo's fine form in the 2011\u201312 season, in which he led Juventus to the league title, the [[2012 Supercoppa Italiana|Supercoppa Italiana]] and Coppa Italia Final, as well as leading [[Italy national football team|Italy]] to the final of [[Euro 2012]], saw him nominated for the 2012 [[UEFA Best Player in Europe Award]], in which he finished 4th.<ref name=\"uefa.com\"/> He was also elected to be part of the [[European Sports Media#2011\u201312|2012 ESM Team of the Year]] and the [[UEFA Team of the Year|2012 UEFA Team of the Year]].<ref name=el/><ref name=\"UEFA: Andrea Pirlo\"/>\n\n====2012\u201313 season====\nPirlo played in the 2012 Supercoppa Italiana in Beijing on 11 August 2012 against Napoli, helping Juventus to a 4\u20132 win in extra time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/juventus-4-2-napoli-aet-143500093--sow.html |title=Juventus 4\u20132 Napoli (aet): Bianconeri sees off nine-man Partenopei in extra time |publisher=Yahoo Sports |date=11 August 2012}}</ref> He curled in a free kick to seal a 2\u20130 defeat of Parma on the opening day of the new Serie A season. The goal caused much controversy, as the Parma players protested that it had not gone over the line, and replays proved inconclusive.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en/match/88041/juventus-vs-parma/report |title=Juventus 2\u20130 Parma: Pirlo free-kick seals opening-day win for champions |website=Goal.com |date=25 August 2012}}</ref> In the following league match against [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]] on 2 September, Pirlo helped to win a penalty and assisted [[Sebastian Giovinco]]'s second goal of the match, as Juventus went on to defeat the home team 4\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/udinese-1-4-juventus-giovinco-175100940--sow.html |title=Udinese 1\u20134 Juventus: Giovinco double helps sink 10-man hosts |publisher=Yahoo! |accessdate=2 September 2012}}</ref> On 29 September, Pirlo opened the scoring when he dispatched a trade mark free kick to send Juventus on their way to a 4\u20131 defeat of Roma.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espnfc.com/us/en/report/352035/report.html?soccernet=true&cc=5901 |title=Juventus 4\u20131 Roma |website=ESPN FC |date=29 September 2012}}</ref> Pirlo was nominated for the [[2012 FIFA Ballon d'Or]], along with Juventus and Italy teammate [[Gianluigi Buffon]], following their performances throughout the calendar year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.juventus.com/juve/en/news/29oct2012_buffonpirlo |title=Ballon d'Or 2013: Nominees List |publisher=Juventus F.C. |date=29 October 2012 |accessdate=6 December 2012}}</ref> Pirlo provided three assists for Juventus during the group stage, helping them to top their [[2012\u201313 UEFA Champions League group stage|group]] undefeated and advance to the knockout stages for first time since the 2008\u201309 tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/football/champions-league/2012-2013/shakhtar-donetsk-juventus-519060.html |title=Shaktar Donetsk vs Juventus: 0\u20131 |publisher=Eurosport |accessdate=6 December 2012}}</ref> Pirlo was also elected the 2012 [[Serie A Footballer of the Year]], as well as the best midfielder of the season, also winning the 2012 [[Guerin d'Oro]]. He was named as part of the 2012 Serie A team of the Year for his performances.<ref name=\"Serie A Team of the Year\"/> Pirlo also won the Pallone Azzurro, given to the best player of the year in the Italian National Team,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vivoazzurro.it/it/news/pirlo-%C3%A8-il-pallone-azzurro-2012 |title=Pirlo \u2013 Pallone Azzurro |publisher=Italian Football Federation |language=Italian |accessdate=30 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213153015/http://vivoazzurro.it/it/news/pirlo-%C3%A8-il-pallone-azzurro-2012 |archivedate=13 December 2013}}</ref> as well as placing fourth in the IFFHS World's Best Playmaker of the Year Award,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iffhs.de/?a433ccd423dce837ccaca7dca84505fdcdc3bfcdc0aec70aeedb8a3915 |title=IFFHS World's Best Playmaker 2012 |publisher=International Federation of Football History & Statistics |accessdate=30 January 2013}}</ref> and seventh in the FIFA Ballon d'Or.<ref name=\"voting results\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/ballond'or/general/01/98/08/52/fboawards-byrank.pdf |title=FIFA Ballon d'Or 2012 \u2013 voting results |publisher=FIFA |format=PDF |date=7 January 2013 |accessdate=7 January 2013}}</ref> Pirlo and Juventus retained their Serie A title that season. Juventus were, however, eliminated by [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] in the quarter finals of the [[2012\u201313 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]], and in the semi-finals of the [[2012\u201313 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]] by Lazio; both of these teams were the winners of these respective competitions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2013/clubs/club=50037/matches/index.html |title=FC Bayern M\u00fcnchen \u2013 UEFA Champions League 2012/13 |publisher=UEFA |accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tuttosport.com/news/calcio/coppa-italia/2015/05/20-975225/coppa_italia_juve-lazio_live_sfida_tevez-felipe_anderson/ |title=Coppa Italia, Juve-Lazio LIVE Pogba e Llorente dal 1' |newspaper=Tuttosport |language=Italian |date=20 May 2015 |accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2013\u201314 season====\n\nPirlo featured in Juventus's 4\u20130 win against Lazio in the [[2013 Supercoppa Italiana]], on 18 August 2013, at the [[Stadio Olimpico]], in Rome. Pirlo helped to create [[Paul Pogba]]'s opening goal in the twenty-third minute of play.<ref>{{cite web |title=Juventus vs. Lazio: 4\u20130 |url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/match/111121/juventus-vs-lazio/play-by-play |website=Goal.com |accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> Pirlo was the only Italian player to be nominated for the [[2013 FIFA Ballon d'Or]], and was also nominated for the 2013 FIFPro World XI.<ref>{{cite web |title=Juventus delighted for Conte, Pirlo over Ballon d'Or nominations |url=http://www.tribalfootball.com/articles/juventus-delighted-conte-pirlo-over-ballon-dor-nominations-3988172 |accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref> On 1 December, Pirlo sustained a knee-ligament injury which would keep him off the field for over a month.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espnfc.com/news/story/_/id/1636237/juventus-andrea-pirlo-month-knee-ligament-injury?cc=5901 |title=Andrea Pirlo out for over a month |website=ESPN FC |accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref> On 12 January 2014, Pirlo signed a new contract with Juventus, which will keep him at the club until 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calciomercato/11-01-2014/juve-pirlo-matrimonio-continua-andrea-dice-ancora-si-fino-2016-202041023581.shtml |title=Juve-Pirlo, il matrimonio continua, Andrea dice ancora s\u00ec fino al 2016 |newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |date=12 January 2014 |accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> On 27 January, Pirlo was named Serie A Footballer of the Year for a second consecutive time, and was once again included in the Serie A Team of the Year.<ref name=\"Vidal e Pirlo sono il top\">{{cite news |url=http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/serie_a/2014/01/27-283890/Oscar+del+calcio%3A+Vidal+e+Pirlo+sono+il+top.+La+Juve+%C3%A8+la+pi%C3%B9+forte+d%27Italia?print |title=Oscar del calcio: Vidal e Pirlo sono il top. La Juve \u00e8 la pi\u00f9 forte d'Italia |newspaper=Tuttosport |language=Italian |date=27 January 2014 |accessdate=19 June 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620001027/http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/serie_a/2014/01/27-283890/Oscar+del+calcio%3A+Vidal+e+Pirlo+sono+il+top.+La+Juve+%C3%A8+la+pi%C3%B9+forte+d%27Italia?print |archivedate=20 June 2015}}</ref> Juventus won their [[2013\u201314 Serie A|30th league title that season]] with a record 102 points and 33 victories; this was also their third consecutive title since Pirlo's arrival. Juventus also reached the quarter-finals of the [[2013\u201314 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]], losing out to Roma. The Turin club suffered a group stage elimination in the [[2013\u201314 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]], but managed a semi-final finish in the [[2013\u201314 UEFA Europa League|UEFA Europa League]], losing out to [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]], with Pirlo scoring a match winning goal from a free kick in the round of 16 against Fiorentina.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soccer-blogger.com/2014/03/21/fiorentina-vs-juventus-2014-europa-league-second-leg-0-1-highlights-pirlo-free-kick-goal-video/ |title=Fiorentina vs Juventus 2014 Europa League Second Leg 0\u20131 Highlights Pirlo Free kick Goal Video |website=soccer-blogger.com |date=21 March 2013 |accessdate=19 May 2014}}</ref> Pirlo was chosen to be part of the 2013\u201314 Europa League Team of the Season, for his performances in the competition.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=2112220.html#uefa+europa+league+squad+season |title=UEFA Europa League squad of the season |publisher=UEFA |accessdate=3 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:1 andrea pirlo 2014.jpg|thumb|upright|Pirlo playing for Juventus in 2014.]]\n\n====2014\u201315 season====\nOn 11 June 2014, Pirlo signed a new contract keeping him at Juventus until 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=Andrea Pirlo signs new two-year deal at Juventus ahed 35 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27794605 |accessdate=11 June 2014 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=11 June 2014}}</ref> Pirlo made his 100th league appearance for Juventus in a 3\u20132 home win over Roma on 5 October 2014.<ref>{{cite news |title=Leonardo Bonucci's spectacular late volley gave Juventus victory in a fiery encounter with title rivals Roma. |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/29476538 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=9 October 2014}}</ref> On 1 November, Pirlo scored Juventus's opening goal from a free kick in a 2\u20130 win over [[Empoli F.C.|Empoli]], on their 117th anniversary; this was his 26th goal from a free kick in Serie A, putting him two goals behind the all-time record holder, [[Sini\u0161a Mihajlovi\u0107]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Serie A: Juventus beat Empoli 2\u20130 to move three points clear |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/serie-a-juventus-beat-empoli-20-to-move-three-points-clear/510041-5-21.html |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> On 4 November, Pirlo scored once again from a trademark, curling direct free kick in a 3\u20132 home win over [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]] in a group-stage [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]] fixture.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2015/matches/round=2000548/match=2014364/postmatch/report/index.html#pogba+caps+juve+recovery |title=Pogba caps Juventus recovery against Olympiacos |publisher=UEFA |date=4 November 2014 |accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref> This was Pirlo's 100th appearance in the UEFA Champions League, marking the occasion with his first UEFA Champions League goal with Juventus.<ref>{{cite news |title=Juventus 3\u20132 Olympiacos: Paul Pogba scores winner after Andrea Pirlo celebrates 100th Champions League appearance with trademark free-kick |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2821028/Juventus-3-2-Olympiacos-Paul-Pogba-scores-winner-Andrea-Pirlo-free-kick.html |newspaper=Daily Mail |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> On 15 December 2014, Pirlo was named the Serie A Footballer of the Year for the third time in his career, and for the third consecutive year since his arrival at Juventus; he was also named part of the 2014 Serie A Team of the Year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/15-12-2014/gran-gala-calcio-buffon-miglior-portiere-prima-uscita-la-d-amico-100237777068.shtml |title=Buffon miglior portiere. Prima uscita con la D'Amico |newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |date=15 December 2014 |accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> In Juventus's 2\u20131 home victory over [[Borussia Dortmund]] in the round of 16 of the UEFA Champions League, on 24 February 2015, Pirlo left the pitch during the first half of the match, after injuring his right calf, ruling him out for three weeks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.us/juventus/story/2318171/juventus-andrea-pirlo-out-three-weeks-with-ankle-injury |title=Juventus' Andrea Pirlo out three weeks with ankle injury |website=ESPN FC |date=26 February 2015 |accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref> Pirlo was called up on 11 April 2015 against Parma following his injury.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.us/juventus/story/2384098/claudio-marchisio-and-andrea-pirlo-returns-delight-juventus-coach-massimiliano-allegri |title=Claudio Marchisio and Andrea Pirlo returns delight Juve coach Allegri |website=ESPN FC |author=Ben Gladwell |date=7 April 2015 |accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref> He returned to the starting line-up on 14 April 2015, helping [[\u00c1lvaro Morata]] to win a penalty which was later converted by Vidal in a 1\u20130 victory over [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]] at the [[Juventus Stadium]], in the first leg of the UEFA Champions League quarter-finals; he was replaced by [[Andrea Barzagli]] during the second half.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Champions-League/Juventus/14-04-2015/champions-juventus-monaco-1-0-vidal-rigore-fa-godere-allegri-stadium-110454988856.shtml |title=Juventus-Monaco 1\u20130: Vidal su rigore fa godere Allegri e lo Stadium |newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |author1=Jacopo Gerna |date=14 April 2015 |accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref> On 26 April, Pirlo scored from a free kick in a 2\u20131 away defeat to local rivals [[Torino F.C.|Torino]] in the \"[[Turin Derby|Derby di Torino]]\"; this was his 28th goal in Serie A from a free kick, which put him level with Mihajlovi\u0107 as the player with the most goals from free kicks in [[Football records in Italy#Most goals from a free kick|Serie A history]].<ref name=\"Pirlo raggiunge Mihajlovic a quota 28\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tuttojuve.com/altre-notizie/pirlo-raggiunge-mihajlovic-a-quota-28-233088 |title=Pirlo raggiunge Mihajlovic a quota 28 |website=TUTTOJUVE.com |language=Italian |date=26 April 2015 |accessdate=27 April 2015}}</ref> On 20 May, Pirlo played a part in both of Juventus's goals as the Turin club defeated Lazio 2\u20131 at the Stadio Olimpico in the [[2015 Coppa Italia Final]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Juventus/20-05-2015/juve-infinita-vince-10-coppa-italia-matri-piega-lazio-supplementari-110907305821.shtml |title=Juve infinita, vince la 10\u00aa Coppa Italia: Matri piega la Lazio ai supplementari |trans-title=An infinite Juve wins the 10th Coppa Italia: Matri sinks Lazio in extra-time |newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=it |author1=Jacopo Gerna |date=20 May 2015 |accessdate=21 May 2015}}</ref> On 6 June 2015, Pirlo played the entirety of the [[2015 UEFA Champions League Final]] as Juventus were defeated 3\u20131 by Barcelona at Berlin's [[Olympiastadion Berlin|Olympiastadion]];<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2015/matches/round=2000552/match=2015227/postmatch/report/index.html |title=Barcelona see off Juventus to claim fifth title |publisher=UEFA |date=6 June 2015 |accessdate=6 June 2015}}</ref> this was the final game of his Juventus career. Pirlo was named to the [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League#Squad of the season|2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League Squad of the season]] for his performances.<ref name=\"UEFA Champions League squad of the season\">{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2255077.html#uefa+champions+league+squad+season |title=UEFA Champions League squad of the season |publisher=UEFA |date=9 June 2015 |accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn total, he made 164 appearances for Juventus in all competitions, scoring 19 goals (15 of which were scored from free kicks), also providing 39 assists; 31 of his goals came in Serie A, from 119 appearances. During his four seasons in [[Turin]], he won four Serie A titles, a Coppa Italia, and two Supercoppe Italiane, also reaching the fourth UEFA Champions League final of his career during his final season with the club. Over 20 seasons in Italy, he made 493 appearances in [[Football records in Italy#Appearances|Serie A]].<ref name=\"Thanks for everything, Maestro\">{{cite web |url=http://www.juventus.com/en/news/news/2015/thanks-for-everything-maestro.php |title=Thanks for everything, Maestro |publisher=Juventus F.C. |date=6 July 2015 |accessdate=6 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===New York City===\n[[File:Andrea Pirlo 2017.jpg|thumb|Pirlo with New York City in 2017.]]\n\n====2015 season====\nOn 6 July 2015, it was announced that Pirlo had completed a move to [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS) expansion franchise [[New York City FC|New York City]] as their third [[Designated Player Rule|Designated Player]].<ref name=\"Thanks for everything, Maestro\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/33415616 |title=Andrea Pirlo: New York City sign Juventus midfielder |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 July 2015 |accessdate=6 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nycfc.com/post/2015/07/06/andrea-pirlo-join-new-york-city-fc-third-designated-player |title=Andrea Pirlo to Join New York City FC as Third Designated Player |publisher=New York City FC |date=6 July 2015 |accessdate=7 July 2015}}</ref> In doing so, he became the highest paid Italian player in all leagues with an $8&nbsp;million salary,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3151975/Frank-Lampard-enjoys-spot-SoulCycle-edges-closer-New-York-City-debut.html|title=Andrea Pirlo becomes the highest paid MLS player with an $8m salary... more than Frank Lampard, Steven Gerrard and David Villa|author1=Daniel Prescott|date=7 July 2015|accessdate=31 December 2015|newspaper=Daily Mail}}</ref> until [[Graziano Pell\u00e8]] overtook him after moving to Chinese club [[Shandong Luneng Taishan F.C.|Shandong Luneng]] the following year.<ref name=\"Pell\u00e8 completes move to Shandong Luneng\">{{cite web |url=http://www.saintsfc.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/20160711-graziano-pelle-announcement-southampton-shandong-luneng-3178958.aspx |title=Pell\u00e8 completes move to Shandong Luneng |publisher=Southampton F.C. |date=11 July 2016 |accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3686338/Graziano-Pelle-moves-fifth-highest-paid-player-world-crazy-Chinese-spending-stop.html |title=Graziano Pelle moves to become the fifth highest-paid player in the world... so, where will the crazy Chinese spending stop? |newspaper=Daily Mail |date=12 July 2016 |accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref> Pirlo made his debut with the club on 26 July 2015 at [[Yankee Stadium]] in New York against [[Orlando City SC|Orlando City]], coming on as a substitute in the 56th minute; he was involved in his team's third and fourth goals and was booked in the 88th minute as New York won the match 5\u20133.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2015/jul/26/new-york-city-fc-v-orlando-city-sc-live |title=New York City FC v Orlando City SC |newspaper=The Guardian |author1=Bryan Graham |date=26 July 2015 |accessdate=26 July 2015}}</ref> He made his first start for New York on 1 August, in a 2\u20133 home defeat to the [[Montreal Impact]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2015/aug/01/new-york-city-fc-montreal-impact-live |title=New York City FC 2\u20133 Montreal Impact \u2013 as it happened |newspaper=The Guardian |author1=Tim Hill |date=1 August 2015 |accessdate=4 August 2015}}</ref> On 12 August, it was announced that Pirlo had placed seventh in the [[UEFA Best Player in Europe Award#2014.E2.80.9315|2015 UEFA Best Player in Europe]].<ref name=\"Best Player in Europe\"/> On 13 August he set up a goal for [[David Villa]] in a 3\u20131 home win over [[D.C. United]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/major-league-soccer/match/412278/new-york-city-fc-dc-united/report |title=David Villa nets winner as NYCFC snap skid, surge past DC United |website=ESPN FC |date=13 August 2013 |accessdate=14 August 2015}}</ref> In October 2015, Pirlo was named to the 59-player shortlist for the [[2015 FIFA Ballon d'Or]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/oct/02/ballon-dor-long-list-2015-lionel-messi-david-ospina |title=2015 Ballon d'Or longlist: Lionel Messi named alongside David Ospina \u2013 report |newspaper=The Guardian |author1=Michael Butler |date=2 October 2015 |accessdate=26 October 2015}}</ref> He finished the [[2015 MLS season]] with 5 assists in 13 appearances, and ended up third in the MLS in minutes per pass, although he failed to score a goal.<ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo - MLS\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/players/andrea-pirlo |title=Andrea Pirlo |publisher=Major League Soccer |accessdate=26 October 2015}}</ref> Despite the presence of Pirlo and two other UEFA Champions League winners, David Villa and [[Frank Lampard]], New York City failed to qualify for the [[2015 MLS Cup Playoffs]] at the conclusion of their debut season, which drew criticism from the press;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3289247/New-York-City-1-3-New-England-Frank-Lampard-David-Villa-Andrea-Pirlo-spark-hope-future-despite-play-failure.html |title=New York City 1\u20133 New England: Frank Lampard, David Villa and Andrea Pirlo spark hope for the future despite play-off failure |newspaper=Daily Mail |author1=Steve Brenner |date=25 October 2015 |accessdate=26 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.the42.ie/new-york-city-fc-2395050-Oct2015/ |title=The MLS dream-team with Lampard, Pirlo & Villa is nothing short of a New York nightmare now |publisher=The 42 |author1=Eoin O'Callaghan |date=17 October 2015 |accessdate=26 October 2015}}</ref> Pirlo in particular drew criticism from the media for his low defensive work-rate.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/mar/07/patrick-vieira-is-the-new-nyc-fc-coach-but-andrea-pirlo-still-has-problems |title=Patrick Vieira is the new NYC FC coach but Andrea Pirlo still has problems |newspaper=The Guardian |author1=Graham Ruthven |author2=Graham Parker |date=7 March 2016 |accessdate=1 June 2016}}</ref> In November, Pirlo became the first MLS player in history to be nominated for the FIFPro World XI.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/11/27/new-york-city-fc-midfielder-andrea-pirlo-becomes-first-mls-player-named-fifa-fifpro |title=New York City FC midfielder Andrea Pirlo becomes first MLS player named to FIFA FIFPro World XI shortlist |publisher=Major League Soccer |date=27 November 2015 |accessdate=1 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2016 season====\nPirlo made his first assist of the [[2016 MLS season]] on 30 April, as he set up a goal for David Villa from a corner in a 3\u20132 home win over the [[Vancouver Whitecaps FC|Vancouver Whitecaps]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/villa-strikes-twice-as-nycfc-downs-caps-1.481460 |title=Villa strikes twice as NYCFC downs 'Caps |publisher=TSN |date=30 April 2016 |accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref> On 18 June, he scored his first MLS goal from a free kick in the 50th minute of a 3\u20132 home victory over [[Philadelphia Union|Philadelphia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/major-league-soccer/story/2897222/mls-frank-lampard-david-villa-andrea-pirlo-all-score-in-nycfcs-win-over-union |title=Frank Lampard, David Villa and Andrea Pirlo score in NYCFC's win over Union |website=ESPN FC |date=18 June 2016 |accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref> In July 2016, Pirlo was included in the roster for the [[2016 MLS All-Star Game]].<ref name=\"2016All-star\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/news/villa-pirlo-and-kaka-headline-mls-all-star-squad-face-arsenal |title=Villa, Pirlo and Kaka headline MLS All-Star squad to face Arsenal |website=FourFourTwo |date=17 July 2016 |accessdate=18 July 2016}}</ref> Pirlo finished his second MLS season with the club with one goal and a team seasonal best of eleven assists in 32 appearances,<ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo - MLS\"/> as New York City finished in second place in the Eastern Conference, and qualified for the [[2016 MLS Cup Playoffs|MLS Cup Playoffs]] for the first time ever, clinching a spot in the Eastern Conference semi-final.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nycfc.com/post/2016/10/24/playoffs-all-you-need-know |title=Playoffs: All You Need to Know |publisher=New York City FC |author1=Mark Booth |date=24 October 2016 |accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref> He was ruled out of the first leg, however, after sustaining a last-minute calf injury, and New York lost the match 2\u20130 away to [[Toronto FC]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/soccer/toronto-fc-tops-new-york-city-fc-2-0-after-first-leg-of-semi-final/article32588493/ |title=Toronto FC tops New York City FC 2\u20130 after first leg of semi-final |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |author1=David Shoalts |date=30 October 2016 |accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref> He appeared in the second leg on 6 November, as New York were eliminated from the Playoffs 7\u20130 on aggregate, following a 5\u20130 home defeat to Toronto.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.us/blog/the-match/60/post/2989137/toronto-exploits-new-york-city-fc-tactics-in-5-0-rout-at-yankee-stadium |title=Toronto exploits New York City FC's tactics in 5\u20130 rout at Yankee Stadium |website=ESPN FC |author1=Graham Parker |date=6 November 2016 |accessdate=7 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== 2017 season and retirement ====\nAfter struggling with persisting physical problems for most of the [[2017 MLS season]], on 8 October 2017, Pirlo announced that he would retire from professional football at the end of the season;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espnfc.com/new-york-city-fc/story/3223773/new-york-citys-andrea-pirlo-to-retire-at-end-of-mls-season |title=New York City's Andrea Pirlo to retire at end of MLS season |website=ESPN FC |date=8 October 2017 |accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref> in total, he was limited to only 15 appearances and two assists during the 2017 MLS regular season.<ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo - MLS\"/> He made his final professional appearance on 5 November, coming on as a 90th-minute substitute in a 2\u20130 home win over [[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]], in the second leg of the [[2017 MLS Cup Playoffs#Conference Semifinals|2017 MLS Cup Eastern Conference Semi-finals]]; New York were eliminated from the Playoffs following a 4\u20133 aggregate loss.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.beinsports.com/au/mls/news/timbers-fall-as-toronto-columbus-edge-through/701286 |title=Timbers fall as Toronto, Columbus edge through |publisher=beIN Sports |date=5 November 2017 |accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football-italia.net/112430/pirlo-hang-his-boots |title=Pirlo to hang up his boots |website=Football Italia |publisher=Tiro Media |date=6 November 2017}}</ref> In total, Pirlo made 62 appearances for New York \u2013 60 of which came in the MLS regular season, with the other two coming in the MLS Cup Playoffs \u2013 over the course of his three seasons with the club, scoring one goal and providing 18 assists, all of which came during the MLS regular season.<ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo - MLS\"/> Pirlo officially communicated his retirement from professional football the following day, on Twitter.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football-italia.net/112435/official-pirlo-confirms-retirement |title=Official: Pirlo confirms retirement |website=Football Italia |publisher=Tiro Media |date=6 November 2017}}</ref> A testimonial match \u2013 ''La Notte del Maestro'' \u2013 was played at the San Siro Stadium in Milan on 21 May 2018, in honour of Pirlo's retirement from professional football.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football-italia.net/121712/inzaghi-hat-trick-pirlo-testimonial |title=Inzaghi hat-trick in Pirlo testimonial |website=Football Italia |publisher=Tiro Media |date=21 May 2018 |accessdate=22 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n{{quote| Pirlo is a silent leader. He speaks with his feet.|[[Marcello Lippi]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sports.ndtv.com/football/news/225305-fifa-world-cup-gianluigi-buffon-andrea-pirlo-still-hungry-for-italian-job |archive-url=https://archive.today/20140609195710/http://sports.ndtv.com/football/news/225305-fifa-world-cup-gianluigi-buffon-andrea-pirlo-still-hungry-for-italian-job |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 June 2014 |title=FIFA World Cup: Gianluigi Buffon, Andrea Pirlo Still Hungry for Italian Job |date=8 June 2014 |accessdate=9 June 2014 |publisher=NDTV Sports }}</ref>}}\n{{quote| To pass the ball to Andrea Pirlo is like to hide it in a safe.|[[Zbigniew Boniek]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.postmatch.org/145/the-pirlo-dilemma/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130630211934/http://www.postmatch.org/145/the-pirlo-dilemma/ |url-status=dead |archivedate=30 June 2013 |title=The Pirlo Dilemma |website=Postmatch |date=27 June 2013 |accessdate=9 June 2014}}</ref>}}\n{{quote| Is he the best player of his generation? Not quite, but he is the most important.|Michael Cox<ref>''[http://espn.go.com/sports/soccer/news/_/id/7145038/why-andrea-pirlo-most-important-player-generation-michael-cox-soccer Andrea Pirlo a giant of his generation]'', ESPN, 25 October 2011.</ref>}}\n\n===Under-21 and Olympic Career, senior team debut, and Euro 2004===\nPirlo [[Captain (association football)|captained]] [[Italy national under-21 football team|Italy]] to an [[UEFA European Under-21 Championship|Under-21 European Championship]] in [[2000 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2000]], wearing the [[Squad number (association football)|number 10 jersey]], and winning the awards for best player and top scorer of the tournament with three goals; he scored both goals \u2013 one from a penalty and the other from a free kick \u2013 in Italy's 2\u20131 victory over [[Czech Republic national under-21 football team|Czech Republic]] in the final. He also led the Italy under-21 team to a semi-final finish in the [[2002 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2002 edition of the tournament]]. Pirlo played for Italy at the [[Football at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2000 Summer Olympics]] in Sydney, scoring a goal in Italy's 1\u20130 opening win over hosts [[Australia national under-23 soccer team|Australia]] on 13 September;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/mensolympic/sydney2000/matches/round=3946/match=20438/index.html |title=Olympic Football Tournaments, Sydney 2000 \u2013 Men: Australia \u2013 Italy (0\u20131) |publisher=FIFA |date=13 September 2000 |accessdate=27 May 2015}}</ref> he also helped Italy win the [[bronze medal]] at the [[Football at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2004 Summer Olympics]] in Athens. With 46 matches and 16 goals, Pirlo is the record appearance holder for the Italian under-21 team, and the second highest goal-scorer after [[Alberto Gilardino]].<ref name=\"FIFA Confederations Cup Brazil 2013 Player Profile: Andrea Pirlo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/players/player=177876/profile.html |title=FIFA Confederations Cup Brazil 2013 Player Profile: Andrea Pirlo |publisher=FIFA |accessdate=8 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712003723/http://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/players/player%3D177876/profile.html |archivedate=12 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"UEFA: Andrea Pirlo\">{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/teamsandplayers/players/player=26917/profile/index.html |title=Andrea Pirlo |publisher=UEFA |accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nPirlo made his Italy senior debut on 7 September 2002 under [[Giovanni Trapattoni]], at the age of 23 in a 2\u20130 away win over [[Azerbaijan national football team|Azerbaijan]] in a [[UEFA Euro 2004 qualifying|Euro 2004 qualifying match]];<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio2002_serie_a/italia/italia/italia.html?ref=search |title=Italia, Del Piero e pochi lampi ma comincia con una vittoria |newspaper=la Repubblica |language=Italian |accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gazzetta.it/premium/plus/Nazionale/10-09-2012/miti-braccetto-pirlo-come-piero-91-volte-l-italia-912563869708.shtml |title=Pirlo come Del Piero 91 volte con l'Italia |newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |author1=Mirko Graziano |date=10 September 2012 |accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref> he also appeared in a friendly match in Pescara against [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]] on 20 November, later that year, which ended in a 1\u20131 draw.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio2002_serie_a/itaturchia/itaturchia/itaturchia.html |title=La nuova Italia bella a met\u00e0 Vieri evita la sconfitta |newspaper=la Repubblica |language=Italian |date=20 November 2002 |accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref> Pirlo scored his first goal for Italy from a free kick in a 4\u20130 away win in a friendly match against [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.repubblica.it/2004/e/sezioni/sport/calcio/nazionale/tunita/tunita/tunita.html |title=I debuttanti del gol fanno bella l'Italia |newspaper=la Repubblica |language=Italian |accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref> His first major tournament with the Italian senior team was [[UEFA Euro 2004]] under Trapattoni, where he made two appearances in Italy's last two group matches: the first in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]], and the second in a 2\u20131 win over [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]]. The Italian team was eliminated in the first round, on direct encounters, following a three-way five-point tie with Sweden and [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]].<ref name=\"UEFA: Andrea Pirlo\"/>\n\n===2006 World Cup===\nUnder Trapattoni's replacement, [[Marcello Lippi]], Pirlo became a key member of Italy's starting line-up during their [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification|2006 World Cup Qualifying campaign]], and he was eventually called up as a starting member of the Italian squad for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/teams/team=43954.html |title=2006 FIFA World Cup Germany\u2122 |publisher=FIFA |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> On 26 March 2005, he assured Italy's participation in the tournament after scoring from two free kicks in a 2\u20130 win against [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] in a World Cup Qualifier.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2012/0623/1224318511490.html |title=Silent but deadly: Italian midfield maestro's skills do talking for him |newspaper=The Irish Times |accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/4351211.stm |title=Italy 2\u20140 Scotland |publisher=BBC Sport |date=26 March 2005 |accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nPirlo was named to Italy's 23-man squad for the 2006 World Cup,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.repubblica.it/2006/05/sezioni/sport/calcio/nazionale/conferenza-stampa-lippi/conferenza-stampa-lippi/conferenza-stampa-lippi.html |title=Lippi ha fiducia, nonostante tutto Convocato Buffon: \"E' sereno\" |newspaper=la Repubblica |language=Italian |date=15 May 2006 |accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref> and appeared in all of Italy's matches at the tournament, playing 668 minutes in total.<ref name=simpatia>{{cite web |url=http://www.blitzquotidiano.it/sport/italia-2006-campioni-del-mondo-grosso-jolly-cannavaro-buffon-voto-simpatia-75-1883864/ |title=Home Sport Italia 2006: campioni del mondo. Grosso jolly, Cannavaro e Buffon muro: voto simpatia 7,5 |website=Blitz Quotidiano |language=Italian |author1=Antonio Sansonetti |date=6 June 2014 |accessdate=3 July 2016}}</ref> In Italy's first match of the tournament on 12 June, Pirlo scored the opening goal against [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]], and subsequently helped set up a goal for [[Vincenzo Iaquinta]] to seal a 2\u20130 victory, as the midfielder was named ''Man of the Match''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4852746.stm |title=Italy 2\u20130 Ghana |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 June 2006 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> In the second match on 17 June, he set up a diving header for Gilardino from a set piece which proved to be vital in the 1\u20131 draw against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4853182.stm |title=Italy 1\u20131 USA |publisher=BBC Sport |date=17 June 2006 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the semi-final against [[Germany national football team|Germany]] on 4 July, he assisted [[Fabio Grosso]]'s opening goal in the dying minutes of extra-time, and was again named ''Man of the Match'', as Italy triumphed 2\u20130 over the hosts.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4991640.stm |title=Last-gasp Italy knock Germany out |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 July 2006 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> In the [[2006 FIFA World Cup Final|final]] against [[France national football team|France]] on 9 July, his corner kick produced [[Marco Materazzi]]'s equalising header ten minutes after France had opened the scoring with a [[Zinedine Zidane]] penalty. Following a 1\u20131 deadlock after extra-time, the match went to a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]], in which he scored the first spot kick, helping Italy to win the title.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stevenson |first=Jonathan |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4991652.stm |title=Zidane off as Italy win World Cup |publisher=BBC Sport |date=9 July 2006 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/results/matches/match=97410064/report.html |title=2006 FIFA World Cup Germany |publisher=FIFA |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> Pirlo formed a formidable midfield partnership with Milan teammate Gattuso, and he completed 475 passes out of 580 attempted throughout the tournament, while also winning 18 challenges.<ref name=simpatia/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mondiali2006.tiscali.it/squadre/t119.html |title=Speciale Mondiali 2006: Italia (Gruppo E) |publisher=Tiscali |language=Italian |accessdate=13 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080626192738/http://mondiali2006.tiscali.it/squadre/t119.html |archivedate=26 June 2008}}</ref> After the final, he was named ''Man of the Match'' for a third time, winning more ''Man of the Match'' Awards than any other player in the tournament.<ref name=\"FIFA Confederations Cup Brazil 2013 Player Profile: Andrea Pirlo\"/> Pirlo was voted the third-best player of the tournament, winning the [[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Ball|Bronze Ball]],<ref name=\"FIFA Confederations Cup Brazil 2013 Player Profile: Andrea Pirlo\"/> and he finished the victorious World Cup campaign as the top assist provider along with teammate [[Francesco Totti]], as well as [[Juan Rom\u00e1n Riquelme]], [[Bastian Schweinsteiger]], and [[Lu\u00eds Figo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thebiglead.com/index.php/2012/02/25/ac-milan-meets-juventus-in-potential-scudetto-decider/ |title=AC Milan Meets Juventus in Potential Scudetto Decider |website=The Big Lead |publisher=Gannett |author=Ty Duffy |date=25 February 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> He was named as part of the 2006 FIFPro XI and as part of the [[2006 FIFA World Cup#All-star team|2006 World Cup Team of the Tournament]] for his performances, placing ninth in both the 2006 Ballon d'Or and the [[2006 FIFA World Player of the Year]] Awards.<ref name=\"FIFPro World XI 2006\"/>\n\n{{quote|\"I don't feel pressure ... I don't give a toss about it. I spent the afternoon of Sunday, 9 July 2006 in Berlin sleeping and playing the [[PlayStation]]. In the evening, I went out and won the World Cup.\"|Pirlo, on his mental state in Italy's World Cup victory over [[France national football team|France]] in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]], in Berlin.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/1717/editorial/2015/07/06/13038762/i-dont-feel-pressure-i-dont-give-a-toss-about-it-the-best-quotes- |title='I don't feel pressure \u2013 I don't give a toss about it' \u2013 The best quotes by and about Andrea Pirlo |website=Goal.com |date=6 July 2015 |accessdate=4 August 2016}}</ref>}}\n\n===Post World Cup===\nPirlo appeared in all three of Italy's group matches at [[UEFA Euro 2008]]. He was named ''Man of the Match'' in Italy's second group match, a 1\u20131 draw against [[Romania national football team|Romania]], on 13 June.<ref name=\"ita-rou report\">{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/newsfiles/euro/2008/Logo_MD07_300695_ITA_ROU_FullReport.pdf |title=Full-time report Italy-Romania |publisher=UEFA |format=PDF |date=13 June 2008 |accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref> On 17 June 2008, Pirlo netted a penalty as Italy defeated France 2\u20130 in the final group match, to send their rivals and World Cup runners-up crashing out of the European Championships in the first round.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2008/7363384.stm |title=France 0\u20132 Italy |publisher=BBC Sport |last=McNulty |first=Phil |date=17 June 2008 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> Italy lost on penalty kicks to eventual winners [[Spain national football team|Spain]] in the quarterfinals,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=232283&cc=5739&league=UEFA.EURO |title=Spain 0\u20130 Italy |date=22 June 2008 |website=ESPN Soccernet |accessdate=15 June 2010}}</ref> as Pirlo and Milan teammate Gattuso were suspended for the match.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/euro2012/history/season=2008/round=15094/match=301702/report=rp.html |title=Casillas' saves put Spain in semis |publisher=UEFA |date=22 June 2008 |accessdate=28 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100525234143/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/euro2012/history/season%3D2008/round%3D15094/match%3D301702/report%3Drp.html |archivedate=25 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=722549.html |title=Can Azzurri cope without suspended duo? |publisher=UEFA |author1=Richard Aikman |date=19 June 2008 |accessdate=19 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 June 2009, Pirlo assisted [[Giuseppe Rossi]]'s second goal in a 3\u20131 win in Italy's opening match of the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup|Confederations Cup]] against the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Mens-National-Team/2009/06/U-S-MNT-Fall-To-Italy-3-1-In-Opening-Match-Of-2009-Confederations-Cup.aspx?print=true |title=2009 FIFA Confederations Cup: Italy vs. USA: 3\u20131 |publisher=United States Soccer Federation |accessdate=18 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512012739/http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Mens-National-Team/2009/06/U-S-MNT-Fall-To-Italy-3-1-In-Opening-Match-Of-2009-Confederations-Cup.aspx?print=true |archivedate=12 May 2013}}</ref> Italy subsequently lost the following two group matches against [[Egypt national football team|Egypt]] and [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], and were eliminated from the competition in the first round.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/confederationscup/southafrica2009/results/match=66205/summary.html |title=Irresistible Brazil eliminate Italy |publisher=FIFA |date=21 June 2009 |accessdate=4 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nPirlo was not able to play the first two games in the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup]] for Italy due to recent injuries. He came off the bench for Italy late in the match on 24 June against [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]]. Even with his help in orchestrating a renewed Italian offence, Pirlo could not prevent Italy from being knocked out of the first round.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/jun/24/italy-slovakia-world-cup-match-report |title=Slovakia 3\u20132 Italy |newspaper=The Guardian |author=Paul Wilson at Soccer City |date=24 June 2010 |accessdate=28 June 2012 |location=London}}</ref>\n\n===Euro 2012===\nCoach Prandelli named Pirlo Vice-Captain of the Italian squad, behind captain, Gianluigi Buffon. Pirlo appeared in nine matches as Italy [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying|qualified]] undefeated for the [[UEFA Euro 2012|European Championships]] in Poland and Ukraine,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2012/teams/team=66/index.html |title=UEFA EURO \u2013 Italy \u2013 |publisher=UEFA |date=20 June 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> providing several assists, and netting one goal in Italy's 5\u20130 victory over the [[Faroe Islands national football team|Faroe Islands]] on 7 September 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/italy/7988190/Italy-5-Faroe-Islands-0-match-report.html |title=Italy 5 Faroe Islands 0: match report |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |author=Italy |date=7 September 2010 |accessdate=28 June 2012 |location=London}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Andrea Pirlo Euro 2012 vs England 01.jpg|thumb|upright|Andrea Pirlo playing for Italy against [[England national football team|England]] in quarter final of [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]]]]\n\nBecause of his excellent performances in leading Juventus to win the Serie A title, Italy coach [[Cesare Prandelli]] included the playmaker in his 32-man provisional squad for Euro 2012, and subsequently in Italy's final 23-man squad for the tournament.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/15846874 |title=Euro 2012: Italy team profile |publisher=BBC Sport |date=9 May 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=1796540.html |title=Di Natale recalled for provisional Italy squad \u2013 |publisher=UEFA |date=13 May 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> Pirlo provided the cutting ball from which [[Antonio Di Natale]] scored the opening goal of Italy's 1\u20131 draw with World and European champions Spain in the opening round of group play on 10 June 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18180099 |title=Euro 2012: Spain 1\u20131 Italy |publisher=BBC Sport |last=Smith |first=Ben |date=10 June 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> Pirlo then opened the scoring himself from a direct free kick in Italy's second group match against [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] on 14 June, which also ended in a 1\u20131 draw; Pirlo was named ''Man of the Match''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17875354 |title=Euro 2012: Day seven as it happened |publisher=BBC Sport |date=14 June 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120617003352/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17875354 |archive-date=17 June 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/newsfiles/euro/2012/2003331_fr.pdf |title=Italy vs. Croatia (1\u20131) |publisher=UEFA |date=14 June 2012 |accessdate=27 May 2015}}</ref> In the final group match against [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]], Pirlo set up [[Antonio Cassano]]'s goal from a corner kick to help Italy take a 1\u20130 lead.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en-my/match/71179/italy-vs-ireland/report |title=Match Report: Italy 2\u20130 Republic of Ireland |website=Goal.com |date=19 June 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> Italy eventually won 2\u20130 and progressed to the knock-out stage of the tournament as runners-up in Group C.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/republic-of-ireland/9316755/Italy-2-Republic-of-Ireland-0-match-report.html |title=Italy 2 Republic of Ireland 0: match report |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |author=Republic of Ireland |date=18 June 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 June, Pirlo produced a ''Man of the Match'' performance in the quarter-finals against [[England national football team|England]], as Italy won 4\u20132 on penalties after the game had finished 0\u20130 in extra time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espnfc.com/us/en/news/1114999/carlisleitaly-deserved-winner-england.html |title=Euro 2012: Italy deserved winner over England |website=ESPN FC |date=24 June 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120628112020/http://espnfc.com/us/en/news/1114999/carlisleitaly-deserved-winner-england.html |archivedate=28 June 2012}}</ref> Pirlo scored in the shoot-out with an audacious [[Chip (association football)|chipped]] penalty down the centre of the goal, also known as a [[Panenka (penalty kick)|Panenka]].<ref name=\"Peerless Pirlo exposes England\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18574269 |title=Euro 2012 analysis: Peerless Pirlo exposes England |publisher=BBC Sport |date=24 June 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> Following the match Pirlo spoke of his eloquent penalty, stating, ''\"At the moment I saw the goalkeeper making strange movements, so I waited for him to move and hit it like that... It was easier for me to chip it at that stage. Maybe my effort put some pressure on England.\"''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.notevenanoriundo.com/2012/06/azzurri-eloquent-decisive-and.html |title=calcio without citizenship: Azzurri: Eloquent, Decisive, and Devastating |website=not even an oriundo |accessdate=28 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413140648/http://www.notevenanoriundo.com/2012/06/azzurri-eloquent-decisive-and.html |archivedate=13 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.football-italia.net/20359/pirlo-why-i-chipped-hart |title=Pirlo: 'Why I chipped Hart' |website=Football Italia |publisher=Tiro Media |date=24 June 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref> Pirlo completed more passes than the entire England midfield, as he managed 131 passes, the most of any player during the match, and the second most in a single match in the history of the European Championship, behind Xavi, with an 87% pass completion rate, as Italy finished the match with 63% ball possession.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/18355305 |title=England 0\u20130 Italy (2\u20134 on penalties) |publisher=BBC Sport |author1=Phil McNulty |date=24 June 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2015}}</ref> He also ran 11.58 kilometres throughout the match, covering more distance than any England player.<ref name=\"Peerless Pirlo exposes England\"/>\n\nIn the semi-final round, on 28 June, Pirlo once again put up a ''Man of the Match'' performance against Germany, starting the play which led to [[Mario Balotelli|Balotelli's]] first goal of the match, as Italy won 2\u20131 to advance to the [[UEFA Euro 2012 Final|final]] of the tournament.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/euro2012/article-2166162/Euro-2012-results-Germany-1-Italy-2-Mario-Balotelli-hits-Azzurri-set-Spain-final.html |location=London |newspaper=Daily Mail |first=Matt |last=Lawton |title=Germany 1 Italy 2: Magic Mario makes his mark as Azzurri extend tournament hoodoo |date=28 June 2012}}</ref> Following Italy's success in the semi-finals, Italy were defeated 4\u20130 against Spain in the final.<ref name=\"UEFA: Andrea Pirlo\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/euro_2012/italia/2012/07/01-197411/L%26apos%3BItalia+crolla+in+finale.+Spagna+campione+d%26apos%3BEuropa+ |title=L'Italia crolla in finale. Spagna campione d'Europa|trans-title=Italy collapses in the final. Spain champions of Europe |newspaper=Tuttosport |language=Italian |last1=Moretti |first1=Alvaro |date=1 July 2012 |accessdate=15 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150330094300/http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/euro_2012/italia/2012/07/01-197411/L%26apos%3BItalia+crolla+in+finale.+Spagna+campione+d%26apos%3BEuropa+ |archivedate=30 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nPirlo won three ''Man of the Match'' Awards at Euro 2012, the most awards won by a single player, along with [[Andr\u00e9s Iniesta]] of tournament champions Spain.<ref name=\"UEFA: Andrea Pirlo\"/> Pirlo was nominated for the [[UEFA Euro 2012#Awards|Player of the Tournament Award]], which ultimately went to Iniesta, and he was also elected to be part of the [[UEFA European Championship Teams of the Tournament#Poland and Ukraine 2012|Team of the Tournament]].<ref name=\"EURO 2012 Team of the Tournament\">{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefa/mediaservices/mediareleases/newsid=1838241.html |title=UEFA EURO 2012 Team of the Tournament |publisher=UEFA |date=2 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2013 Confederations Cup===\nPirlo was selected for Italy's squad to play in Brazil at the [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup|2013 Confederations Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://english.gazzetta.it/Football/03-06-2013/italy-name-confederations-cup-squad-ogbonna-and-ranocchia-miss-out-20504407317.shtml |title=Italy name Confederations Cup squad: Ogbonna and Ranocchia miss out |newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport |date=4 June 2013 |accessdate=8 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130611081918/http://english.gazzetta.it/Football/03-06-2013/italy-name-confederations-cup-squad-ogbonna-and-ranocchia-miss-out-20504407317.shtml |archivedate=11 June 2013}}</ref> He won his 100th cap on 16 June in Italy's opening game against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]], opening the scoring with a trademark free kick as Italy won 2\u20131, and Pirlo was voted ''Man of the Match''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2342737/Confederations-Cup-Italy-2-Mexico-1-match-report.html?ico=sport%5Eheadlines |title=Italy 2 Mexico 1: Pirlo lights up 100th cap with stunning free-kick as Balotelli strikes to grab win in Confederations Cup clash |newspaper=Daily Mail |date=16 June 2013 |accessdate=16 June 2013 |location=London}}</ref>\nHe was only the fifth Italian player to receive 100 caps after [[Dino Zoff]], [[Paolo Maldini]], [[Gianluigi Buffon]] and [[Fabio Cannavaro]].<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[World Soccer (magazine)|World Soccer]]|date=Summer 2013|page=9|title=Heroes & Villains}}</ref> In the second group stage match against [[Japan national football team|Japan]] on 19 June, Pirlo assisted [[Daniele De Rossi|De Rossi's]] goal against from a corner, as the match ended 4\u20133 to Italy.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://english.gazzetta.it/Football/20-06-2013/confederations-cup-italy-4-3-japan-giovinco-goals-takes-italy-through-20617634758.shtml |title=FIFA Confederations Cup 2013 \u2013 Italy vs Japan: 4\u20133 |newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport |date=20 June 2013 |accessdate=24 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624015459/http://english.gazzetta.it/Football/20-06-2013/confederations-cup-italy-4-3-japan-giovinco-goals-takes-italy-through-20617634758.shtml |archivedate=24 June 2013}}</ref> The win allowed Italy to progress to the semi-finals of the competition for the first time.\nPirlo did not play in the third group stage match against hosts Brazil, as he had come down with a minor injury at the end of the second match, although he would be available to play for the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/sport/football/injured-pirlo-not-to-play-against-brazil/article4837250.ece |title=Injured Pirlo Not to Play Against Brazil |location=Chennai, India |newspaper=The Hindu |date=21 June 2013 |accessdate=24 June 2013}}</ref> Italy were defeated 4\u20132 in the final group stage match on 22 June, which meant that they finished second in group A, and would be playing the winners of group B, tournament favourites Spain, in a rematch of the [[Euro 2012 final|European Championship Final of the previous year]]. Italy held Spain to 0\u20130 draw on 27 June, as the match eventually went to penalties. Pirlo netted his penalty, but Bonucci's miss allowed Spain to advance to the final, as Italy lost the shoot-out 7\u20136.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/matches/round=255207/match=300222468/summary.html |title=Spain edge dramatic shootout to reach Final |publisher=FIFA |date=27 June 2013 |accessdate=27 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418233757/http://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/matches/round%3D255207/match%3D300222468/summary.html |archivedate=18 April 2015}}</ref> Pirlo was injured for the third place final, although Italy managed to defeat [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] 3\u20132 on penalties on 30 June, after a 2\u20132 draw. Pirlo was named to the [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup#Awards|Team of the Tournament]],<ref name=\"2013 FIFA Confederations Cup Dream Team\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/dreamteam/ |title=2013 FIFA Confederations Cup Dream Team |publisher=FIFA |accessdate=27 May 2015}}</ref> and was nominated for the Golden Ball award, although he failed to place amongst the top three players of the tournament, as the awards went to [[Neymar]], Iniesta, and [[Paulinho (footballer, born July 1988)|Paulinho]], respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/news/newsid=2122604/?intcmp=fifacom_hp_module_latest_comments |title=Adidas Golden Ball Shortlist |publisher=FIFA |accessdate=1 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2014 World Cup===\nPirlo scored one goal during Italy's [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification|qualification campaign]] for the 2014 FIFA World Cup, which saw them top their group, undefeated.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2014/jun/25/zico-italy-andrea-pirlo-world-cup-2014 |title=Zico: Italy pay price for over-reliance on Andrea Pirlo and must rebuild |newspaper=The Guardian |date=25 June 2014 |accessdate=26 June 2014}}</ref> Pirlo converted a penalty as Italy dispatched [[Armenia national football team|Armenia]] by a score of 3\u20131 on 12 October 2012, and assisted several goals during the World Cup qualifying campaign.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/worldcup/season=2014/matches/round=2000294/match=2008547/postmatch/report/index.html |title=Resolute Italy head off Armenia challenge |publisher=UEFA |date=12 October 2012 |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref> On 5 June 2014, Pirlo was selected by Italy manager Prandelli as part of his 23-man squad for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]] in Brazil.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/jun/05/italy-squad-world-cup-2014 |title=Italy squad for 2014 World Cup: the 23 chosen by Cesare Prandelli |newspaper=The Guardian |date=5 June 2014 |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref> On 12 June, Pirlo announced that he would retire from international football following the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/italy/story/1875007/andrea-pirlo-to-retire-from-italy-after-world-cup |title=Pirlo to quit Italy after World Cup |website=ESPN FC |date=12 June 2014 |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2014 World Cup, Italy were placed in Group D, along with [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]], England and Uruguay, in what was called the \"Group of Death\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/englands-world-cup-rivals-italy-2899762 |title=England's World Cup rivals Italy livid they are in Group of Death that also includes Uruguay |newspaper=Daily Mirror |accessdate=26 June 2014}}</ref> On 14 June, in Italy's opening match against England, Pirlo wore the captain's armband due to Buffon's last minute injury. The match ended with a 2\u20131 win to Italy. Pirlo heavily contributed to Italy's win, controlling the flow of the game, and setting up several goalscoring chances, as Italy dominated possession. During the match, Pirlo made 108 passes in total, only misplacing five, with a pass completion rate of 95.4%, completing the most passes of any other player in the previous opening matches of the 2014 World Cup. With a 93.2 pass percentage, Italy also managed to record the highest pass accuracy percentage of any team in a World Cup match since Denmark in the 1966 World Cup, completing 561 of their 602 passes.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/worldcup2014/article-2658288/Italy-prove-pass-masters-Azzurri-rack-highest-accuracy-recorded-World-Cup-game-1966.html?ico=sport^headlines |title=Italy prove they are the pass masters as Azzurri rack up highest accuracy ever recorded in a World Cup game since 1966 |newspaper=Daily Mail |accessdate=16 June 2014}}</ref> Pirlo also contributed to Italy's first goal of the match: [[Antonio Candreva]]'s short corner was played to [[Marco Verratti]], who then passed the ball out wide towards Pirlo, who drew his marker with him. Pirlo let the ball pass in between his legs to Marchisio, leaving him with space to score with a low drive from outside the area. Pirlo also managed to hit the crossbar from a swerving free kick in injury time.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Mondiali/15-06-2014/inghilterra-italia-1-2-gol-marchisio-sturridge-balotelli-80930904968.shtml?rlabs=1&ak=2 |title=Inghilterra-Italia 1\u20132: gol di Marchisio, Sturridge e Balotelli |newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |date=15 June 2014 |accessdate=16 May 2014}}</ref> Italy suffered 1\u20130 defeats in both of their remaining matches against Costa Rica and Uruguay, however and were eliminated in the group stage for the second consecutive World Cup, finishing in a disappointing third place in their group, behind Costa Rica and Uruguay. Pirlo's appearance against Uruguay was his 112th cap for Italy, which allowed him to equal [[Dino Zoff]]'s number of appearances for the Italian national team, and made him the fourth most capped player for the Italian national team. The Italian squad and manager, Cesare Prandelli, were criticised for over-relying on Pirlo to create goalscoring chances. Although Pirlo was able to set up some goal scoring opportunities and did test the opposition goalkeepers with some dangerous free kicks in the final two group games, his performances were stifled by the defensive pressure of the opposition, and he was much less dominant than he had been in the opening match against England.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\"/> Although he had previously communicated his intention to retire after the World Cup, he stated, upon his return to Italy, that he would still be available to play for the national team.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lastampa.it/2014/06/26/multimedia/sport/speciali/mondiali-di-calcio-2014/pirlo-se-nuovo-ct-vuole-resto-in-azzurro-p4ngsgr3LEONR7gDzvmyyH/pagina.html |title=Pirlo: Se il nuovo ct vuole resto in azzurro |newspaper=La Stampa |language=Italian |date=26 June 2014 |accessdate=26 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140627045930/http://lastampa.it/2014/06/26/multimedia/sport/speciali/mondiali-di-calcio-2014/pirlo-se-nuovo-ct-vuole-resto-in-azzurro-p4ngsgr3LEONR7gDzvmyyH/pagina.html |archive-date=27 June 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Euro 2016===\n[[File:20150616 - Portugal - Italie - Gen\u00e8ve - Andra Pirlo.jpg|thumb|right|Pirlo playing for Italy in 2015]]\n\nDespite previously announcing his international retirement following the 2014 World Cup, Pirlo reversed his decision, and under new Italy manager, and Pirlo's former Juventus manager Conte, Pirlo returned to the Italian squad.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2222260-andrea-pirlo-returns-to-italy-squad-following-giacomo-bonaventuras-injury |title=Andrea Pirlo Returns to Italy Squad Following Giacomo Bonaventura's Injury |date=6 October 2014 |website=Bleacher Report |publisher=Turner |accessdate=30 November 2014}}</ref> On 10 October, Pirlo started in Italy's second [[UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying|Euro 2016 qualifying match]], which ended in a 2\u20131 home win over Azerbaijan, overtaking Zoff with his 113th appearance for Italy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://it.sports.yahoo.com/notizie/qualificazioni-euro-2016-pirlo-supera-zoff-113-presenze-192340449--sow.html |title=Qualificazioni Euro 2016 \u2013 Pirlo supera Zoff: 113 presenze in Nazionale |publisher=Eurosport |language=Italian |date=10 October 2014 |accessdate=1 June 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119234823/https://it.sports.yahoo.com/notizie/qualificazioni-euro-2016-pirlo-supera-zoff-113-presenze-192340449--sow.html |archivedate=19 November 2015}}</ref> Pirlo assisted [[Giorgio Chiellini|Chiellini's]] first goal of the match from a corner kick.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/1717/editorial/2014/10/10/5173062/pirlo-shows-he-is-too-good-to-retire-as-chiellini-rescues |title=Pirlo shows he is too good to retire as Chiellini rescues Italy |website=Goal.com |date=10 October 2014 |accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref> In August 2015, Pirlo was called for Italy's Euro 2016 qualifying matches against Malta and Bulgaria in September; he appeared in Italy's 1\u20130 home victory over [[Malta national football team|Malta]] on 3 September, becoming the first MLS player to represent Italy;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.football-italia.net/72474/verratti-and-pirlo-against-malta |title=Verratti and Pirlo against Malta? |website=Football Italia |publisher=Tiro Media |date=2 September 2015 |accessdate=3 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxsports.com/soccer/story/italy-keep-pace-euro-qualification-lackluster-win-malta-1-0-graziano-pelle-match-report-090315 |title=Italy keep pace in Euro Qualifying after lackluster win over Malta |publisher=Fox Sports |date=3 September 2015 |accessdate=3 September 2015}}</ref> this was his final international appearance.<ref name=\"Nazionale in Cifre - FIGC: Pirlo, Andrea\"/> In total, Pirlo made four appearances under Conte, as Italy qualified for [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]] on 10 October in a 3\u20131 win over Azerbaijan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/italy-beats-azerbaijan-to-qualify-for-euro-2016/ |title=Italy beats Azerbaijan to qualify for Euro 2016 |publisher=Sportsnet |date=10 October 2015 |accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref> On 23 May 2016, Pirlo, along with fellow MLS compatriot Giovinco, was left off of Conte's 30-player shortlist for Italy's Euro 2016 squad. Regarding their omission, Conte commented in a press conference: \"When you make a certain choice and go to play in certain leagues, you do so taking it into account that they could pay the consequences from a footballing viewpoint\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.us/italy/story/2879294/andrea-pirlo-and-sebastian-giovinco-omitted-from-italy-squad-due-to-mls-play-antonio-conte |title=MLS play cost Andrea Pirlo, Sebastian Giovinco their Italy chance \u2013 Conte |website=ESPN FC |author1=Ben Gladwell |date=24 May 2016 |accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref> In response to Conte's comments, Pirlo stated to ''[[Sky Sport (Italy)|Sky Italia]]'': \"I have spoken to Conte and there is no disappointment on my part, he knows what he has to do and what he should not do. We had discussions during the season and both parties made their own decisions. He is the coach and it's only right he makes his decisions and decides what is best for him. I hope Italy win although the favourites are other teams such as Germany, Spain and France.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/12022/10299645/andrea-pirlo-accepts-antonio-contes-italy-snub-for-euro-2016 |title=Andrea Pirlo accepts Antonio Conte's Italy snub for Euro 2016 |publisher=Sky Sports |author1=Allan Valente |date=30 May 2016 |accessdate=1 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn total, Pirlo made 116 appearances for Italy, scoring 13 goals, making him the fifth-most capped player in his nation's history.<ref name=\"Appearances for Italy\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/ital-recintlp.html#app |title=Appearances for Italy National Team |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |author1=Roberto Di Maggio |author2=Jos\u00e9 Luis Pierrend |date=14 September 2017 |accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\n{{quote| ''Pirlo is a genius. Together with Baggio, I think he's the greatest talent that Italian football has produced in the last 25 years''.|Gianluigi Buffon<ref name=\"Buffon reveals greatest Italians\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fantasista10.co.uk/buffon-reveals-greatest-italians/ |title=Buffon reveals \u2018greatest Italians\u2019 |website=fantasista10 |accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref>}}\n{{quote| ''Pirlo spots a pass in a split-second that lesser players could spend a whole lifetime waiting to see''.|[[Carlo Ancelotti]]<ref name=lifetime>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/06/04/carlo-ancelotti-exclusive-andrea-pirlo-spots-a-pass-in-a-split-s/ |title=Andrea Pirlo spots a pass in a split second that others wait a lifetime to see |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |author=Carlo Ancelotti |date=4 June 2016 |accessdate=6 June 2016}}</ref>}}\n{{quote| ''Pirlo can make his feet do whatever he wants. He's a genius''.|[[Johan Cruyff]]<ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo still as good as ever\"/>}}\n\n===Position===\nTactically, Pirlo was capable of playing in several midfield positions, but was usually deployed by his club and national teams as a [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]], in the role of a deep-lying playmaker, due to his vision and passing accuracy. A highly technical and creative player, Pirlo is regarded by players, managers, and pundits as one of the greatest ever players in his position;<ref name=\"Soccerlens.com\"/><ref name=\"A.C. Milan Hall of Fame: Andrea Pirlo\"/> throughout his career, he was considered as one of the greatest midfielders in the world and of his generation,<ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo Player Profile - ESPN FC\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxsports.com/soccer/story/andrea-pirlo-xavi-hernandez-make-their-claim-best-midfielder-in-modern-football-era-060215 |title=Pirlo, Xavi make their claim of being the best midfielder in the modern era |publisher=Fox Sports |author1=Kris Voakes |author2=Ben Hayward |date=2 June 2015 |accessdate=9 June 2016}}</ref> and as one of the greatest Italian players ever,<ref name=\"Buffon reveals greatest Italians\"/> and is regarded as one of the greatest midfielders of all time by several pundits, managers and players.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nycfc.com/post/2017/11/06/vieira-pirlo-changed-football-forever |title=Vieira: Pirlo Changed Football Forever |publisher=New York City FC |author1=Mark Booth |date=6 November 2017 |accessdate=22 May 2018}}</ref> Pirlo started his career in a more advanced role, as an attacking midfielder, and also played as a [[Forward (association football)#Second striker|supporting striker]] on occasion.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://ricerca.gelocal.it/iltirreno/archivio/iltirreno/2001/02/24/LS202.html |title=Mazzone manda in campo un Brescia spavaldo: due punte e Pirlo rifinitore E Baggio vuole farsi rimpiangere |newspaper=Il Tirreno |language=Italian |date=24 February 2001 |accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> Although he was considered a talented young prospect, even drawing comparisons with former Italian footballer [[Gianni Rivera]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tuttonazionali.com/nazionale-a/boninsegna-pirlo-a-il-nuovo-rivera-3728 |title=Boninsegna: \"Pirlo \u00e8 il nuovo Rivera\" |website=Tutto Nazionali |language=Italian |accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> Pirlo occasionally struggled in this role, due to his lack of pace, and competition from other talented and more dynamic players in his position.<ref name=\"A.C. Milan Hall of Fame: Andrea Pirlo\"/><ref name=\"making\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/inter/?action=read&idtmw=294247 |title=Adelio Moro: \"Pirlo, come lui solo Rivera. Mazzone lo ha plasmato...\" |website=TUTTOmercatoWEB.com |language=Italian |accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nBecause of this, he was later moved to a deep-lying playmaker role by his coaches Mazzone, Terim, and Ancelotti, where he was able to excel due to his unique capabilities.<ref name=\"A.C. Milan Hall of Fame: Andrea Pirlo\"/><ref name=\"making\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/rassegna-stampa/mazzone-il-ruolo-di-pirlo-una-mia-intuizione-339399 |title=Mazzone: \"Il ruolo di Pirlo? Una mia intuizione\" |website=TUTTOmercatoWEB.com |language=Italian |accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> This position best utilised Pirlo's attributes, and allowed him to operate creatively from a deeper position, in or even behind the main midfield line, in a seemingly [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfield]] role, where he was allowed more time on the ball to create scoring opportunities with his trademark long balls.<ref name=\"A.C. Milan Hall of Fame: Andrea Pirlo\"/><ref name=\"making\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefalse9.com/2012/01/resurgence-of-deep-lying-playmaker-part.html |title=The Resurgence of the Deep Lying Playmaker-Part 1 |website=The False 9 |accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Scholes, Xavi and Andrea Pirlo revive\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2012/mar/19/paul-scholes-xavi-andrea-pirlo-playmaker |title=Paul Scholes, Xavi and Andrea Pirlo revive the deep-lying playmaker |newspaper=The Guardian |author=Michael Cox |date=19 March 2012 |accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> During his final season with Milan, Pirlo was also used on the [[Midfielder#Winger|wing]] under Allegri,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.panorama.it/sport/calcio/allegri-pirlo-ruolo-rapporto-difficile-milan/ |title=Allegri e Pirlo, storia di un rapporto impossibile |website=Panorama |language=Italian |accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> due to his ability to provide accurate [[Cross (football)|crosses]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1234437-euro-2012-why-andrea-pirlo-is-the-most-valuable-player-of-the-tournament |title=Euro 2012: Why Andrea Pirlo Is the Most Valuable Player of the Tournament |website=Bleacher Report |publisher=Turner |accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thescore.com/news/799848 |title=VIDEO: Andrea Pirlo makes New York City FC debut against Orlando City |publisher=theScore Inc. |author1=Armen Bedakian |date=26 July 2015 |accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.juventus.com/en/news/news/2012/the-champions-andrea-pirlo.php |title=The Champions: Andrea Pirlo |publisher=Juventus F.C. |date=13 June 2013 |accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/sports/soccer/euro-2012-wrap-spain-comes-together-to-make-history |title=Euro 2012 wrap: Spain comes together to make history |newspaper=National Post |author1=Matthew Scianitti |date=1 July 2012 |accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Skills===\n[[File:Andrea Pirlo Juventus.jpg|thumb|right|Pirlo playing for [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] in 2012]]\n\nAlthough not gifted with pace, stamina, physicality or notable defensive skills, work-rate, or tackling abilities,{{#tag:ref|See<ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo Player Profile - ESPN FC\"/><ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo is old, slow, rarely sprints and is just not the player he was \u2013 because he is even better\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/italy/10676557/Italys-Andrea-Pirlo-is-old-slow-rarely-sprints-and-is-just-not-the-player-he-was-because-he-is-even-better.html |title=Italy's Andrea Pirlo is old, slow, rarely sprints and is just not the player he was \u2013 because he is even better |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |author1=Jim White |date=4 March 2014 |accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo-BBC\">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2004/italy/players_to_watch/3681379.stm |title=Andrea Pirlo |publisher=BBC Sport |date=25 May 2004 |accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"changing role of deep-lying midfielder\">{{cite web |url=http://m.espn.com/soccer/blogs/blogpost?id=2445308&blogname=espnfcunited&wjb= |title=Champions League semis showcase changing role of deep-lying midfielder |website=ESPN FC |author1=Michael Cox |date=12 May 2015 |accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo: The football genius\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41903596 |title=Andrea Pirlo: The football genius who defied the number crunchers |publisher=BBC Sport |author1=Mike Henson |date=7 November 2017 |accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref>|name=\"style1\"|group=\"nb\"}} Pirlo was known for his composure in possession, and drew praise for his touch, technique, balance, elegance, close control, and [[Dribbling#Association football|dribbling]] ability, as well as his flair and creativity in beating players with [[Dummy (football)|feints]] during one-on-one situations, in order to retain the ball and create space for himself to play and receive passes.{{#tag:ref|See<ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo Player Profile - ESPN FC\"/><ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo still as good as ever\"/><ref name=\"Allegri didn\u2019t want me\">{{cite web |url=http://www.football-italia.net/18683/pirlo-allegri-didn%E2%80%99t-want-me |title=Pirlo: Allegri didn't want me |website=Football Italia |publisher=Tiro Media |date=11 May 2012 |accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo\">{{cite news |url=http://temi.repubblica.it/gazzettadimantova-europei2008/2008/05/23/andrea-pirlo/ |title=Andrea Pirlo |newspaper=la Repubblica |language=Italian |date=23 May 2008 |accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=remembrance>{{cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2015/6/23/8829633/andrea-pirlo-new-york-city-fc-mls-leaving-juventus |title=In remembrance of the fully featured version of Andrea Pirlo |website=SB Nation |publisher=Vox Media |author1=Zito Madu |date=23 June 2015 |accessdate=13 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"L\u2019addio di Pirlo e Xavi\">{{cite news |url=http://www.corriere.it/sport/15_giugno_26/addio-contemporaneo-grande-calcio-pirlo-xavi-storia-calcio-49458b08-1bf9-11e5-a24d-298f280523ad.shtml |title=L'addio (contemporaneo) al grande calcio di Pirlo e Xavi. E il loro posto nella grande storia del calcio |newspaper=Corriere della Sera |language=Italian |author1=Mario Sconcerti |date=6 July 2015 |accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"magic in their boots\">{{cite web |url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/football/six-superstars-shaking-up-the-world-game-with-the-magic-in-their-boots/news-story/38c118673f74bf29e29e9cea58ba4973 |title=Six superstars shaking up the world game with the magic in their boots |publisher=Fox Sports |author1=Trevor Marshallsea |date=8 February 2016 |accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Happy retirement, Andrea Pirlo\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/men/thinking-man/happy-retirement-andrea-pirlo-12-times-midfield-philosopher/ |title=Happy retirement, Andrea Pirlo: 12 times the midfield philosopher proved himself to be a cut above |work=The Telegraph |last1=Morrissy-Swan |first1=Tom\u00e9 |date=7 November 2017 |accessdate=4 September 2019 }}</ref>|name=\"style2\"|group=\"nb\"}} His reactions and ability to anticipate plays also enabled him to cover ground in midfield and intercept passes despite his lack of pace, tackling ability, or stamina.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.repubblica.it/venerdi/articoli/2017/03/02/news/calcio_talent_scout_campionato_maradona_totti_pele_cassano-159600453/ |title=Se ti viene la pelle d'oca hai scovato un campione |newspaper=la Repubblica |language=Italian |author1=Angelo Carotenuto |date=2 March 2017 |accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref> As a [[playmaker]], he is highly regarded by pundits for his outstanding vision, awareness, and football intelligence, as well as his movement, positional sense, inventive play, anticipation, ability to read the game, and his wide range of distribution, which enabled him to play the ball first time and rarely relinquish possession, even when put under pressure; in addition to being capable of playing precise, short exchanges to teammates, he was also known for frequently attempting riskier and more difficult passes and is renowned in particular for his extremely accurate long-range passing, both on the ground or in the air, with either foot, despite being naturally right footed.{{#tag:ref|See<ref name=\"FIFA Confederations Cup Brazil 2013 Player Profile: Andrea Pirlo\"/><ref name=\"A.C. Milan Hall of Fame: Andrea Pirlo\"/><ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo is old, slow, rarely sprints and is just not the player he was \u2013 because he is even better\"/><ref name=\"changing role of deep-lying midfielder\"/><ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo: The football genius\"/><ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo\"/><ref name=\"L\u2019addio di Pirlo e Xavi\"/><ref name=\"magic in their boots\"/><ref name=\"Happy retirement, Andrea Pirlo\"/><ref name=\"Totti is gone, Pirlo becomes the pacesetter for Italy\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/2008-05-29-950280943_x.htm |title=Totti is gone, Pirlo becomes the pacesetter for Italy |newspaper=USA Today |last=Dampf |first=Andrew |date=29 May 2008 |accessdate=15 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/player/_/id/11888/andrea-pirlo?cc=5901 |title=Andrea Pirlo |website=ESPN Soccernet |accessdate=25 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"THOUGHTS ON BALOTELLI, PIRLO\">{{cite web |url=http://www2.tsn.ca/story/?id=399476 |title=DE VOS: THOUGHTS ON BALOTELLI, PIRLO, PRANDELLI AND MORE |publisher=The Sports Network |author1=Jason De Vos |date=28 June 2012 |accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/jun/15/andrea-pirlo-pass-master-england-italy |title=Andrea Pirlo the pass master stars in his own film to hurt England |newspaper=The Guardian |author1=Owen Gibson |date=15 June 2014 |accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"The Pirlo King\"/><ref name=\"Role of Xavi and Pirlo\"/><ref name=\"It's idiotic to man-mark Pirlo\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lastampa.it/2013/11/12/sport/calcio/qui-juve/tanti-esperimenti-e-studio-alla-tv-ecco-il-segreto-delle-magie-di-pirlo-PEIdgJP5g6fNPIe1vxnmlM/pagina.html |title=Tanti esperimenti e studio alla tv Ecco il segreto delle magie di Pirlo |newspaper=La Stampa |language=Italian |date=12 November 2013 |accessdate=31 January 2017}}</ref>|name=\"style3\"|group=\"nb\"}} He is considered to be one of the best passers in the history of the sport,{{#tag:ref|See<ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo Player Profile - ESPN FC\"/><ref name=\"A.C. Milan Hall of Fame: Andrea Pirlo\"/><ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo\"/><ref name=\"Key battles\">{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/19693/7853616/key-battles |title=Key battles |publisher=Sky Sports |date=30 June 2012 |accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1634018-25-most-skilled-passers-in-world-football-history |title=25 Most Skilled Passers in World Football History |website=Bleacher Report |publisher=Turner |author1=Max Towle |date=9 May 2013 |accessdate=10 October 2018}}</ref>|name=\"style4\"|group=\"nb\"}} and is also known for his accurate [[Shooting (association football)|striking]] ability from distance.<ref name=\"Totti is gone, Pirlo becomes the pacesetter for Italy\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tuttojuve.com/altre-notizie/tuttosport-la-juve-e-il-tiro-dalla-distanza-nei-campionati-europei-i-bianconeri-segnano-piu-di-tutti-da-lontano-227308 |title=Tuttosport \u2013 La Juve e il tiro dalla distanza. Nei campionati europei i bianconeri segnano pi\u00f9 di tutti da lontano |website=TUTTOJUVE.com |author1=Antonio Guerra |language=Italian |date=17 March 2015 |accessdate=5 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150705200105/http://www.tuttojuve.com/altre-notizie/tuttosport-la-juve-e-il-tiro-dalla-distanza-nei-campionati-europei-i-bianconeri-segnano-piu-di-tutti-da-lontano-227308 |archivedate=5 July 2015}}</ref> These characteristics allowed him to contribute to his team's offensive play with goals and [[Assist (football)|assists]].<ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo\"/>\n\nPirlo was a free-kick<ref name=\"Totti is gone, Pirlo becomes the pacesetter for Italy\"/><ref name=\"ilgiornale.it\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ilgiornale.it/news/pirlo-e-punizioni-diavolo-ho-imparato-studiando-baggio.html |title=Pirlo e le punizioni da Diavolo: \"Ho imparato studiando Baggio\" |newspaper=il Giornale |language=Italian |accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> and [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty-kick]] specialist.<ref name=\"Totti is gone, Pirlo becomes the pacesetter for Italy\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://sport.repubblica.it/news/sport/calcio-milan-pirlo-entra-per-battere-rigore/131051 |title=Calcio, Milan: Pirlo entra per battere rigore e segna |newspaper=la Repubblica |language=Italian |accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.repubblica.it/speciali/calcio/europei/polonia-ucraina2012/squadre/italia/2012/06/24/news/pirlo_de_rossi-37898939/ |title=De Rossi: \"Pirlo come Totti\" \"Il rigore? L'ho visto carico\" |newspaper=la Repubblica |language=Italian |date=24 June 2012 |accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> Throughout his career, he was regarded as one of the best free-kick takers in the world,<ref name=\"Totti is gone, Pirlo becomes the pacesetter for Italy\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/newscentre/features/news/newsid=1551015/index.html |title=Kings of the free-kick |publisher=FIFA |date=2 December 2011 |accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref> and drew praise from pundits for his versatility, and ability to both score and create chances from dead-ball situations.<ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo-BBC\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.us/story/1117183/ageless-pirlo-continues-to-produce |title=Ageless Pirlo continues to produce |website=ESPN FC |author1=Roger Bennett |date=27 June 2012 |accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/news/alessio-labels-pirlo-worlds-best-free-kick-taker |title=Alessio: Pirlo is world's best free-kick taker |website=FourFourTwo |date=20 March 2014 |accessdate=5 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.football-italia.net/46640/free-kick-master-pirlo |title=Free-kick master Pirlo |website=Football Italia |publisher=Tiro Media |date=19 March 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2015}}</ref> He was extremely effective at [[Curl (football)|curling]] shots accurately on target from close range,<ref name=\"ilgiornale.it\"/> a technique that he perfected by studying Baggio in training sessions during their time at Brescia together;<ref name=\"ilgiornale.it\"/> as a youngster, [[Michel Platini]] was also one of his major influences when taking free kicks.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.repubblica.it/2005/c/sezioni/sport/calcio/nazionale/pirlo/pirlo/pirlo.html |title=Pirlo l'uomo nuovo \"Ho imparato guardando Baggio\" |newspaper=la Repubblica |language=Italian |last=Curr\u00f2 |first=Enrico |date=29 March 2005 |accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> Pirlo was also capable of scoring from long-range free kicks with swerve and power, due to his unique technique, which was inspired by [[Juninho Pernambucano|Juninho's]] \"[[Knuckleball#Association football|knuckle ball]]\" free kicks; this technique was later dubbed the ''maledetta'' (\"accursed\") in the Italian media.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Squadre/Juventus/11-11-2013/juventus-pirlo-ma-che-punizione-hai-tirato-maledetta-che-sfida-fisica-201549826321.shtml |title=Juventus: Pirlo, ma che punizione hai tirato? La maledetta che sfida la fisica |newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |date=11 November 2013 |accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://sport.sky.it/sport/calcio_italiano/2012/01/21/intervista_nicola_ludwig_scienza_nel_pallone_calcio.html |title=Belle e \"maledette\": vi spiego io le parabole di Pirlo |publisher=Sky Sport |language=Italian |date=21 January 2012 |accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> Pirlo has scored the highest number of free kicks in [[Football records in Italy|Serie A]], alongside Sini\u0161a Mihajlovi\u0107.<ref name=\"Pirlo raggiunge Mihajlovic a quota 28\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/10/italy/2013/10/31/4372773/pirlo-surpasses-del-piero-in-serie-a-free-kick-ranking |title=Pirlo surpasses Del Piero in Serie A Free Kick Ranking |website=Goal.com |date=31 October 2013 |accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Nicknames===\nFellow players on the Italian national team nicknamed Pirlo ''l'architetto'' (\"the Architect\"), because of the way in which he built plays, and set up goal-scoring opportunities with long, lobbed through passes.{{#tag:ref|See<ref name=\"The Pirlo King\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/the-pirlo-king-7878712.html |title=The Pirlo King |newspaper=The Independent |author1=Miguel Delaney |date=23 June 2012 |accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Role of Xavi and Pirlo\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sport.net/the-role-of-xavi-and-pirlo_360759 |title=The Role of Xavi and Pirlo |publisher=Sport.net |author1=Sam Cooper |date=26 May 2015 |accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"It's idiotic to man-mark Pirlo\">{{cite news |author1=Giuseppe Muro |title=Joachim Low: It's idiotic to man-mark Pirlo |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/joachim-low-its-idiotic-to-man-mark-pirlo-7892942.html |newspaper=London Evening Standard |accessdate=30 January 2017 |date=27 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Pirlo: I have all I need here\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=986881.html |title=Pirlo: I have all I need here |publisher=FIFA |accessdate=15 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nycfc.com/post/2016/08/19/pirlos-corner-taking-yankees-game |title=Pirlo's Corner: Taking in a Yankees Game |publisher=New York City FC |date=19 August 2016 |accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref>|name=\"style5\"|group=\"nb\"}} In later seasons, Juventus fans also dubbed him ''il professore'' (\"the professor\"),<ref name=\"Soccer Megastar Roams Freely\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/06/t-magazine/soccer-andrea-pirlo-new-york-city-fc.html |title=On New York's Bustling Streets, a Soccer Megastar Roams Freely |newspaper=The New York Times |author1=Jeff Oloizia |date=29 February 2016 |accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref> ''Maestro'',<ref name=\"Thanks for everything, Maestro\"/> and ''Mozart'',<ref name=\"Soccer Megastar Roams Freely\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spaziojuve.it/2012/grazie-campioni-andrea-mozart-pirlo/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528074501/http://www.spaziojuve.it/2012/grazie-campioni-andrea-mozart-pirlo/ |url-status=dead |archivedate=28 May 2012 |title=Grazie Campioni \u2013 Andrea \"Mozart\" Pirlo |website=SpazioJuve.it |date=26 May 2012 |accessdate=9 March 2013}}</ref> as a reference to the [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Austrian composer]]'s prodigious ability. Pirlo was also frequently compared to fellow former Milan and Italy playmaker Albertini early in his Milan career,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rivistastudio.com/articoli/due-o-tre-cose-su-demetrio-albertini-il-vecchio-pirlo/ |title=Due o tre cose su Demetrio Albertini, il vecchio Pirlo |language=Italian |accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref> due to their similar characteristics and style of play.<ref name=\"forzaitalianfootball.com\">{{cite web |url=http://forzaitalianfootball.com/2013/06/legends-of-calcio-demetrio-albertini/ |title=Legend of Calcio: Demetrio Albertini |accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> Pirlo was often thought to be Albertini's heir for Milan and the national team;<ref name=\"forzaitalianfootball.com\"/> he inherited his nickname ''the metronome'' whilst playing at Milan, for the way in which he influenced games by controlling the tempo of his team's play through his direct, precise, and efficient passing game in midfield, as well as his ability to make himself available to teammates to receive and subsequently distribute the ball.{{#tag:ref|See<ref name=\"A.C. Milan Hall of Fame: Andrea Pirlo\"/><ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo Topics Page\"/><ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo: The Metronome\"/><ref name=\"Happy retirement, Andrea Pirlo\"/><ref name=\"Totti is gone, Pirlo becomes the pacesetter for Italy\"/><ref name=\"THOUGHTS ON BALOTELLI, PIRLO\"/><ref name=\"It's idiotic to man-mark Pirlo\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sport/metronome-isn-t-marking-time-1.387349 |title=Metronome isn't marking time |newspaper=The Irish Times |author1=Paddy Agnew Euroscene |date=28 October 2003 |accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo's peerless pass-mastery\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2012/may/14/andrea-pirlo-juventus-notts-county |title=Andrea Pirlo's peerless pass-mastery could lift even the Trentside fog |newspaper=The Guardian |author1=Richard Williams |date=14 May 2012 |accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref>|name=\"style6\"|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n==After football==\nIn August 2019, Pirlo enrolled in the [[UEFA Pro Licence]] courses at [[Centro Tecnico Federale di Coverciano|Coverciano]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football-italia.net/143280/pirlo-toni-begin-pro-courses |title=Pirlo & Toni begin Pro courses |publisher=Football Italia |date=23 August 2019 |accessdate=30 October 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPirlo is one of two children along with his brother Ivan.<ref name=\"making\"/> Pirlo and his wife Deborah Roversi married in 2001 and have two children: son Niccol\u00f2 (born 2003) and daughter Angela (born 2006).<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/2009/06/24/andrea-pirlo-profile-10-things-you-need-to-know-about-the-chelsea-target-115875-21468066 |title=Andrea Pirlo profile: 10 Things you need to know about the Chelsea target |newspaper=Daily Mirror |author1=Jake Lofdahl |author2=Oliver Pickup |date=24 June 2009 |accessdate=4 October 2010}}</ref> In 2014, Pirlo and Roversi divorced after thirteen years of marriage, following Pirlo's affair with Valentina Baldini, a woman he met at his golf club.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/worldcup2014/article-2654261/Andrea-Pirlo-seeks-help-priest-fears-love-life-affect-football.html |title=Andrea Pirlo seeks help from priest over fears his love life will affect his football |newspaper=Daily Mail |date=10 June 2014 |accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nPirlo's father founded a metal trading company in Brescia in 1982 called Elg Steel. Pirlo himself retains a stake in the family business.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://espresso.repubblica.it/dettaglio/la-vera-storia-di-pirlo-lo-zingaro/2180635 |title=La vera storia di Pirlo lo 'zingaro' \u2013 l'Espresso |newspaper=la Repubblica |author=di Gianfrancesco Turano |language=Italian |date=14 May 2012 |accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref> With regard to his wealth from his family business and footballing career, Pirlo stated in an interview with Italian ''Vanity Fair'' magazine that he never talks about money.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.andreapirlo.net/site/2012/05/28/dedicato-a-chi-mi-chiama-zingaro/ |title=Dedicato a chi mi chiama \"zingaro\" |website=AndreaPirlo.net |date=28 May 2012 |accessdate=20 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105140255/http://www.andreapirlo.net/site/2012/05/28/dedicato-a-chi-mi-chiama-zingaro |archivedate=5 November 2014}}</ref> Pirlo is known for being a wine connoisseur and he also runs his own vineyard in Italy, which produces around 15\u201320,000 bottles a year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espnfc.com/blog/_/name/espnfcunited/id/5381?cc=5901 |title=As Goetze heads to Bayern, Pirlo describes Guardiola's allure |website=ESPN FC |date=30 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Pirlo wrote an autobiography, with Alessandro Alciato, titled ''Penso Quindi Gioco'' (''I Think Therefore I Play'').<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.football-italia.net/33289/pirlo-milan-juve-and-conte |title=Pirlo: 'Milan, Juve and Conte' |website=Football Italia |publisher=Tiro Media |date=20 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/pirlo-liverpool-drank-our-blood-they-mentally-destroyed-us-30185726.html |title=Pirlo: 'Liverpool drank our blood... they mentally destroyed us' |newspaper=Irish Independent |date=15 April 2014 |accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> On 1 September 2014, Pirlo, along with many current and former footballing stars, took part in the \"Match for Peace\", which was played at the Stadio Olimpico, in Rome, with the proceeds being donated entirely to charity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.matchforpeace.org/?lang=en |title=Interreligious Match for Peace: 1/9/2014 |website=.matchforpeace.org |accessdate=1 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903092935/http://www.matchforpeace.org/?lang=en |archivedate=3 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/01-09-2014/calcio-partita-pace-baggio-dinho-eto-o-campo-il-papa-90323482706.shtml?rlabs=1 |title=Il Papa a Maradona: \"Ti aspettavo\". Diego show con Baggio, poi si infuria: \"Icardi non doveva giocare\" |newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |date=1 September 2014 |accessdate=1 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, it was reported that Pirlo's jersey was the highest-selling MLS shirt in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/12096/10502891/new-york-city-fcs-andrea-pirlo-tops-mls-shirt-sales-for-2016 |title=New York City FC's Andrea Pirlo tops MLS shirt sales for 2016 |publisher=Sky Sports |date=15 July 2016 |accessdate=18 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 July 2017, Pirlo's partner, Valentina Baldini, gave birth to their twins named Leonardo and Tommaso.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.football-italia.net/107443/pirlo-welcomes-twins-and-italy-return |title=Pirlo welcomes twins and Italy return |website=Football Italia |publisher=Tiro Media |date=9 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/09-08-2017/pirlo-papa-mamma-valentina-annuncia-gemelli-blog-210884170520.shtml |title=Pirlo di nuovo pap\u00e0: mamma Valentina nel suo blog annuncia i due gemelli |newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |date=9 August 2017 |accessdate=9 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nPirlo features in [[EA Sports]]' [[FIFA (video game series)|football video game]] ''[[FIFA 20]]'' as one of the new [[FIFA 20#Ultimate Team|Ultimate Team Icons]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ea.com/games/fifa/fifa-20/ultimate-team/fut-icons |title=FIFA 20 FUT Icons |publisher=EA.com |accessdate=19 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n:Source:<ref name=\"Italy - A. Pirlo - Profile - Soccerway\"/><ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo Player Profile - ESPN FC\"/><ref name=\"Andrea Pirlo - MLS\"/><ref name=\"tuttocalciatori\">{{cite web |url=https://www.tuttocalciatori.net/Pirlo_Andrea |title=Andrea Pirlo |website=TuttoCalciatori.Net |language=Italian |accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"nycfc profile\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nycfc.com/players/36/andrea-pirlo |title=Andrea Pirlo |publisher=New York City FC |accessdate=27 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160429233044/http://www.nycfc.com/players/36/andrea-pirlo |archivedate=29 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Season\n! colspan=\"3\"| League\n! colspan=\"2\"| Cup<ref group=\"nb\">Includes [[Coppa Italia]] and [[U.S. Open Cup]]</ref>\n! colspan=\"2\"| Continental<ref group=\"nb\">Includes [[UEFA Champions League]], [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup / UEFA Europa League]] and [[UEFA Super Cup]]</ref>\n! colspan=\"2\"| Other<ref group=\"nb\">Includes [[Supercoppa Italiana]], [[Intercontinental Cup (football)|Intercontinental Cup]], [[FIFA Club World Cup]] and [[MLS Cup Playoffs]]</ref>\n! colspan=\"2\"| Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\"|[[Brescia Calcio|Brescia]]||[[1994\u201395 Brescia Calcio season|1994\u201395]]||rowspan=\"1\"|[[Serie A]]\n|1||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||1||0\n|-\n|[[1995\u201396 Serie B|1995\u201396]]||rowspan=\"2\"|[[Seri